  title:"The Interview", emoji:"🎙️", genre:"School",
  wordCount:213, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Interviewing the oldest person in the village — with one unexpected question.",
  paragraphs:[
    "As part of our local history project, each pupil in my class was assigned an older person from the village to interview. I was given Mr. Hennessy, who was eighty-three years old and had lived in the same house since 1967. My teacher, Miss Bello, said he remembered when the fields behind the high street were still farmland.",
    "I prepared six questions and wrote them on index cards. On a Saturday morning in February, Mum walked me to his house and waited outside while I knocked on the door.",
    "Mr. Hennessy was short and moved slowly, but his eyes were sharp. He made me a glass of squash and sat in an armchair. I asked my questions one by one. He answered carefully, correcting himself when he thought he had the year wrong. He talked about the old post office, the cinema that closed in 1981, and the time the river flooded the lower street.",
    "Towards the end, he put down his glass and asked me a question. 'What do you think this village will look like when you are eighty-three?' I had not prepared for that. I thought for a long moment. Then I said I hoped it would still have people who remembered things. He was quiet for a moment and then said, 'That is a very good answer.'"
  ],
