  blurb:"Making a full meal for the whole family — completely alone — for the first time.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My parents had been dropping hints for weeks that it would be good for me to cook a proper dinner. My older sister had started cooking one meal a week at my age. I had been watching and learning for months, so one Sunday evening I said I would do it.",
    "I chose pasta with a tomato sauce — not from a jar, a real sauce. Dad found me a recipe and then very deliberately went and sat in the other room. I appreciated that. Some people help by hovering, which is not actually help.",
    "I chopped an onion, which made my eyes water, and fried it in olive oil until it was soft. I added tinned tomatoes, a pinch of salt, some dried basil, and a small spoonful of sugar — the recipe said the sugar balanced the acidity of the tomatoes. I let it simmer for twenty minutes while the pasta cooked.",
    "I served it with grated cheese on top and a side of garlic bread that I made by spreading butter and garlic powder on sliced bread and putting it under the grill. When everyone sat down, the kitchen smelled like something from an actual restaurant. Dad tried the sauce and said, 'You can make this every week.' Mum said that was exactly what she had been planning."
  ],
