  wordCount:261, readMins:3,
  blurb:"The last assembly of primary school — and the particular feeling of an ending.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The final assembly of Year Six was on the last Thursday of July. Every child in the school came — five hundred and forty of us — into the hall. The Year Sixes sat at the front, which felt strange, because for the previous six years we had always sat at the back.",
    "Mr. Kaur, the headteacher, gave a speech. He was not the sort of person who spoke in clichés, and he did not that day either. He talked about the specific things he had noticed about our year group — our science fair, the mural we had painted in the corridor, the time eight of us had stayed after school for three weeks to fix the school garden after the flooding.",
    "He called our names one by one, and each person walked up to receive a small card with a message written inside. When he called mine, I walked to the front and he shook my hand and said something quietly that was just for me. I do not think it was planned — it felt too specific to have been.",
    "Afterwards, we had lunch in the playground. People were signing each other's shirts and taking photographs. I stood near the edge with my friend Jess and we did not take any photographs. We had talked about this — we both agreed that photographs of moments like this never quite captured what the moment felt like. We stayed for the whole afternoon.",
    "I walked home a different way that evening. I am not sure why — I think I needed the extra few minutes to let the day settle before I arrived anywhere."
  ],
