STORIES[3][3].push({
  id:"l3.4s5", levelId:3, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Map on the Wall", emoji:"🗺️", genre:"History / Home",
  wordCount:311, readMins:3,
  blurb:"A large old map in the hallway — and all the questions it raises about the past.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The map has been in our hallway since before I was born. It is a large-scale ordnance survey map from 1953, framed behind glass, showing the area within roughly eight kilometres of our house. My parents bought it at a car boot sale in the 1990s because they liked the detail. It is still there, slightly faded but readable.",
    "I have walked past it my whole life without looking at it properly. Then, one afternoon in the Easter holidays, I stopped. I found our road — it is there, already named, running between two other streets that still exist. But the field behind the primary school is marked as 'nursery gardens', and the supermarket was a factory called Perkins & Sons (Engineers). The industrial estate is missing entirely; it was built in the 1970s.",
    "What interested me most was a footpath marked in dashes running diagonally across what is now the back of the trading estate. I asked my grandmother if she remembered it. She said she used it as a child to get to school — it cut ten minutes off the walk, and everybody used it. It was closed when the estate was built and nobody, as far as she knew, had ever objected formally.",
    "I checked the definitive footpath map online. The path is listed as a public right of way. It has never been legally extinguished. The trading estate was built across it without proper diversion orders.",
    "I have not done anything with this information yet. My grandmother says it probably does not matter after seventy years. But the dashes are still on the map, and every time I pass it I wonder."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "ordnance survey":{def:"A national mapping organisation that creates detailed maps of Britain.",pos:"noun"},
    "large-scale":{def:"Showing a small area in great detail.",pos:"adjective"},
    "industrial estate":{def:"An area of land with factories and warehouses.",pos:"noun"},
    "trading estate":{def:"An area with commercial businesses and warehouses.",pos:"noun"},
    "right of way":{def:"A legal right to walk or travel along a particular path.",pos:"noun"},
    "extinguished":{def:"Here: legally ended or removed.",pos:"verb"},
    "diversion order":{def:"An official document that legally moves a footpath to a new route.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the map of?",options:["The whole of Britain","A city centre","The area within about 8 kilometres of the narrator's house","A historical town that no longer exists"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A large-scale ordnance survey map... showing the area within roughly eight kilometres of our house.'"},
    {question:"What is the supermarket built on, according to the 1953 map?",options:["Nursery gardens","A car park","A factory called Perkins & Sons","An open field"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The supermarket was a factory called Perkins & Sons (Engineers).'"},
    {question:"Why had people used the old diagonal footpath?",options:["It led to a park","It avoided the traffic","It cut ten minutes off the walk to school","It was the only paved path"],correct:2,
     feedback:"The grandmother said 'it cut ten minutes off the walk, and everybody used it.'"},
    {question:"What did the narrator find out about the footpath legally?",options:["It was properly closed in the 1970s","It was never a public right of way","It was legally extinguished in 1973","It was still a public right of way and had never been properly closed"],correct:3,
     feedback:"'The path is listed as a public right of way. It has never been legally extinguished.'"}
  ]
});

