STORIES[3][5].push({
  id:"l3.6s4", levelId:3, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Ceramics Room", emoji:"🏺", genre:"Art / School",
  wordCount:339, readMins:3,
  blurb:"An after-school ceramics club — and the peculiar pleasure of making something with your hands.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The ceramics room at school is at the far end of the art block, past the print studio. It has a kiln in the corner, a large table covered in canvas, and a smell that I now associate entirely with making things — clay dust, faint chemical traces from the glazes, and something earthy underneath that does not go away. I started going on Thursdays in October.",
    "I had no experience with clay. The first session I made something that was supposed to be a bowl and turned out to be more of a collapsed oval. Miss Parkes, who runs the club, said collapsing was informative and that I should feel the clay again and understand where the pressure had gone wrong. She did not correct it for me.",
    "Clay work is slower than I expected. Hand-building a small pot takes two sessions minimum: one to build the form and let it dry to leather-hard, then another to smooth the surface and add any texture before it goes into the bisque firing. After that, glazing, then the glaze firing. The whole process from clay to finished object takes between two and four weeks. You make several things at once because waiting is part of it.",
    "The thing I like most is the concentration it requires. In ceramics, you cannot think about something else. The clay responds to inattention immediately — the wall thins on one side, the base lifts, the form loses its line. You have to be there, in the room, paying attention with your hands. I find that a relief.",
    "I have made eleven pots. Four are at home, three went to relatives at Christmas, one cracked in the bisque firing and was a good lesson, and three are still in progress. Miss Parkes says I have a feel for it. I think she says this to everyone, but I also think it might be true."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "kiln":{def:"A large oven used to harden clay objects at very high temperatures.",pos:"noun"},
    "glaze":{def:"A liquid coating applied to ceramics before firing to give colour or a shiny finish.",pos:"noun"},
    "leather-hard":{def:"The stage when clay has dried enough to hold its shape but is still slightly flexible.",pos:"adjective"},
    "bisque firing":{def:"The first firing of clay, which hardens it before glazing.",pos:"noun"},
    "hand-building":{def:"Shaping clay using the hands rather than a wheel.",pos:"noun"},
    "inattention":{def:"Lack of care or concentration.",pos:"noun"},
    "informative":{def:"Providing useful information or insight.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What happened to the narrator's first bowl?",options:["It cracked in the kiln","It turned out too small","It collapsed into a shape that was more of an oval","Miss Parkes used it as an example of good work"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Something that was supposed to be a bowl and turned out to be more of a collapsed oval.'"},
    {question:"Why does ceramics take two to four weeks from clay to finished object?",options:["The kiln is only on once a month","Each stage requires drying, firing, and glazing time","Miss Parkes limits how many sessions you can use","The clay must be ordered specially"],correct:1,
     feedback:"Building, drying to leather-hard, bisque firing, glazing, then glaze firing all take time."},
    {question:"What does the narrator say they find a relief about ceramics?",options:["It is quiet in the room","The results are always visible","It requires full concentration, leaving no room for other thoughts","You can listen to music while working"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'You have to be there, in the room, paying attention with your hands. I find that a relief.'"},
    {question:"How many of the eleven pots did the narrator give to relatives at Christmas?",options:["Two","Three","Four","Five"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Three went to relatives at Christmas.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][5].push({
  id:"l3.6s5", levelId:3, subLevel:5,
  title:"Storm Day", emoji:"⛈️", genre:"Nature / Everyday Life",
  wordCount:342, readMins:3,
  blurb:"A day when school closes early because of a storm — and what happens with the unexpected free time.",
  paragraphs:[
    "School sent a message at half past twelve to say that due to the forecast, the afternoon sessions were cancelled and all pupils should leave by one. There was a named storm arriving — Storms had been given names since the 2010s, which I found slightly strange since it made them feel planned. This one was Elin.",
    "The walk home took twice as long as usual. By two o'clock, the wind was already significant and there were leaves and small bits of branches on the pavements. I found a section of plastic guttering in the road that had blown off a house further up the street. I moved it to the pavement so cars could pass.",
    "At home, my mother had already moved the wheelie bins into the side passage and brought the outdoor furniture in. The kitchen felt smaller with the garden chair leaning against the cupboard. She made soup, which she does not usually do on weekdays, and we ate it at three in the afternoon listening to the wind increase.",
    "The storm reached its peak at around eight in the evening. We lost power for twenty minutes, then it came back. A large section of fence between our garden and the Hargreaves' next door came down completely, which we discovered the next morning. A rowan tree at the end of the road lost a significant branch, which blocked the pavement and had to be cut through by the council the following day.",
    "School was open normally on Thursday. On the way in, the evidence of Elin was everywhere — piles of leaf debris along the gutters, a boarded-up window on the high street, sections of scaffolding that had shifted on the building site near the station. By Friday, most of it had been cleared. You would not have known, unless you had been there."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "forecast":{def:"A prediction of future weather conditions.",pos:"noun"},
    "significant":{def:"Here: strong enough to be noticeable and important.",pos:"adjective"},
    "guttering":{def:"The channels fixed to the edge of a roof to carry rainwater away.",pos:"noun"},
    "rowan":{def:"A type of tree with white flowers and red berries, common in Britain.",pos:"noun"},
    "scaffolding":{def:"A temporary metal framework built around a building for workers.",pos:"noun"},
    "debris":{def:"Scattered pieces of rubbish or broken material.",pos:"noun"},
    "peak":{def:"The highest or most intense point.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why was school cancelled for the afternoon?",options:["A heating fault","Heavy snowfall","A named storm was forecast","A fire alarm test"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Due to the forecast, the afternoon sessions were cancelled' — Storm Elin was arriving."},
    {question:"What did the narrator do with the plastic guttering in the road?",options:["Reported it to the council","Left it where it was","Moved it to the pavement so cars could pass","Took it home"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I moved it to the pavement so cars could pass.'"},
    {question:"What damage did the narrator discover the morning after the storm?",options:["A roof tile had fallen","The garden shed had collapsed","A section of fence between the gardens had come down","A tree had fallen across the driveway"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A large section of fence between our garden and the Hargreaves' next door came down completely.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator say about the following Friday?",options:["More storm damage was found","The rowan tree still blocked the pavement","Most of the evidence had been cleared","School was closed again"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'By Friday, most of it had been cleared. You would not have known, unless you had been there.'"}
  ]
});

