STORIES[3][6].push({
  id:"l3.7s1", levelId:3, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Observatory", emoji:"🔭", genre:"Science / Personal",
  wordCount:354, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A school trip to an observatory — and what it means to understand how far away something is.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The observatory is on a hill outside the town, about twenty minutes by minibus. The school takes a group every year in March, when there is the best chance of clear skies and the nights are not yet as short as summer. This year the sky was almost entirely clear, which the astronomer who met us said was unusual for March in this part of the country.",
    "She was called Dr Whitfield and she wore a red torch around her neck. She explained at the start that white light destroyed night vision but red light did not, which was why the observatory used red lighting throughout and why we should avoid using our phones. She said our eyes needed about twenty minutes to fully adjust to the dark.",
    "The main telescope was larger than I expected — the tube alone was longer than I am tall. When it was your turn, you climbed a small ladder and looked through the eyepiece, and Dr Whitfield told you what you were seeing. I looked at Saturn. The rings are real. You know this already, from pictures, but seeing them through an actual eyepiece is different — they are solid, three-dimensional, and very clearly not part of the planet itself. They look almost too neat to be natural.",
    "Dr Whitfield said something I have thought about since. She said that the light from Saturn takes approximately 1.3 hours to reach us, depending on where Saturn is in its orbit. So the Saturn I saw was as it was 1.3 hours earlier. Then she said the light from the nearest star other than the Sun takes 4.2 years to reach us. I looked at a star through the telescope afterwards and thought: this is the past.",
    "On the minibus back, most people talked about Saturn. A few people were asleep. I looked out of the window at the orange glow of the town and thought about light travelling across distances I could not hold in my head, and arriving at an eyepiece, and being seen."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "observatory":{def:"A building equipped with telescopes for observing the sky.",pos:"noun"},
    "night vision":{def:"The ability to see in low light conditions.",pos:"noun"},
    "eyepiece":{def:"The lens of a telescope or microscope that you look through.",pos:"noun"},
    "three-dimensional":{def:"Having height, width, and depth; not flat.",pos:"adjective"},
    "orbit":{def:"The path of a planet or object around a star or planet.",pos:"noun"},
    "astronomer":{def:"A scientist who studies stars, planets, and space.",pos:"noun"},
    "adjust":{def:"To change slightly in order to fit a new situation.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did the observatory use red lighting?",options:["It used less energy","It made the equipment easier to see","Red light did not destroy night vision as white light did","It was an astronomy tradition"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'White light destroyed night vision but red light did not.'"},
    {question:"What did the narrator look at through the main telescope?",options:["The Moon","Jupiter","Saturn","A distant galaxy"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I looked at Saturn. The rings are real.'"},
    {question:"What fact about Saturn's light did Dr Whitfield share?",options:["It takes 4.2 years to reach Earth","It takes 1.3 hours to reach Earth","It travels faster than light from other stars","It appears different from what it really looks like"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The light from Saturn takes approximately 1.3 hours to reach us.'"},
    {question:"What thought occurred to the narrator when looking at a distant star afterwards?",options:["The star might not be real","The telescope was not powerful enough","This is the past — they were seeing old light","Stars look very different up close"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I looked at a star through the telescope afterwards and thought: this is the past.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][6].push({
  id:"l3.7s2", levelId:3, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Departure Board", emoji:"🚂", genre:"Travel / Everyday Life",
  wordCount:352, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Waiting in a train station for a delayed train — and what the waiting shows you.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My train was delayed by forty-three minutes, which the departure board announced at first as 'Expected: 14:28' and then, at 14:20, changed to 'Delayed'. The word 'Delayed' with no further time given is worse than a specific number. A specific number can be planned around. 'Delayed' just means: we are not telling you.",
    "I found a seat on the concourse facing the board. The concourse at this station is a Victorian building with a long glass roof, and in the afternoon light the dust in the air was visible as a slow drift. People were everywhere — business travellers checking phones, a family distributing sandwiches from a paper bag, a man in a high-visibility jacket reading a novel with the concentration of someone who does this every day.",
    "Every few minutes the board updated and there was a quiet collective turning of heads. If the update was good news — a platform confirmed, a delay reduced — a kind of low relief passed through the concourse, not expressed in any particular way but noticeable. If it was bad news, the same people turned back to their phones or their sandwiches without visible reaction.",
    "I noticed a woman sitting opposite who was watching the same thing I was. We had been there for about twenty minutes when she caught my eye and said: 'Northern service?' I said it was. She said she had been delayed on this concourse four times in the last month. She said it was her commute. She said she had stopped being annoyed about it and started thinking of it as reading time. She held up a book she had finished three weeks earlier than she would have without the delays.",
    "My train arrived at 14:52, thirteen minutes later than the second estimate. I had read thirty pages of my own book and watched a toddler fall asleep in his pushchair with a half-eaten biscuit in his hand. It was not a wasted afternoon. Waiting rarely is, if you stop fighting it."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "concourse":{def:"The large central hall of a railway station.",pos:"noun"},
    "departure board":{def:"A screen or board showing train or flight departure times.",pos:"noun"},
    "Victorian":{def:"From the period of Queen Victoria's reign (1837–1901), often used to describe architecture.",pos:"adjective"},
    "high-visibility jacket":{def:"A bright, fluorescent jacket worn for safety so workers can be seen easily.",pos:"noun"},
    "commute":{def:"A regular journey between home and work.",pos:"noun"},
    "collective":{def:"Shared by all members of a group.",pos:"adjective"},
    "toddler":{def:"A young child who has just learnt to walk.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did the narrator say 'Delayed' with no time was worse than a specific number?",options:["It suggested the train was cancelled","A specific number could be planned around","It meant the delay would be very long","No one would help with the question"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A specific number can be planned around. \"Delayed\" just means: we are not telling you.'"},
    {question:"What was the woman opposite doing on the concourse four times a month?",options:["Waiting for a friend","Watching trains for a hobby","It was her commute and she was often delayed","She was a station employee"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She said it was her commute. She said she had been delayed on this concourse four times in the last month.'"},
    {question:"How had the woman changed her attitude to delays?",options:["She always complained to the rail company","She switched to a different route","She stopped being annoyed and started thinking of it as reading time","She travelled at different times"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had stopped being annoyed about it and started thinking of it as reading time.'"},
    {question:"What was the toddler doing when the narrator's train finally arrived?",options:["Running around the concourse","Crying","Asleep in his pushchair with a half-eaten biscuit","Watching the departure board"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A toddler fell asleep in his pushchair with a half-eaten biscuit in his hand.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][6].push({
  id:"l3.7s3", levelId:3, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Repair Café", emoji:"🔧", genre:"Community",
  wordCount:356, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A community event where people bring broken things to be fixed — and what that teaches about objects.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The Repair Café runs on the first Saturday of every month in the church hall. People bring broken things — toasters, lamps, torn clothing, a bicycle with a stuck gear, a radio from the 1970s — and volunteers with different skills try to fix them. There is tea and cake. The fixing is free. If the object cannot be fixed, it cannot be fixed, but they always try.",
    "I went in November to see if someone could fix a lamp my grandmother gave me. The brass stand had come away from the base and I had no idea what adhesive would hold metal to ceramic without cracking it under heat. The man who looked at it — a retired engineer who came every month, apparently — said the problem was that the original adhesive had been applied incorrectly decades ago and had transferred the stress to the wrong part of the joint. He reattached it with a two-part epoxy, clamped it, and told me to leave it for twenty-four hours.",
    "While waiting, I watched the other tables. A young woman in her twenties was fixing a sewing machine with a broken tension wheel. She had disassembled part of the bobbin mechanism on a cloth laid flat on the table and was working methodically through the parts. At the clothing table, a woman with white hair was sewing a tear in a coat lining with stitches so small I could barely see them.",
    "A man came in with a blender that had stopped working. The electronics volunteer opened it and found that a single capacitor had failed — a component about the size of a drawing pin. The replacement cost roughly fifteen pence. The blender had been about to be thrown away.",
    "I collected my lamp the following Saturday. The repair was invisible. The lamp is on my desk now. The engineer was not there that week, but someone told me his name was Harold and he had been coming for six years. I do not know what Harold gets out of it, but I have some ideas."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "adhesive":{def:"A substance used for sticking things together.",pos:"noun"},
    "ceramic":{def:"Made from clay that has been heated to harden it.",pos:"adjective"},
    "epoxy":{def:"A very strong type of two-part adhesive.",pos:"noun"},
    "tension wheel":{def:"A part in a sewing machine that controls the tightness of the thread.",pos:"noun"},
    "bobbin":{def:"A small spool that holds thread in a sewing machine.",pos:"noun"},
    "capacitor":{def:"A small electronic component that stores electrical charge.",pos:"noun"},
    "methodically":{def:"In a careful, systematic, and ordered way.",pos:"adverb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was wrong with the lamp the narrator brought?",options:["The bulb had blown","The wiring was faulty","The brass stand had come away from the base","The switch was broken"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The brass stand had come away from the base.'"},
    {question:"What did the engineer say had caused the original failure?",options:["The wrong type of adhesive had been used","The adhesive had been applied incorrectly and transferred stress to the wrong joint","The ceramic had cracked from heat","The stand was the wrong size for the base"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The original adhesive had been applied incorrectly... and had transferred the stress to the wrong part of the joint.'"},
    {question:"What had caused the blender to stop working?",options:["A broken blade","A faulty motor","A burnt-out fuse","A single failed capacitor"],correct:3,
     feedback:"'The electronics volunteer opened it and found that a single capacitor had failed.'"},
    {question:"How much did the replacement part for the blender cost?",options:["About fifteen pence","About five pounds","About fifty pence","Nothing — it was donated"],correct:0,
     feedback:"'The replacement cost roughly fifteen pence.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][6].push({
  id:"l3.7s4", levelId:3, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Last Allotment Plot", emoji:"🌱", genre:"Nature / Community",
  wordCount:358, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Taking on an overgrown allotment plot — and what ten years of neglect looks like.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Plot 14 had been unworked for nine or ten years, the site manager said, which meant it had been growing whatever it chose. The previous tenant had apparently stopped coming one spring and not renewed the lease, and nobody had taken it on since because it looked so daunting. When we arrived, it was head-height brambles at the back, a collapsed cold frame, and couch grass everywhere.",
    "My mother had joined the waiting list three years earlier. She is a gardener who had been working in our small back garden and wanted more space. She said we would sort it together, which I took to mean a manageable family project. What it meant in practice was three weekends of cutting and digging before we reached the soil.",
    "The couch grass was the worst. It sends roots horizontally through the soil and any piece left in the ground will regrow. You cannot rotavate couch grass because you just create more pieces. You have to dig it by hand, fork it loose, and remove every section of root you can find. My father found this satisfying in a way I did not fully share but learned to understand.",
    "Under the brambles at the back of the plot was a fruit cage — metal posts still standing, the netting long gone, but four gooseberry bushes inside it still alive and producing. There was also a rhubarb crown so old and established that it had grown through and around the base of one of the posts. My mother said a rhubarb crown that old was worth more than anything we could plant.",
    "By the following March, we had one cleared raised bed, one section of path, and a working compost bay. The brambles were gone. The couch grass was mostly gone. The gooseberry bushes had been pruned back and were already showing new growth. We harvested the rhubarb in April. Nine years of neglect, and it was the best rhubarb any of us had ever tasted."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "brambles":{def:"Wild prickly shrubs that produce blackberries.",pos:"noun"},
    "cold frame":{def:"A low, unheated structure with a transparent roof, used to protect young plants.",pos:"noun"},
    "couch grass":{def:"A vigorous weed that spreads through horizontal roots.",pos:"noun"},
    "rotavate":{def:"To break up soil using a machine with rotating blades.",pos:"verb"},
    "fruit cage":{def:"A frame covered in netting to protect fruit bushes from birds.",pos:"noun"},
    "rhubarb crown":{def:"The main root and growing point of a rhubarb plant.",pos:"noun"},
    "compost bay":{def:"A section or container for storing and making compost.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why had no one taken on Plot 14 for nine or ten years?",options:["The rent was too high","It was in the wrong part of the site","It looked too daunting because it was overgrown","The soil was too poor"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Nobody had taken it on since because it looked so daunting.'"},
    {question:"Why could you not rotavate couch grass?",options:["The machine could not cut through the roots","Rotavating would damage the soil structure","You just create more pieces that each regrow","The roots were too deep for the machine"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'You cannot rotavate couch grass because you just create more pieces.'"},
    {question:"What did the narrator's mother say about the old rhubarb crown?",options:["It needed to be removed to plant vegetables","It was worth more than anything they could plant","They should try to sell it","It was too old to produce good rhubarb"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A rhubarb crown that old was worth more than anything we could plant.'"},
    {question:"How did the rhubarb taste when they finally harvested it?",options:["Too bitter after years without care","Reasonable but needed sweetening","The best rhubarb any of them had ever tasted","They were unsure — it was their first time eating rhubarb"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Nine years of neglect, and it was the best rhubarb any of us had ever tasted.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][6].push({
  id:"l3.7s5", levelId:3, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Lighthouse Keeper's Logbook", emoji:"🏮", genre:"History",
  wordCount:355, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A family visits a lighthouse museum and finds a logbook full of carefully recorded ordinary days.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The lighthouse was automated in 1987, which means nobody has lived in it since. The attendant at the museum told us this before we went up — she said it was important context, because otherwise visitors expected something dramatic at the top and were sometimes disappointed when it was just a light. The light itself is still operational, she said. Trinity House still uses it. It just does not need a person to run it.",
    "On the way down, there was a display case with two logbooks from the 1930s. Lighthouse keepers were required to write an entry every day, regardless of whether anything happened. Most entries were a few lines: weather conditions, sea state, visibility in nautical miles, shipping observed, any maintenance done. The handwriting changed slightly over the years as the shifts rotated between two or three keepers.",
    "What struck me was an entry from 14 November 1934. The sea state was recorded as force 9, which is severe — the kind of conditions where waves can be nine metres high. The entry read: 'Heavy gale from SW. High confused sea. Lantern maintained throughout. Night watch completed without incident.' Four lines. Then the next day: 'Conditions easing. SW veering W. Cleaned glass.' The storm, which must have been terrifying, was recorded in the same register as cleaning the glass.",
    "I thought about this on the drive home. The keepers recorded everything equally — the extreme and the routine — because that was the job. Their personal feelings about a force 9 gale were not relevant to the logbook. The logbook was for ships that might use the light. It was not for them.",
    "There is something I find quite moving about that. Doing something important, carefully, without being asked to perform the emotion of it."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "automated":{def:"Changed to operate by machines without human control.",pos:"verb"},
    "Trinity House":{def:"The authority responsible for lighthouses and navigation aids around England and Wales.",pos:"noun"},
    "nautical miles":{def:"Units of distance used at sea (approximately 1.85 km each).",pos:"noun"},
    "force 9":{def:"A reading on the Beaufort scale indicating a severe gale.",pos:"noun"},
    "veering":{def:"Changing direction, especially of the wind.",pos:"verb"},
    "register":{def:"Here: tone or level of formality.",pos:"noun"},
    "routine":{def:"Ordinary, regular, and not special.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did the attendant explain the lighthouse was automated?",options:["Visitors needed to pay a different price","It was important context — otherwise people expected drama and were disappointed","Health and safety rules required the explanation","The light was not working that day"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She said it was important context, because otherwise visitors expected something dramatic... and were sometimes disappointed.'"},
    {question:"What were lighthouse keepers required to do every day?",options:["Signal to passing ships","Write a logbook entry, regardless of whether anything happened","Maintain the light mechanism","Check the weather instruments at noon"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Lighthouse keepers were required to write an entry every day, regardless of whether anything happened.'"},
    {question:"What does a force 9 sea state indicate?",options:["Calm conditions","Light winds and gentle swell","Severe gale with very high waves","Fog and poor visibility"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Force 9, which is severe — the kind of conditions where waves can be nine metres high.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator find moving about the keepers' way of recording?",options:["The beautiful handwriting","That they worked so long without seeing other people","Doing something important carefully, without performing the emotion of it","The fact that the logbooks survived so long"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Doing something important, carefully, without being asked to perform the emotion of it.'"}
  ]
});

