STORIES[3][7].push({
  id:"l3.8s1", levelId:3, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Interview", emoji:"💼", genre:"Everyday Life",
  wordCount:364, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A first job interview — and the strange performance of trying to seem like yourself.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The interview was for a Saturday job at a bookshop. It was a small independent, not a chain, and the advertisement had said something about enthusiasm for books being more important than experience. I had enthusiasm and no experience, so I applied.",
    "I was asked to come at eleven on a Thursday. I arrived at ten to eleven, which is what my mother had told me to do: early enough to show respect, not so early as to be inconvenient. There was a woman in her fifties sitting behind the till, who told me the manager was with another candidate and would be five minutes. There was another candidate, which I had not considered. I sat in the section labelled Travel and tried to look calm.",
    "The manager was a tall man called Niall with reading glasses pushed up on his head. He asked me about the last book I had read that I had genuinely liked, and why. He asked what I thought made someone a good bookseller. He asked if I could work without supervision. He did not ask me to describe my strengths and weaknesses, which I had prepared an answer to, and which felt wasted.",
    "The strange thing about interviews is that you are both yourself and a version of yourself you are presenting. You answer truthfully, but you also choose which truths. You try to seem like someone who is confident but not arrogant, interested but not overenthusiastic. It is an odd performance and everyone in the room knows it is happening, but everyone pretends otherwise.",
    "He offered me the job at the end of the interview, which I had not expected to happen in the room. He said they needed someone who had read things and cared about them, and that was harder to find than it should be. I started the following Saturday. I have been there eleven months. I still feel slightly fraudulent some mornings, but less so than I used to."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "independent":{def:"Not part of a large company or chain; privately owned.",pos:"adjective"},
    "candidate":{def:"A person applying for a job.",pos:"noun"},
    "supervision":{def:"Watching over and directing someone's work.",pos:"noun"},
    "arrogant":{def:"Having an exaggerated sense of one's own importance.",pos:"adjective"},
    "fraudulent":{def:"Here: a feeling of being a fake or not deserving something.",pos:"adjective"},
    "genuinely":{def:"Truly and sincerely, without pretending.",pos:"adverb"},
    "enthusiasm":{def:"Eagerness and energy for something.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What did the bookshop advertisement say was more important than experience?",options:["Good timekeeping","Enthusiasm for books","Previous retail work","Being available on weekdays"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Enthusiasm for books being more important than experience.'"},
    {question:"Why had the narrator prepared an answer about strengths and weaknesses?",options:["The advertisement asked for one","It was a common interview question","Niall had emailed to say he would ask it","Their mother suggested it"],correct:1,
     feedback:"The narrator had 'prepared an answer to' the classic strengths/weaknesses question, though it was never asked."},
    {question:"What does the narrator describe as strange about interviews?",options:["The waiting room atmosphere","You are both yourself and a version of yourself you are presenting","The questions are always the same","Interviewers rarely listen properly"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'You are both yourself and a version of yourself you are presenting.'"},
    {question:"Why did Niall say they needed someone like the narrator?",options:["Their timetable was flexible","Someone who had read things and cared about them was harder to find than it should be","They had strong retail experience","They were available immediately"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'They needed someone who had read things and cared about them, and that was harder to find than it should be.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][7].push({
  id:"l3.8s2", levelId:3, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Night Shift", emoji:"🌙", genre:"Family / Work",
  wordCount:361, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Staying up late and seeing the house from a different angle — through the eyes of a parent who works nights.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My mother works three night shifts a week at the hospital — she is a nurse, and nights are part of the rotation. She leaves at nine-thirty in the evening and comes back at around eight in the morning. On the nights she works, the house is different. My father cooks and goes to bed early. The house is quieter.",
    "Once, when I was twelve, I could not sleep. I came downstairs at two in the morning and sat at the kitchen table with a glass of water. The house felt completely unfamiliar. The same rooms, the same furniture — but at two in the morning, without the structure of daily life running through them, they were just rooms. Walls and space.",
    "I thought about my mother, who at that moment was somewhere in the hospital — a ward, a corridor, a nurses' station — doing things that needed doing. She had chosen work that was required at night because the patients who needed care at three in the morning needed it as much as the ones at three in the afternoon. I had never thought about this before, sitting in the kitchen at two.",
    "When she came home that morning, I was in the kitchen again, making toast. She looked tired in the way that is different from ordinary tiredness — a specific flatness around the eyes that I recognised from other mornings. She said the night had been busy. She made tea. We sat for twenty minutes before she went to bed.",
    "I have thought about that morning several times. There is something important in the idea that ordinary life runs on work done while most people are asleep — not just hospitals, but all the bakeries, the haulage drivers, the radio presenters, the people who print newspapers, the engineers who fix things without disrupting the daytime. Most of it stays invisible, which is partly what makes it work."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "rotation":{def:"A system where different people take turns doing different tasks.",pos:"noun"},
    "nurses' station":{def:"A desk or area in a hospital where nursing staff work and keep records.",pos:"noun"},
    "flatness":{def:"Here: a lack of expression or energy, visible in someone's face.",pos:"noun"},
    "haulage":{def:"The transport of heavy goods by road.",pos:"noun"},
    "disrupting":{def:"Interrupting or preventing something from continuing normally.",pos:"verb"},
    "invisible":{def:"Not seen or noticed.",pos:"adjective"},
    "unfamiliar":{def:"Not known or recognised; strange.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What is the narrator's mother's job?",options:["A doctor","A nurse","A hospital administrator","A paramedic"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She is a nurse, and nights are part of the rotation.'"},
    {question:"What struck the narrator about the house at two in the morning?",options:["It was too cold","It felt completely unfamiliar — just walls and space, without daily life running through it","It was noisier than expected","They heard someone outside"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Without the structure of daily life running through them, they were just rooms. Walls and space.'"},
    {question:"How did the narrator recognise their mother's post-night-shift tiredness?",options:["She always went straight to bed","She did not speak when she arrived home","A specific flatness around the eyes","She moved more slowly than usual"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A specific flatness around the eyes that I recognised from other mornings.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator say about overnight work at the end?",options:["They think night work should be better paid","Most of it stays invisible, which is partly what makes it work","More people should try working at night","Night shifts are only necessary in hospitals"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Most of it stays invisible, which is partly what makes it work.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][7].push({
  id:"l3.8s3", levelId:3, subLevel:7,
  title:"What the River Knows", emoji:"🌊", genre:"Nature / Science",
  wordCount:363, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Volunteering for a river survey — and what one day of counting tells you about a whole ecosystem.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The survey was organised by a local conservation group, and they needed volunteers with no specialist knowledge — just people willing to spend a Saturday morning on the riverbank. I went in September, which is apparently the best time for invertebrate surveys because the populations are at their peak and the water temperature means the creatures are active.",
    "They gave us nets on long handles, rubber gloves, and trays of water for sorting specimens. The technique was simple: you hold the net downstream, kick the riverbed vigorously upstream of it for thirty seconds, then lift the net and transfer what you have caught to the tray. The tray goes on a white sheet on the bank and you work through the contents with a blunt probe, trying to identify and count everything alive.",
    "In my first kick-sample, there were 47 living invertebrates of at least eight different types. The group leader — a woman called Mira who had been doing this for fifteen years — identified them quickly: mayfly nymphs, stonefly larvae, water beetles, freshwater shrimps, a leech, and what turned out to be a rare riffle beetle that she took three photographs of and entered into a national database.",
    "Mira explained why the variety mattered. Different species tolerate different levels of pollution. Stonefly larvae, she said, cannot survive in water above a certain pollution threshold. Finding them in good numbers means the water is clean. Finding only worms and certain fly larvae, with nothing sensitive, means the opposite. The river tells you what has been done to it, if you know how to ask.",
    "We surveyed four points along the river. The results were different at each one — better above the village than below it, worse at the section near the old farm track. The data goes to the Environment Agency. Mira said it was possible that one day's data from one volunteer group could trigger an investigation that changed how land nearby was managed. I found that genuinely useful to know."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "invertebrate":{def:"An animal without a backbone, such as an insect, worm, or snail.",pos:"noun"},
    "specimens":{def:"Individual examples collected for study.",pos:"noun"},
    "nymphs":{def:"The young form of certain insects, such as mayflies.",pos:"noun"},
    "larvae":{def:"The young, worm-like form of an insect before it develops fully.",pos:"noun"},
    "threshold":{def:"The point at which something starts to happen.",pos:"noun"},
    "riffle beetle":{def:"A small beetle that lives in fast-flowing, well-oxygenated water.",pos:"noun"},
    "Environment Agency":{def:"The government body responsible for protecting the environment in England.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why is September the best time for invertebrate surveys?",options:["The river is at its lowest level","Populations peak and water temperature keeps creatures active","Rainfall is lowest so the water is clearest","Rare species migrate to the river"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The populations are at their peak and the water temperature means the creatures are active.'"},
    {question:"What made the rare riffle beetle significant?",options:["It was an endangered species","Mira photographed it and entered it into a national database","It was the first found in the river","It was only found at one survey point"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A rare riffle beetle that she took three photographs of and entered into a national database.'"},
    {question:"What do stonefly larvae indicate about water quality?",options:["They can survive pollution better than other species","They indicate high levels of nitrates","They cannot survive above a certain pollution threshold, so finding them means the water is clean","They thrive in both clean and polluted water"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Stonefly larvae cannot survive in water above a certain pollution threshold. Finding them in good numbers means the water is clean.'"},
    {question:"What could data from one volunteer group's survey potentially do?",options:["Replace professional monitoring","Allow the group to manage the land directly","Trigger an investigation that changed how nearby land was managed","Prove the river was safe for swimming"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'One day's data from one volunteer group could trigger an investigation that changed how land nearby was managed.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][7].push({
  id:"l3.8s4", levelId:3, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Archive", emoji:"📁", genre:"History / Research",
  wordCount:362, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A school project leads to a local archive — and an unexpected discovery about a school that no longer exists.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The local history project was meant to be about the area in the 1940s. My teacher suggested the county archive, which I had not known existed. It is in a building near the library, staffed by two archivists, and it holds documents going back several centuries. You have to ask for materials at the front desk, and you are not allowed to use pens — pencils only.",
    "I had come to look for anything relating to the war years. One of the archivists, a quiet man called Mr Peake, asked if I had anything specific in mind. I did not. He said the most interesting things were usually found by people who did not. He brought out a box of materials relating to a school called St Columba's, which had been evacuated from London to our town in September 1939 and had spent the whole war here before returning in 1945.",
    "The box contained school logbooks, class registers, letters between the headmaster and the London County Council, and a set of photographs. In the photographs, the London children were photographed alongside the local children — two schools sharing one building, using it in shifts. The London children looked slightly formal, as if they were still in the city. The local ones looked easier in the space.",
    "One letter was from a London parent complaining that the area was 'not what had been agreed upon' regarding accommodation standards. Another was from the headmaster to the Council requesting additional funding for basic supplies. The handwriting was careful and official, but you could read the strain underneath.",
    "I spent three hours there. The project was supposed to be four hundred words. What I handed in was nine hundred, and my teacher gave me a note saying I should have kept to the brief. She also said, at the bottom, that the discovery about St Columba's was genuinely interesting. I have been back to the archive four times since."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "archive":{def:"A collection of historical documents and records, or the place where they are stored.",pos:"noun"},
    "archivists":{def:"People trained to manage and preserve historical records.",pos:"noun"},
    "evacuated":{def:"Moved from a dangerous place to a safer one.",pos:"verb"},
    "registers":{def:"Official lists of names and information, such as school attendance records.",pos:"noun"},
    "London County Council":{def:"The local government authority for London until 1965.",pos:"noun"},
    "accommodation":{def:"A place to live or stay.",pos:"noun"},
    "brief":{def:"The instructions or requirements given for a task.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was unusual about using the county archive?",options:["You needed a membership card","You were not allowed to use pens, only pencils","The opening hours were very limited","You needed a teacher to accompany you"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'You are not allowed to use pens — pencils only.'"},
    {question:"Why had St Columba's school come to the town?",options:["It had been closed down permanently","The building was being renovated","It had been evacuated from London at the start of the war","The headmaster had moved to the area"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A school called St Columba's, which had been evacuated from London to our town in September 1939.'"},
    {question:"How did the two schools share the one building?",options:["Different wings for each school","Using it in shifts","London children in the morning, local in the afternoon","Alternate days of the week"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Two schools sharing one building, using it in shifts.'"},
    {question:"What did the teacher say in her note at the end of the project?",options:["Only that the word count was too long","That the research was poor","That the word count was too long, but also that the St Columba's discovery was genuinely interesting","That the narrator should visit the archive again"],correct:2,
     feedback:"She noted the brief was not followed, but added 'the discovery about St Columba's was genuinely interesting.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][7].push({
  id:"l3.8s5", levelId:3, subLevel:7,
  title:"Slow Bread", emoji:"🍞", genre:"Home / Everyday Life",
  wordCount:366, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Learning to make sourdough — the kind that takes three days and teaches you something about patience.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Making sourdough bread takes much longer than making ordinary bread. You maintain a starter — a living culture of wild yeast and bacteria that you feed flour and water every day. The starter ferments, producing the gas that makes the bread rise. If you neglect it for too long, it dies. My grandmother kept hers alive for eleven years before she gave me a portion of it in a jar.",
    "The bread itself takes three days if you do it properly. Day one: mix the dough, do a series of folds over three hours, then refrigerate overnight. Day two: shape the loaf and prove it again, in a floured basket, for another twelve to eighteen hours in the fridge. Day three: bake in a covered cast-iron pot at high heat. The steam trapped inside the pot produces the crust. You take the lid off for the last fifteen minutes.",
    "The first three loaves I made were wrong in different ways. The first was too flat because I had not folded the dough enough times and the structure had no strength. The second was gummy in the middle — it had been proved too long and the yeast had exhausted its food. The third was better: a proper open crumb, a crisp crust, and the slight sourness that comes from a longer fermentation.",
    "What the bread teaches you is that it operates on its own schedule, not yours. You can understand the process and follow it correctly, and a change in kitchen temperature or humidity will still alter the timing. You have to watch the dough, not the clock. If it looks ready, it is ready. If it does not, another two hours.",
    "I bake every Saturday now. The starter lives on the kitchen windowsill in a jar with a rubber band marking where it was after the last feeding. I move the rubber band when I feed it and check the rise. My grandmother rings on Saturdays sometimes and asks how it is getting on, which is how we talk about the starter as if it is a person. It has lived in our family longer than I have."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "starter":{def:"A mixture of flour and water containing wild yeast, used to make sourdough bread rise.",pos:"noun"},
    "ferments":{def:"Undergoes a chemical change by yeast or bacteria, producing gas.",pos:"verb"},
    "prove":{def:"To allow dough to rise before baking.",pos:"verb"},
    "cast-iron":{def:"Made from a heavy, rigid type of iron.",pos:"adjective"},
    "crumb":{def:"The soft interior texture of bread.",pos:"noun"},
    "humidity":{def:"The amount of water vapour in the air.",pos:"noun"},
    "exhausted":{def:"Here: used up all available resources.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Where did the narrator's starter originally come from?",options:["They made it from scratch","A specialist bakery","A portion of their grandmother's eleven-year-old starter","A kit bought online"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'My grandmother kept hers alive for eleven years before she gave me a portion of it in a jar.'"},
    {question:"What was wrong with the second loaf?",options:["It was too flat from under-folding","It had a burnt crust","It was gummy in the middle from being proved too long","It had too strong a sour flavour"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The second was gummy in the middle — it had been proved too long and the yeast had exhausted its food.'"},
    {question:"What does the bread teach about timing?",options:["Exact timings must be followed to the minute","Timing is less important than the type of flour used","You must watch the dough, not the clock","A shorter prove always produces a better loaf"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'You have to watch the dough, not the clock. If it looks ready, it is ready.'"},
    {question:"How does the narrator track the starter's growth between feedings?",options:["A temperature gauge","A rubber band marking the level after each feeding","A daily photograph","Weighing the jar"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A jar with a rubber band marking where it was after the last feeding.'"}
  ]
});

