STORIES[3][8].push({
  id:"l3.9s4", levelId:3, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Last Season", emoji:"🏏", genre:"Sport / Family",
  wordCount:376, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A grandfather's last cricket season — and why a game about almost nothing means a great deal.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My grandfather played cricket for the village team for forty-one years, from 1975 until last summer, when his knee finally made it impractical. He was not a gifted player by any standard measure. He batted at nine, which means eighth or ninth wicket down, and he took wickets irregularly but reliably — a medium-pace bowler who had one delivery that swung unexpectedly in damp conditions and accounted for many batsmen who were playing more cautiously than the situation required.",
    "I went to three of his matches last summer, knowing it would be the last season. Village cricket moves slowly. The batting side sits on benches at the boundary edge. There is tea at the interval, with sandwiches provided by a rota of volunteers. Between overs, nothing much happens. Fielders adjust their positions slightly. The scorer marks a dot in the book. A dog wanders onto the outfield and is gently removed.",
    "My grandfather fielded at mid-on, which is a position close to the bowler. He moved carefully because of the knee, but he took a catch in the second match I attended — a low, difficult catch that required him to move suddenly to his right — and the appeal from the fielders was genuine and loud. He held the ball up and smiled the way people do when they have done something they were not sure they still could.",
    "After the last game of the season, the team gathered outside the pavilion. Someone had organised a small presentation — a framed photograph and a bottle of something. My grandfather gave a short speech that thanked people individually, which took longer than the other speeches, and there was a moment near the end when he paused and looked at the pitch and did not say anything for a few seconds.",
    "I have not played cricket. I do not particularly want to. But I have been thinking about that pause since September. Forty-one years of the same ground, the same rota, the same tea — and at the end of it, something worth pausing for."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "medium-pace":{def:"A bowling style that is neither very fast nor very slow.",pos:"adjective"},
    "swung":{def:"Here: moved through the air in a curved path (of a cricket ball).",pos:"verb"},
    "rota":{def:"A list that shows when different people are responsible for a task.",pos:"noun"},
    "pavilion":{def:"The building at a cricket ground where players change and rest.",pos:"noun"},
    "mid-on":{def:"A fielding position close to the bowler on the leg side.",pos:"noun"},
    "appeal":{def:"In cricket, a shout from fielders asking the umpire if a batsman is out.",pos:"noun"},
    "impractical":{def:"Not sensible or possible to do in the circumstances.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Where did the grandfather bat in the batting order?",options:["At the top, as an opener","At number five","At nine — eighth or ninth wicket down","As a specialist number eleven"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He batted at nine, which means eighth or ninth wicket down.'"},
    {question:"What was special about the grandfather's bowling delivery?",options:["It was extremely fast","It swung unexpectedly in damp conditions","It was always aimed at the stumps","It was consistently accurate"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'One delivery that swung unexpectedly in damp conditions and accounted for many batsmen.'"},
    {question:"What happened after the grandfather took the catch?",options:["The batting team disputed it","The umpire was unsure","The fielders appealed genuinely and loudly","The grandfather dropped the ball initially"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The appeal from the fielders was genuine and loud.'"},
    {question:"What struck the narrator about the pause in the grandfather's speech?",options:["It suggested he was upset","It felt like a performance for the audience","Forty-one years of the same ground had produced something worth pausing for","The grandfather could not remember the names he wanted to thank"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Forty-one years of the same ground, the same rota, the same tea — and at the end of it, something worth pausing for.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][8].push({
  id:"l3.9s5", levelId:3, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Translation", emoji:"📖", genre:"Language / Family",
  wordCount:373, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Helping to translate letters between a grandmother and her relatives abroad — and what gets lost.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My grandmother came from Poland in 1968 and her English has never been good with formal written language, though her spoken English is confident and particular. Her younger sister, who never left Poland, writes letters twice a year. They are long letters, handwritten in Polish, about family, health, the garden, the neighbourhood, and small observations about the world. My grandmother reads them without help. Replying is harder.",
    "She dictates her replies to me, in a mixture of English and Polish, and I type them on my laptop. My Polish is basic — I understand more than I can speak, and my reading is slow — but for this purpose I am translator and typist. She speaks; I ask her to repeat when I have not understood; I type what she means, not always exactly what she says.",
    "What gets lost is difficult to define. She uses a phrase sometimes that translates literally as 'the grey of the morning', which in Polish carries a specific emotional quality — not sadness exactly, but a kind of settled melancholy that is not uncomfortable, more like familiarity. In English, 'the grey of the morning' sounds poetic but does not carry that weight. We have had conversations about which English phrase is closest. We have not found one.",
    "Her sister replies to whatever I have typed, which means she is reading my translation rather than my grandmother's own words. My grandmother says Hania does not seem to notice. I think this is because they have been writing to each other for fifty years and can read what the other means through whatever words arrive.",
    "I have been doing this for three years. My Polish has improved considerably. I made a mistake in the second letter that changed the meaning of a sentence about their mother from a memory to a criticism, and my grandmother laughed for a long time about it. She said Hania had written back asking who had upset her. The sentence was corrected in the following letter. Some things are more important than precision."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "dictates":{def:"Speaks words aloud for someone else to write down.",pos:"verb"},
    "translator":{def:"A person who converts language from one form into another.",pos:"noun"},
    "melancholy":{def:"A feeling of quiet sadness or thoughtfulness.",pos:"noun"},
    "familiarity":{def:"The quality of being well known or comfortable through long experience.",pos:"noun"},
    "precision":{def:"The quality of being exact and accurate.",pos:"noun"},
    "particular":{def:"Here: having a distinctive and individual quality.",pos:"adjective"},
    "literally":{def:"In the exact or primary meaning of a word or phrase.",pos:"adverb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why does the narrator help with the letters rather than the grandmother writing them alone?",options:["The grandmother cannot read Polish anymore","The grandmother's written English struggles with formal language","The sister only reads English","The letters need to be typed for delivery"],correct:1,
     feedback:"The grandmother's 'English has never been good with formal written language.'"},
    {question:"What is the problem with the Polish phrase meaning 'the grey of the morning'?",options:["It has no equivalent English words at all","In English it sounds poetic but does not carry the same emotional weight","It refers to a Polish cultural tradition","The sister does not use the phrase so it would confuse her"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'In English, \"the grey of the morning\" sounds poetic but does not carry that weight.'"},
    {question:"What mistake did the narrator make in the second letter?",options:["They addressed it to the wrong person","They wrote in the wrong language by accident","They changed a sentence about the mother from a memory to a criticism","They left out an entire paragraph"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A mistake... changed the meaning of a sentence about their mother from a memory to a criticism.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator say at the end about precision?",options:["Precision is essential in translation","Some things are more important than precision","Precision improves with practice","The grandmother values precision above all else"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Some things are more important than precision.'"}
  ]
});

