STORIES[3][9].push({
  id:"l3.10s1", levelId:3, subLevel:9,
  title:"The Inventory", emoji:"📋", genre:"Home / Family",
  wordCount:381, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Helping to inventory a family home before it is sold — and what objects reveal about people.",
  paragraphs:[
    "My aunt had to sell her house when she moved into smaller accommodation, and she asked me to help make an inventory of the contents. The estate agent had said it would be useful for insurance purposes, and also to help with decisions about what to keep, donate, or dispose of. I spent two Saturdays going through every room systematically with a notebook and a camera.",
    "An inventory is a strange thing to compile because it requires you to look at objects as objects rather than as part of the background of someone's life. A house you have visited since childhood is not normally composed of things — it is composed of rooms and smells and the particular quality of the light through specific windows. When you start listing what is actually there, the rooms become different.",
    "My aunt's kitchen had forty-three items on the shelves and in the visible cupboards, not counting the contents of the drawers. The sitting room had two bookcases containing 214 volumes, which I did not count individually but estimated from shelf measurements. There was a painting above the fireplace that my aunt said had come from an auction in 1978 for four pounds. There was a small bronze horse on the mantelpiece that had belonged to her father, who died before she was thirty.",
    "She made decisions quickly, which I had not expected. The large furniture and most of the kitchen equipment went to a clearance company. A selection of books went to the library. The painting, it turned out, was worth considerably more than four pounds — a valuer came, looked at the back of the canvas, and named a figure that made my aunt sit down. She is having it assessed properly.",
    "She kept the bronze horse. She kept a small collection of letters and photographs. She kept three particular books and a set of cups that had been her mother's. Everything else — forty years of ordinary life — is now in other people's houses or has gone elsewhere. She said it was lighter, after. I said I could see why. The horse is on her windowsill in the new flat, which is the first thing you see when you walk in."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "inventory":{def:"A complete list of objects in a particular place.",pos:"noun"},
    "compile":{def:"To produce a list or collection by gathering information.",pos:"verb"},
    "clearance company":{def:"A business that removes and disposes of the contents of a property.",pos:"noun"},
    "valuer":{def:"A person who professionally assesses the monetary worth of an object.",pos:"noun"},
    "mantelpiece":{def:"A shelf above a fireplace.",pos:"noun"},
    "bronze":{def:"A brownish metal alloy of copper and tin.",pos:"noun"},
    "assessed":{def:"Evaluated carefully to determine value or condition.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did the estate agent suggest an inventory?",options:["It was required by law","It was useful for insurance and deciding what to keep","The removal company needed it","The council required it for planning"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Useful for insurance purposes, and also to help with decisions about what to keep, donate, or dispose of.'"},
    {question:"What did the narrator find strange about compiling the inventory?",options:["The aunt kept interrupting","It took much longer than expected","It made them look at objects as objects rather than as part of someone's life","The rooms were very full"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'An inventory requires you to look at objects as objects rather than as part of the background of someone's life.'"},
    {question:"What happened when a valuer looked at the painting?",options:["They confirmed it was worth about four pounds","They could not identify who had painted it","They named a figure that made the aunt sit down","They said it should be sent to auction immediately"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A valuer came, looked at the back of the canvas, and named a figure that made my aunt sit down.'"},
    {question:"What did the aunt say after the clearance?",options:["She regretted giving so much away","She said it was lighter","She wished she had kept the painting","She was unsure about the new flat"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She said it was lighter, after.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][9].push({
  id:"l3.10s2", levelId:3, subLevel:9,
  title:"The Memory Test", emoji:"🧠", genre:"Science / Personal",
  wordCount:379, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Taking part in a university memory experiment — and what it teaches about how memory actually works.",
  paragraphs:[
    "A psychology department at the local university ran a public participation study on memory and invited sixth-form students to volunteer. I went on a Wednesday afternoon in February with two people from my class. We were told it would take about ninety minutes and we would receive a £10 shopping voucher, which was the honest reason most of us went.",
    "The experiment had several parts. In the first, we were shown sixty photographs of everyday objects for two seconds each, then asked thirty minutes later to identify which ones we had seen from a larger set of photographs that included similar-but-different items. I was confident in most of my identifications. I was wrong in eleven of them.",
    "The second part was more interesting. We read a short passage about a fictional burglary, then answered questions about the details. The passage mentioned that the burglar wore a dark jacket. After a delay and a series of unrelated tasks, a researcher mentioned casually — as if checking something — that 'the man in the blue jacket' had acted quickly. In the final test, over half the participants said they had read that the jacket was blue. Including me.",
    "The researcher explained afterwards that this was called the misinformation effect — when post-event information becomes incorporated into a person's memory of the original event, replacing or altering what was actually there. It happens most reliably when the new information is plausible and presented by someone who appears authoritative. Eyewitness testimony, she said, was affected by it more often than most people assumed.",
    "What struck me was not that I had been wrong. I had expected to be wrong about some things. What struck me was how certain I had felt. The blue jacket was there, clear and definite, when I tried to recall the passage. It felt like memory. It was, apparently, construction. I am now considerably more cautious about anything I feel certain about."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "psychology":{def:"The study of the human mind and behaviour.",pos:"noun"},
    "misinformation effect":{def:"The tendency for memory to be altered by information received after the original event.",pos:"noun"},
    "post-event":{def:"Occurring after the event being remembered.",pos:"adjective"},
    "incorporated":{def:"Made part of something; absorbed into a whole.",pos:"verb"},
    "plausible":{def:"Seeming reasonable or probable.",pos:"adjective"},
    "eyewitness testimony":{def:"A first-hand account of an event by someone who was present.",pos:"noun"},
    "authoritative":{def:"Appearing confident, reliable, and knowledgeable.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How many of the narrator's photograph identifications were wrong?",options:["Three","Seven","Eleven","Fifteen"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I was wrong in eleven of them.'"},
    {question:"What was the 'misinformation effect' the researcher described?",options:["Remembering things that never happened from imagination","Forgetting things that did happen under stress","Post-event information becoming incorporated into memory, replacing what was actually there","The tendency to believe others rather than yourself"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'When post-event information becomes incorporated into a person's memory of the original event, replacing or altering what was actually there.'"},
    {question:"When is the misinformation effect most reliable?",options:["When the new information contradicts the original strongly","When the person is young","When the new information is plausible and presented by someone authoritative","When the original event was very emotional"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Most reliably when the new information is plausible and presented by someone who appears authoritative.'"},
    {question:"What conclusion does the narrator draw at the end?",options:["They will trust their memory less and verify more","They are considerably more cautious about anything they feel certain about","Memory experiments are unreliable themselves","They would not participate in studies again"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'I am now considerably more cautious about anything I feel certain about.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][9].push({
  id:"l3.10s3", levelId:3, subLevel:9,
  title:"The Unfinished Building", emoji:"🏗️", genre:"History / Observation",
  wordCount:382, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A building that has been under construction for twelve years — and what long projects reveal about intention.",
  paragraphs:[
    "There is a building in the centre of town that has been under construction for twelve years. I know this because there is a planning notice still attached to the hoarding, faded but legible, dated 2014. The original approval was for a mixed-use development: retail on the ground floor, twelve residential units above. The hoarding shows a computer-generated image of the finished building — glass and pale brick, people with coffee cups walking past a planted forecourt.",
    "The site has gone through several phases. For the first three years, there was active construction: the basement was dug, the concrete frame was poured, the first two floors were built. Then work stopped. The crane was dismantled. For about two years there was nothing — just the incomplete structure behind the hoarding, weathering quietly.",
    "Then a different company took over. You could tell because the hoarding was repainted and new contact details appeared. Work resumed, more slowly. Two more floors were added over the following three years. Then another gap, during which the scaffolding remained but no workers appeared for months. Currently, something is happening again — there are materials arriving and a small crew of workers visible from the upper deck of passing buses.",
    "I researched the site at the county records office. Three different developers have held the planning permission at different times. Two of them became insolvent. The current owner acquired the site in 2021 at a significant discount, which is recorded in the land registry documents. The permitted development is still live. The planning authority has extended it twice.",
    "The computer-generated image on the hoarding shows a finished building that has not existed for twelve years, and may not exist for several more. The people with coffee cups are frozen mid-stride, permanently about to walk past a forecourt that is still a construction site. I find this one of the more accurate representations of how long things actually take."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "hoarding":{def:"A large, temporary screen placed around a construction site.",pos:"noun"},
    "mixed-use development":{def:"A building or area designed for both commercial and residential use.",pos:"noun"},
    "forecourt":{def:"An open area in front of a building.",pos:"noun"},
    "insolvent":{def:"Unable to pay debts; bankrupt.",pos:"adjective"},
    "land registry":{def:"The official record of who owns land and property.",pos:"noun"},
    "planning permission":{def:"Official approval from a local authority to carry out building work.",pos:"noun"},
    "permitted development":{def:"Building work that has been granted planning approval.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How does the narrator know construction started in 2014?",options:["A local news article","A planning notice on the hoarding, faded but still legible","The original developer's website","Records at the county office"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'There is a planning notice still attached to the hoarding, faded but legible, dated 2014.'"},
    {question:"How did the narrator know when a different company took over the site?",options:["A new planning notice was posted","The original developer announced it publicly","The hoarding was repainted and new contact details appeared","The design of the building changed"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The hoarding was repainted and new contact details appeared.'"},
    {question:"What happened to two of the three developers who held the planning permission?",options:["They were taken over by larger companies","They became insolvent","They sold the permission at a profit","They completed other projects instead"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Two of them became insolvent.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator say about the computer-generated image on the hoarding?",options:["It is an accurate representation of the future building","It no longer matches the current design","It shows people frozen mid-stride in a forecourt that is still a construction site","It has been replaced three times over twelve years"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The people with coffee cups are frozen mid-stride, permanently about to walk past a forecourt that is still a construction site.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][9].push({
  id:"l3.10s4", levelId:3, subLevel:9,
  title:"The Exam Result", emoji:"📊", genre:"School / Personal",
  wordCount:378, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Waiting for a result that matters — and what the waiting itself teaches you.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Results day is in August, and you can get them online from seven in the morning before the envelope arrives at school at eight-thirty. I had known this for months, which gave me several months in which to decide how I felt about it. I decided, in advance, that I would wait for the envelope. I felt this was more dignified. At six forty-five on results morning, I checked my phone.",
    "The grades appeared in a list in alphabetical order by subject. Biology at the top, then Chemistry, then English Language, then English Literature. I read them in order. Biology was better than expected. Chemistry was what I had expected. English Language was worse than expected. English Literature was much better than expected.",
    "The overall result was approximately what I needed. I say approximately because the grade boundaries had shifted slightly and what had been required for the particular path I had in mind turned out to be slightly different from what I had prepared for. I spent thirty minutes online working out whether I had what was needed. I had, with a small margin.",
    "I called my mother, who was in the kitchen. She came upstairs and we looked at the screen together. She said the English Literature grade was excellent. I said the English Language grade was disappointing. She said that was fair, and asked what had happened in the Language exam. I said I thought I had answered the wrong question in Section B, but I could not be certain because I had stopped thinking about it in May.",
    "The envelope arrived at eight-thirty. I had already known the contents for almost two hours by then. Opening it felt important anyway. There is something that paper does that a screen does not. I kept the results slip. I do not know entirely why. It is in the drawer with the other things that seemed, at the time, worth keeping — even though most of what it records is already in the past."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "grade boundaries":{def:"The minimum marks needed to achieve each grade in an exam.",pos:"noun"},
    "margin":{def:"The amount by which something exceeds a minimum requirement.",pos:"noun"},
    "alphabetical order":{def:"Arranged according to the letters of the alphabet.",pos:"noun"},
    "dignified":{def:"Calm and composed; having self-respect.",pos:"adjective"},
    "approximately":{def:"Roughly; not exactly but close to.",pos:"adverb"},
    "results slip":{def:"A printed document showing exam grades.",pos:"noun"},
    "Section B":{def:"A division of an exam paper.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What had the narrator decided in advance about getting results?",options:["To check online at exactly seven","To wait for the envelope at school","To ask a friend to check first","To wait until noon when the stress would be less"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'I decided, in advance, that I would wait for the envelope.' (Then checked the phone at 6:45 anyway.)"},
    {question:"Which subject grade was much better than expected?",options:["Biology","Chemistry","English Language","English Literature"],correct:3,
     feedback:"'English Literature was much better than expected.'"},
    {question:"Why did the narrator spend thirty minutes online after reading the results?",options:["They were comparing their grades with friends","They needed to confirm an acceptance to a course","They were working out whether the shifted grade boundaries meant they had what was needed","They were appealing against the English Language result"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The grade boundaries had shifted slightly... I spent thirty minutes online working out whether I had what was needed.'"},
    {question:"Why did the narrator keep the results slip?",options:["For a future application","It was a legal requirement","They could not say exactly why — it seemed worth keeping","Their mother asked them to"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I do not know entirely why. It is in the drawer with the other things that seemed, at the time, worth keeping.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[3][9].push({
  id:"l3.10s5", levelId:3, subLevel:9,
  title:"Everything Ordinary", emoji:"☀️", genre:"Reflection",
  wordCount:383, readMins:4,
  blurb:"A reflection on a day that felt significant for no particular reason — and why some ordinary days stay.",
  paragraphs:[
    "There was a day in April that I keep returning to. Nothing happened in it — nothing that would constitute a story if you tried to tell it. I walked to school in morning light that was genuinely warm for the first time that year. I had a conversation in the lunch queue with someone I do not usually speak to about something I cannot now remember. I ate a sandwich on the grass because it was finally dry enough. I walked home. I did my homework. I ate dinner.",
    "It is difficult to explain why that day stays. I have had days with more to report — events, achievements, difficulties, moments that could be narrated. This was not one of them. But the quality of the light that morning was specific in a way I noticed, and the warmth had a particular freshness because it was the first of the year, and I had a general sense during the walk home that things were fine, which is not a feeling you can manufacture.",
    "I have read that memory is selective and disproportionate — that significant events and strongly emotional ones are retained more reliably than routine days. This is probably true. But there is also a category of retained memory that seems to work differently: ordinary days that were particularly themselves. Not special in content but saturated with a quality of being fully present.",
    "I think the April day stays because I was paying attention without trying to. The light was there and I saw it. The warmth was there and I felt it. The person in the queue said something and I listened. Nothing was recorded or photographed. It existed only as the day itself, which is the condition most days are in but which most days do not seem to achieve.",
    "I have thought about what it would mean to have more days like that. I do not think you can engineer them — that would change what they are. But you can perhaps increase the likelihood by paying attention more often. It sounds simple. I am working on it."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "constitute":{def:"To be or form something.",pos:"verb"},
    "disproportionate":{def:"Too large or too small in comparison to something else.",pos:"adjective"},
    "retained":{def:"Kept in memory.",pos:"verb"},
    "saturated":{def:"Here: completely filled with a quality.",pos:"adjective"},
    "selective":{def:"Choosing carefully; not including everything.",pos:"adjective"},
    "manufacture":{def:"Here: artificially create or produce.",pos:"verb"},
    "likelihood":{def:"The probability of something happening.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What made the April morning notable for the narrator?",options:["Something unexpected happened","They performed well in a test","The light was genuinely warm for the first time that year","A friend said something kind"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'I walked to school in morning light that was genuinely warm for the first time that year.'"},
    {question:"What does the narrator say about why the day stays in memory?",options:["It involved an important conversation","They felt fully present and paid attention without trying to","They wrote about it at the time","Something unusual happened on the way home"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'I was paying attention without trying to... It existed only as the day itself.'"},
    {question:"How does the narrator describe the general category of days that stay in memory unexpectedly?",options:["Days when achievements occurred","Days that were saturated with a quality of being fully present","Days with extreme weather","Days when social connections were made"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Ordinary days that were particularly themselves... saturated with a quality of being fully present.'"},
    {question:"What is the narrator's conclusion about creating more such days?",options:["Plan more special activities","You cannot engineer them, but paying attention more often increases the likelihood","Write about each day in a journal","Spend more time outside"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'You can perhaps increase the likelihood by paying attention more often.'"}
  ]
});

