    "After that, the fox came every night. Lily's mother was worried. 'Foxes carry diseases,' she said. 'And they dig holes in the lawn.' Lily's father was less concerned. He pointed out that foxes had lived in cities for decades and were generally harmless to people. Lily herself said nothing, but she started leaving a small dish of water near the back fence. She never put food out — she had read that feeding urban foxes can make them too dependent on humans.",
    "One morning, Lily found three small cubs playing in the garden. They tumbled over each other and chased a fallen leaf. Lily watched from the window for twenty minutes without moving. That evening, she wrote about the cubs in her nature notebook with careful detail. Whatever her parents decided about the fox, she was glad the family had visited. Some things, she thought, are worth a few holes in a lawn."
