  blurb:"A community mural project starts as a disagreement — and ends as something nobody had imagined.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The blank wall at the end of Crane Street had been a problem for years. People had written graffiti on it, pasted posters, and generally ignored it. Then the community centre announced a competition: local artists could submit designs for an official mural. The winner would receive a small grant and permission to paint the whole wall. Seventeen designs were submitted. The judging panel included a professional artist, the head of the community centre, and three residents who had been selected randomly.",
    "The panel could not agree. Two of the residents preferred a design showing the town's industrial history — old factories and workers in black and white. The professional artist preferred a bold, abstract design by a young art student. After three meetings, the panel member who had said the least spoke up. She was a retired primary school teacher called Mrs. Almeida, and she had not previously said which design she preferred. 'Why choose one?' she asked. 'The history design and the abstract one could exist on the same wall. One side for the past. One side for the future. And the middle — where they meet — left open for the community to add.'",
    "It took them a moment to understand what she meant. Then everyone began talking at once. The final mural took six months to complete. The left side told the town's history. The right side showed bold, colourful abstract shapes. In the centre, a wide section had been left with light grey paint and a stack of permanent markers chained nearby. Two years later, the centre section was completely covered in messages, drawings, and signatures."
  ],
