STORIES[4][4].push({
  id:"l4.5s5", levelId:4, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Invisible Infrastructure", emoji:"🏗️", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:259, readMins:3,
  blurb:"A school trip to a water treatment plant makes Dani think differently about everything that happens when she turns on a tap.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Dani had turned on a tap every day of her life without thinking about it. Water arrived, reliably and immediately, and that was that. The school trip to the municipal water treatment plant was something she had signed up for mainly because it meant missing double maths. She did not expect to find it interesting.",
    "The plant manager, a quiet man named Mr. Henriksen, explained the process from beginning to end. Water was drawn from the reservoir twelve kilometres away, transported through underground pipes, filtered through layers of sand and activated carbon, treated with chlorine to kill bacteria, tested for over two hundred different contaminants, and then distributed through a network of pipes that ran under every road in the town. The entire system ran twenty-four hours a day, every day of the year, maintained by a team of thirty-two people.",
    "What struck Dani most was not the scale of the technology — it was the invisibility of it. All of this was happening continuously, at enormous effort and expense, and most people who used the water had never thought about it for a single second. She thought about the engineers who had designed the system decades earlier, who had known that nobody would ever thank them or even notice their work if it functioned correctly. The gratitude only appeared when something broke.",
    "On the bus back to school, she wrote in her notebook: 'The things that work perfectly are the ones we forget to think about.' She was not sure whether that was something to be grateful for or something to be slightly ashamed of. Probably, she decided, both."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "municipal":{def:"Relating to a town or city government.",pos:"adjective"},
    "contaminants":{def:"Substances that make something impure or unsafe.",pos:"noun"},
    "activated carbon":{def:"A specially treated form of carbon used to filter impurities.",pos:"noun"},
    "infrastructure":{def:"The basic systems and structures a society needs to function.",pos:"noun"},
    "reservoir":{def:"A large natural or artificial lake used for storing water.",pos:"noun"},
    "distributed":{def:"Sent out to many places from a central point.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why had Dani signed up for the school trip?",options:["She was interested in water treatment","She wanted to learn about engineering","It meant missing double maths","Her friend had recommended it"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had signed up mainly because it meant missing double maths.'"},
    {question:"How many contaminants was the water tested for?",options:["Twenty","Fifty","One hundred","Over two hundred"],correct:3,
     feedback:"'Tested for over two hundred different contaminants.'"},
    {question:"What struck Dani most about the water treatment system?",options:["Its enormous cost","Its invisibility — it worked constantly but nobody thought about it","How simple the process was","The number of workers needed"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'What struck Dani most was not the scale of the technology — it was the invisibility of it.'"},
    {question:"What observation did Dani write in her notebook?",options:["'Engineers deserve more credit'","'Water treatment is more complex than expected'","'The things that work perfectly are the ones we forget to think about'","'Infrastructure should be made more visible'"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The things that work perfectly are the ones we forget to think about.'"}
  ]
});


