STORIES[4][5].push({
  id:"l4.6s2", levelId:4, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Map Makers", emoji:"🗺️", genre:"History",
  wordCount:276, readMins:3,
  blurb:"A history project about old maps leads Kemi to think about what maps leave out — and why.",
  paragraphs:[
    "For her history project, Kemi had been given a collection of printed images: maps of her country from the fourteenth century through to the twentieth. The task was to identify how the maps had changed over time and explain what those changes showed about history. Kemi had expected this to be straightforward — old maps were less accurate, new maps were more accurate, and that was the story.",
    "She was wrong. As she looked more closely, she began to notice things that were absent. The early maps, made by European explorers, showed coastlines and trading routes with impressive detail — but the interior of the continent was almost entirely blank, labelled only with phrases like 'unknown territories' or left with decorative illustrations of animals and mountains that were clearly invented. Yet people had been living in those regions for thousands of years. Their roads, settlements, and trade routes existed. They simply had not been considered worth mapping by the people doing the mapping.",
    "Later colonial maps replaced the blank spaces with European names and administrative borders that often cut straight through existing communities and landscapes without regard for what was already there. The maps became more complete in one sense, but what they showed was not reality — it was a particular version of reality, one that served specific purposes.",
    "Kemi's final project was not what she had originally planned. Instead of tracing the improvement of cartographic accuracy, she wrote about what maps leave out, and why, and who decides. Her teacher gave her the highest mark in the class and wrote in the margin: 'This is the question all historians should be asking.' Kemi read that comment several times."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "cartographic":{def:"Relating to the making of maps.",pos:"adjective"},
    "colonial":{def:"Relating to the period when one country ruled another.",pos:"adjective"},
    "administrative":{def:"Relating to the management or government of a place.",pos:"adjective"},
    "interior":{def:"The inner part of something; the area away from the edges.",pos:"noun"},
    "absent":{def:"Not present; missing.",pos:"adjective"},
    "settlements":{def:"Places where people have built homes and live together.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What did Kemi originally expect her project about maps to show?",options:["That old maps showed more detail","That maps had always been accurate","That old maps were less accurate and new ones more accurate — a simple story of improvement","That maps change mainly for political reasons"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Old maps were less accurate, new maps were more accurate, and that was the story.' — but she was wrong."},
    {question:"What did Kemi notice about the interior regions on early European maps?",options:["They were shown in great detail","They were blank or had invented illustrations, despite having been inhabited for thousands of years","They showed trade routes correctly","They were coloured differently"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The interior of the continent was almost entirely blank... Yet people had been living in those regions for thousands of years.'"},
    {question:"What was wrong with the later colonial maps, according to Kemi?",options:["They were physically smaller","They used incorrect coastlines","They imposed European names and borders without regard for what was already there","They removed the trading routes"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Colonial maps replaced the blank spaces with European names and administrative borders that often cut straight through existing communities.'"},
    {question:"What did Kemi's final project focus on?",options:["How cartographic technology improved","What maps leave out, and why, and who decides","The most famous map makers in history","The accuracy of modern maps"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She wrote about what maps leave out, and why, and who decides.'"}
  ]
});

