STORIES[4][6].push({
  id:"l4.7s1", levelId:4, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Photograph on the Wall", emoji:"🖼️", genre:"Family",
  wordCount:291, readMins:3,
  blurb:"A photograph in his grandfather's study sparks a conversation that helps Leo understand something he hadn't known about his family.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The photograph had been on the wall of his grandfather's study for as long as Leo could remember. It showed a group of young men in what appeared to be military uniforms, standing in front of a truck, somewhere that looked dry and very flat. His grandfather was not in the photograph — or at least, Leo had never found him in it. When he had asked about it as a small child, his grandfather had changed the subject.",
    "Leo was thirteen when he finally asked again, this time at the end of an afternoon when his grandfather seemed to be in a reflective mood. His grandfather sat back in his chair and looked at the photograph for a while. 'Those are friends,' he said. 'Good men. We were the same age as you are now when that was taken, more or less.' He paused. 'Not all of them came home.'",
    "Leo waited. He had learned, as he'd grown older, that the moments after his grandfather went quiet were often the most informative — and that asking another question could close things off rather than open them. After some time, his grandfather named each person in the photograph from left to right, said something about each one, and was quiet again. The whole conversation lasted perhaps twenty minutes and covered things Leo had not known — a country he had never heard mentioned, a year before his grandfather met his grandmother, a period of time that had remained, until now, simply absent from the family story.",
    "On the drive home, Leo thought about all the things that must exist in the histories of the people around him that he would never know unless he asked, and sometimes not even then. He decided to ask more often."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "reflective":{def:"Thinking carefully and quietly about something.",pos:"adjective"},
    "informative":{def:"Giving useful information.",pos:"adjective"},
    "military":{def:"Relating to the armed forces.",pos:"adjective"},
    "absent":{def:"Not present; missing.",pos:"adjective"},
    "histories":{def:"The past events of people's lives.",pos:"noun"},
    "period":{def:"A length of time.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why had Leo never asked about the photograph as a child?",options:["He was not curious about it","His grandfather had always changed the subject","The photograph was in a room he was not allowed in","He thought he knew who was in it"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'When he had asked about it as a small child, his grandfather had changed the subject.'"},
    {question:"What did Leo's grandfather mean by 'Not all of them came home'?",options:["Some of the men got lost","Some of the men moved to other countries","Some of the men died","Some of the men stayed where they were posted"],correct:2,
     feedback:"This phrase, used in the context of military service, means that some of the men were killed."},
    {question:"Why did Leo decide not to ask another question after his grandfather went quiet?",options:["He was bored","He had learned that asking again could close things off rather than open them","He was afraid of upsetting his grandfather","He had already learned what he wanted to know"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'He had learned that the moments after his grandfather went quiet were often the most informative — and that asking another question could close things off.'"},
    {question:"What did Leo reflect on during the drive home?",options:["How much he had missed by not asking sooner","How strange the photograph looked","That all the people he knew had unknown histories he might never discover unless he asked","That his grandfather had been hiding information"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He thought about all the things that must exist in the histories of the people around him that he would never know unless he asked.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][6].push({
  id:"l4.7s2", levelId:4, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Quiet Student", emoji:"✏️", genre:"School",
  wordCount:289, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When a new teacher consistently calls on the quiet students at the back, Maya begins to notice that silence isn't always what it seems.",
  paragraphs:[
    "In most classes, Maya sat at the back and did not put her hand up. She was not disengaged — she followed every lesson, took careful notes, and completed every assignment on time. But something about the act of raising her hand felt exposing in a way she had never fully examined. The risk was not getting the answer wrong; it was the moment of visibility itself, everyone turning to look.",
    "The new English teacher, Mr. Osei, seemed to have noticed this pattern across the class within the first week. He did not call on students randomly, which could be alarming. Instead, he gave the class a question, allowed two full minutes of silent thinking time, and then asked for responses in a particular way — not 'Who can answer?' but 'What are people thinking?' The slight change in phrasing made a difference Maya could not immediately explain. It felt less like being tested and more like being consulted.",
    "The first time he called on her specifically, she had already formed her answer during the thinking time and delivered it more clearly than she expected. He responded to it seriously, extended it, and built the next question from what she had said. Maya noticed that two other students — both quiet, both at the back — straightened slightly in their seats.",
    "By the middle of term, Maya was still not one of the students who answered most often. But she had started, on occasion, to put her hand up first. She had not changed; the conditions had changed. She thought about this sometimes when she heard people describe quiet students as not being engaged. Presence, she had decided, came in many forms — and most of them were invisible to people who were only looking for raised hands."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "disengaged":{def:"Not involved or interested.",pos:"adjective"},
    "visibility":{def:"The state of being seen by others.",pos:"noun"},
    "phrasing":{def:"The particular words chosen to express something.",pos:"noun"},
    "consulted":{def:"Asked for your opinion or input.",pos:"verb"},
    "exposing":{def:"Making you feel seen or vulnerable.",pos:"adjective"},
    "presence":{def:"Being in a place; also: showing engagement.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why didn't Maya put her hand up in class?",options:["She didn't know the answers","She found the lessons boring","The act of visibility itself — everyone turning to look — felt exposing","She was told not to by a previous teacher"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Something about the act of raising her hand felt exposing... The risk was not getting the answer wrong; it was the moment of visibility.'"},
    {question:"How did Mr. Osei change the way he asked for answers?",options:["He only asked students who had been quiet","He randomly selected students using a computer","He gave thinking time and asked 'What are people thinking?' rather than 'Who can answer?'","He allowed students to write their answers instead"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He gave the class a question, allowed two full minutes of silent thinking time, and asked 'What are people thinking?' — not 'Who can answer?'"},
    {question:"What did Maya notice about the other quiet students when Mr. Osei responded seriously to her answer?",options:["They looked uncomfortable","Two of them straightened slightly in their seats","They started to laugh","They looked away"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Two other students — both quiet, both at the back — straightened slightly in their seats.'"},
    {question:"What conclusion did Maya reach about 'presence' in class?",options:["Quiet students are not really present","Putting your hand up is the only real sign of engagement","Presence comes in many forms — most invisible to those only looking for raised hands","Engaged students are always the loudest"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Presence came in many forms — and most of them were invisible to people who were only looking for raised hands.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][6].push({
  id:"l4.7s3", levelId:4, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Seed Bank", emoji:"🌾", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:288, readMins:3,
  blurb:"During a visit to a national seed bank, a school group learns why preserving plants that no one has heard of might be the most important work in the world.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The building looked unremarkable from the outside — a low structure surrounded by grassland on the edge of the countryside. But inside, in a series of vaults maintained at minus twenty degrees Celsius, was a collection of over two and a half billion seeds representing more than forty thousand plant species from every continent on Earth. The guide explained this calmly, as if these were ordinary numbers. The students stood listening, and several of them looked like they had not yet processed what they were being told.",
    "The purpose of the seed bank, the guide explained, was insurance. Not insurance against a particular disaster, but against the general unpredictability of the future. Many of the seeds held here came from plants that were now extinct in the wild — if the seeds were destroyed, those species would be gone entirely. Others came from plants that were currently common but might not be in fifty years, as land use, climate, and disease continued to shift.",
    "One student asked why it mattered if plants that nobody ate or used went extinct. The guide's answer was careful. She explained that we did not yet know which plants would turn out to be medically or agriculturally important — history was full of examples of plants that had been dismissed as insignificant and later found to contain compounds that led to important medicines. The question was not whether a plant was currently useful. It was whether we should make a permanent decision about its value on behalf of all future generations.",
    "Walking back to the coach, the student who had asked the question was quiet for a long time. Then he said, to nobody in particular, 'That's a different kind of question than I asked.'"
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "vaults":{def:"Secure, locked rooms used for storage.",pos:"noun"},
    "species":{def:"A group of living things that share the same characteristics.",pos:"noun"},
    "extinct":{def:"No longer existing anywhere in the world.",pos:"adjective"},
    "agriculturally":{def:"Relating to farming and growing food.",pos:"adverb"},
    "compounds":{def:"Chemical substances made of two or more elements.",pos:"noun"},
    "generations":{def:"All the people born and living at around the same time.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What is the main purpose of the seed bank?",options:["To sell rare seeds to scientists","To grow food in case of famine","To act as insurance against an unpredictable future by preserving plant species","To study how seeds grow in cold conditions"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The purpose of the seed bank was insurance... against the general unpredictability of the future.'"},
    {question:"Why are some seeds in the bank particularly critical?",options:["They are the oldest seeds in the world","They come from the rarest colours of flowers","They come from plants that are now extinct in the wild — the seeds are all that remain","They are needed for current farming"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Many of the seeds came from plants that were now extinct in the wild — if the seeds were destroyed, those species would be gone entirely.'"},
    {question:"How did the guide answer the student's question about unknown plants?",options:["She said they were not worth keeping","She said nature had its own balance and nothing was needed","We do not know which plants may be useful — history shows dismissed plants later proved medically important","She said the decision had already been made by scientists"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'History was full of examples of plants that had been dismissed as insignificant and later found to contain compounds that led to important medicines.'"},
    {question:"What did the student mean when he said 'That's a different kind of question than I asked'?",options:["He had asked a simple question but received a much larger, more philosophical answer","He felt the guide had ignored his question","He wanted to ask a different question","He thought the guide was wrong"],correct:0,
     feedback:"He had asked about practical usefulness; the guide answered about moral responsibility to future generations — a much bigger question."}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][6].push({
  id:"l4.7s4", levelId:4, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Understudy", emoji:"🎭", genre:"Art",
  wordCount:291, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When the lead actor in the school play falls ill the night before the performance, the understudy must step in — and discovers something about herself she hadn't known.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Paloma had learned every line of the play. She had attended every rehearsal, observed every blocking decision, and helped the lead actress, Greta, with her lines when they practised in the common room. Nobody had expected Greta to get ill. Greta had not missed a rehearsal in six weeks. But on the evening before the performance, Greta's mother called the drama teacher to say that Greta had a high fever and would not be able to perform.",
    "The drama teacher, Ms. Varga, called Paloma at nine o'clock that evening. Paloma's first response was a clear, calm 'yes' that surprised both of them. It was only after she had put the phone down that the feeling arrived — a cold, specific dread that settled in her chest and did not move for the rest of the evening. She knew the part. The question was whether she could actually perform it.",
    "The following afternoon, on stage, something happened that she had not predicted. The lights, the audience, the sound of quiet as she waited to enter — all of it was frightening, but the fear had a different quality from what she had imagined. It was sharpening rather than paralyzing. She was more alert than she had ever been in rehearsal. The first line came, and then the second, and then the play carried her forward the way a current carries something placed in it.",
    "Afterwards, a teacher she did not know well stopped her in the corridor and said she had been extraordinary. Paloma thanked her and continued walking, because she needed a few minutes alone before she could speak to anyone. She was trying to understand what had happened — how fear, at the right intensity, had turned into something she could only describe as clarity."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "understudy":{def:"An actor who learns another's part and replaces them if needed.",pos:"noun"},
    "blocking":{def:"The planned movements of actors on stage.",pos:"noun"},
    "dread":{def:"Strong fear about something that may happen.",pos:"noun"},
    "paralyzing":{def:"Causing someone to be unable to move or act.",pos:"adjective"},
    "sharpening":{def:"Making something clearer and more focused.",pos:"verb"},
    "intensity":{def:"The strength or degree of something.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How had Paloma prepared for the role she wasn't originally cast in?",options:["She had only read the script once","She had learned all the lines and attended every rehearsal, helping Greta practise","She had designed the costumes","She had helped direct the other actors"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Paloma had learned every line of the play... attended every rehearsal... helped the lead actress with her lines.'"},
    {question:"How did Paloma feel after saying 'yes' to performing?",options:["Excited and confident","Proud and ready","A cold, specific dread that settled in her chest","Relieved that she had been given the chance"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Only after she had put the phone down did the feeling arrive — a cold, specific dread that settled in her chest.'"},
    {question:"How was the fear Paloma felt on stage different from what she had imagined?",options:["It was much stronger than expected","It disappeared as soon as the lights came on","It was sharpening rather than paralyzing — she was more alert","It only appeared when she forgot a line"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The fear had a different quality from what she had imagined. It was sharpening rather than paralyzing.'"},
    {question:"What was Paloma trying to understand after the performance?",options:["Why she hadn't been cast originally","How the audience had reacted","How fear, at the right intensity, had turned into clarity","Whether she wanted to act again"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was trying to understand what had happened — how fear, at the right intensity, had turned into something she could only describe as clarity.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][6].push({
  id:"l4.7s5", levelId:4, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Night Shift", emoji:"🌙", genre:"Daily Life",
  wordCount:289, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When school is cancelled due to heavy snow, Dara spends the day with her mother at work — and sees a part of her mother's life she had never noticed.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The school closure was announced before six in the morning. Dara, who had been awake anyway, heard her mother moving quietly in the kitchen and went downstairs. Her mother was a nurse, and her shift started at seven regardless of snow. 'You can come with me,' her mother said, without much preamble. 'You'll have to stay in the family room. But it's better than being home alone all day.' Dara had no objection. She had never seen where her mother worked.",
    "The family room was a small, comfortable space near the ward entrance, used by relatives during long waits. Dara sat there for most of the morning with a book, a thermos of tea her mother had made, and the sounds of the corridor — footsteps that moved with purpose, occasional announcements over the intercom, trolleys. Twice her mother passed the glass window and waved without stopping.",
    "At lunchtime, her mother sat with her for twenty minutes in the family room, eating quickly from a container she had prepared the evening before. She talked about two patients — not by name, but in terms of situations — and Dara listened without speaking much. What struck her was not the clinical detail but the way her mother talked: careful, contained, and with a steadiness that suggested she had held much more difficult conversations than this one.",
    "On the drive home, Dara asked how her mother did it every day. Her mother thought for a moment and said, 'You get used to the difficult parts and you stay grateful for the good ones.' She paused. 'It's not that complicated, really.' Dara looked out at the white fields and thought that it probably was, and that the simplicity of the answer was a kind of strength in itself."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "preamble":{def:"An introduction before the main part of a conversation.",pos:"noun"},
    "ward":{def:"A large room in a hospital for patients.",pos:"noun"},
    "intercom":{def:"A communication system used in buildings.",pos:"noun"},
    "clinical":{def:"Relating to medical treatment of patients.",pos:"adjective"},
    "contained":{def:"Controlled and calm, not showing strong emotion.",pos:"adjective"},
    "thermos":{def:"An insulated container that keeps drinks hot or cold.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did Dara's mother still go to work despite the snow?",options:["She didn't know school was cancelled","She needed the extra pay","Her shift started at seven regardless","She enjoyed working in the snow"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Her shift started at seven regardless of snow.'"},
    {question:"What surprised Dara about the way her mother spoke about patients at lunchtime?",options:["Her mother shared too many personal details","The clinical details were frightening","Not the detail, but the steadiness and careful, contained way her mother spoke","Her mother seemed unhappy about her job"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'What struck her was not the clinical detail but the way her mother talked: careful, contained, and with a steadiness.'"},
    {question:"How did Dara's mother explain how she managed difficult parts of the job?",options:["By separating work and home life completely","By talking about it with colleagues","By getting used to the difficult parts and staying grateful for the good ones","By focusing only on the positive moments"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'You get used to the difficult parts and you stay grateful for the good ones.'"},
    {question:"What did Dara think about her mother's simple answer?",options:["She agreed it was not complicated","She thought her mother was avoiding the real question","She thought it probably was complicated, and that the simplicity of the answer was a kind of strength","She was confused by the answer"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Dara thought that it probably was, and that the simplicity of the answer was a kind of strength in itself.'"}
  ]
});


