STORIES[4][9].push({
  id:"l4.10s1", levelId:4, subLevel:10,
  title:"The Science of Trust", emoji:"🔬", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:337, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Researching the psychology of trust for a school project, Leila finds herself questioning what she thought she knew about her own relationships.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Leila's extended research project required her to choose a topic from a prescribed list and produce a structured investigation over six weeks. She chose 'the psychology of trust' because it sounded manageable and because she had some vague sense of being interested in why people trusted each other. She expected to find clear answers. The research produced something more complicated.",
    "The first thing she encountered was the distinction between different kinds of trust. Cognitive trust — the kind based on evidence and reliability — was different from affective trust, which was based on emotional connection and the sense of being cared for. Both mattered, but they operated differently: cognitive trust could be built through repeated demonstrations of reliability, while affective trust was often established more quickly and less rationally, and was more vulnerable to a single significant betrayal.",
    "She found research suggesting that people were often inaccurate about whom they trusted most — that self-report measures of trust did not always match behavioural indicators. People said they trusted person A more than person B, but when their behaviour was observed, they often shared more private information with person B, sought their advice more readily, or deferred to their judgement in ambiguous situations. The gap between stated trust and enacted trust was, apparently, normal and widespread.",
    "Leila thought about her own relationships as she read. She was quite certain she trusted her best friend most among her peers. But when she examined her recent behaviour more carefully — who she called when something went wrong, whose opinion she sought before making decisions, who she told things to before anyone else — the picture was less clear than she had expected. She had not previously thought of trust as something that might exist differently in her actions than in her stated beliefs.",
    "Her final report examined both the theory and her own reflection, and noted the irony that a project intended to be scientific had turned out to require as much personal honesty as academic analysis. She was not sure whether that made it more or less rigorous. Her teacher suggested it made it both."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "cognitive":{def:"Relating to thought and mental processes.",pos:"adjective"},
    "affective":{def:"Relating to feelings and emotions.",pos:"adjective"},
    "betrayal":{def:"An act of breaking someone's trust.",pos:"noun"},
    "deferred":{def:"Put off making a decision; accepted someone else's judgement.",pos:"verb"},
    "rigorous":{def:"Done with thorough care and accuracy.",pos:"adjective"},
    "enacted":{def:"Put into action; expressed through behaviour.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the key difference between cognitive trust and affective trust?",options:["Cognitive trust was about family; affective trust was about friends","Cognitive trust was built on evidence and reliability; affective trust on emotional connection","Cognitive trust was faster to build; affective trust was slower","They were essentially the same, used in different contexts"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Cognitive trust — based on evidence and reliability — was different from affective trust, based on emotional connection and the sense of being cared for.'"},
    {question:"What did research find about people's self-reported trust?",options:["People were very accurate about whom they trusted","People never knew whom they trusted most","Self-reported trust often did not match behavioural indicators — people's actions differed from their stated beliefs","Self-reporting was the most reliable method"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Self-report measures of trust did not always match behavioural indicators... the gap between stated trust and enacted trust was normal and widespread.'"},
    {question:"What did Leila discover when she examined her own behaviour carefully?",options:["She trusted her best friend most, as she had assumed","Her trust relationships were exactly as she had stated","The picture of who she actually turned to was less clear than she had expected","She discovered she had very few people she could trust"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'When she examined her recent behaviour... the picture was less clear than she had expected.'"},
    {question:"What irony did Leila note in her final report?",options:["Science is always less helpful than common sense","A scientific project had required as much personal honesty as academic analysis","Trust cannot be studied academically","Research always changes the thing being studied"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A project intended to be scientific had turned out to require as much personal honesty as academic analysis.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][9].push({
  id:"l4.10s2", levelId:4, subLevel:10,
  title:"The Architecture of a Street", emoji:"🏘️", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:336, readMins:3,
  blurb:"On a school project about urban design, Marcus begins to see the street he has walked every day for twelve years completely differently.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The urban design project asked students to choose a street in their local area and analyse how its physical features affected the behaviour of the people who used it. Marcus chose the street he lived on, partly because it was convenient and partly because he had assumed he already knew everything about it. The first observation session — just sitting on a wall and watching for forty-five minutes — showed him how wrong that assumption had been.",
    "He began to notice patterns he had not consciously registered. The wide pavement on the north side of the street meant that pedestrians naturally clustered there, while the narrower south side was used more transactionally — people passing through rather than stopping. The small café that had opened three years ago had, without him noticing, changed the character of the fifty metres around it: people slowed down, stopped to look at the menu, or paused to speak to someone they had recognised. A handful of ornamental trees — planted eight years ago, he discovered from council records — had created shade that made sitting on the low wall outside the post office feel inviting rather than exposed.",
    "The least-used section of the street, he found, was a stretch of about thirty metres that had no active frontage — no shops, no cafés, no building entrances. Just a long blank wall belonging to a car park. People walked faster through that section, and almost nobody stopped. He found research confirming this was a general urban pattern: blank frontages decreased pedestrian dwell time and increased the subjective sense of a space being unsafe.",
    "Marcus had walked down this street every day of his school life. He had never looked at it. He wrote in his conclusion: 'The built environment makes constant decisions about how we move and where we stop, and most of us experience those decisions without ever examining them.' His design teacher wrote in the margin: 'This is what urban design is. Well done for finding it.'",
    "Marcus went home and walked down his street again, slowly, looking at everything. It took twelve minutes instead of three. He thought he had been missing a great deal."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "frontage":{def:"The face of a building along a street.",pos:"noun"},
    "transactionally":{def:"In a way focused only on completing a task, without lingering.",pos:"adverb"},
    "dwell time":{def:"The amount of time a person spends in a particular place.",pos:"noun"},
    "ornamental":{def:"Decorative; used for beauty rather than function.",pos:"adjective"},
    "clustered":{def:"Gathered closely together in a group.",pos:"verb"},
    "pedestrian":{def:"A person travelling on foot.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did Marcus choose his own street for the project?",options:["It was the most interesting street in the area","His teacher suggested it","It was convenient and he assumed he already knew it well","It had recently been redesigned"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Partly because it was convenient and partly because he had assumed he already knew everything about it.'"},
    {question:"What effect had the café had on the street?",options:["It attracted only young people","It had made the area noisier","Without his noticing, it had changed the character of the fifty metres around it — people slowed, stopped, and paused","It had reduced the number of pedestrians"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The small café had, without him noticing, changed the character of the fifty metres around it.'"},
    {question:"Why did people walk faster through the blank-walled section of the street?",options:["It was downhill","Blank frontages decreased pedestrian dwell time and increased the subjective sense of unsafety","There was more traffic there","The pavement was narrower there"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Blank frontages decreased pedestrian dwell time and increased the subjective sense of a space being unsafe.'"},
    {question:"What was Marcus's main conclusion about the built environment?",options:["Streets should have more trees","Café owners should design streets","The built environment makes constant decisions about how people move, and most people never examine these","Urban design is only important in large cities"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The built environment makes constant decisions about how we move and where we stop, and most of us experience those decisions without ever examining them.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][9].push({
  id:"l4.10s3", levelId:4, subLevel:10,
  title:"The Last Fishing Season", emoji:"🎣", genre:"Nature",
  wordCount:336, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When the government announces new fishing restrictions, a coastal family must come to terms with the end of a way of life — and what that means for the next generation.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The announcement came in March: new quotas and zoning restrictions would take effect from the following October, substantially reducing the area where small-scale fishing boats could operate within fifteen kilometres of the coast. For families like Mira's, who had fished the same waters for three generations, it was not simply a change in regulation. It was, as her father said on the evening of the announcement, 'the end of something.'",
    "Mira was thirteen and had spent every summer aboard her father's boat since she was old enough to be trusted with a line. She understood the technical side of fishing — the tides, the species, the equipment — better than most of her classmates understood anything they had been formally taught. But she also understood, in a way she had not been able to articulate before the announcement, that this knowledge had a context. It made sense because it connected to a practice, and without the practice, the knowledge became historical rather than useful.",
    "Her father took the news with a quietness that she recognised as the kind he used when he was deciding how to think about something, rather than when he had already decided. Over several weeks, she watched him research the specifics of the new regulation, consult with other fishing families, and attend two local meetings. He did not rage against the restrictions — he understood, he said, why they existed. The fish stocks had been declining for a decade. Something had to change.",
    "What he mourned was not the loss of income, which could be replaced with difficulty, but the specific texture of a working life lived on the water — the quality of attention it required, the physical knowledge accumulated over years, the relationship with a place that was built through use rather than observation. 'You can visit the sea,' he told Mira. 'But we worked it. That's different.'",
    "Mira wrote about the season in a journal she kept that summer. She did not know what to conclude. She had been taught that conservation was necessary and that she agreed with it. She had also watched her father grieve something real. Both things, she found, could be true at the same time — and the difficulty of holding them together was not a reason to let go of either."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "quotas":{def:"Official limits on the amount of something that can be produced.",pos:"noun"},
    "zoning":{def:"Dividing land or sea into areas with specific allowed uses.",pos:"noun"},
    "articulate":{def:"To put something into clear words.",pos:"verb"},
    "mourned":{def:"Felt deep sadness about the loss of something.",pos:"verb"},
    "accumulated":{def:"Built up gradually over time.",pos:"verb"},
    "conservation":{def:"The protection of nature and natural resources.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How did Mira's father describe the impact of the restrictions on their family?",options:["A minor inconvenience they would adjust to","'The end of something'","An unfair government decision","An opportunity to try a new career"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'It was, as her father said, 'the end of something.''"},
    {question:"What did Mira realise about her fishing knowledge after the announcement?",options:["It was not very useful even while fishing","It would help her get a job in marine science","It made sense only in the context of the practice — without it, the knowledge became historical","It could easily be transferred to a different career"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'This knowledge had a context. It made sense because it connected to a practice, and without the practice, the knowledge became historical rather than useful.'"},
    {question:"What did Mira's father say he most mourned?",options:["The loss of income","The end of his boat","The specific texture of a working life on the water — the physical knowledge and relationship with place built through use","The relationships with other fishing families"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He mourned the specific texture of a working life lived on the water... the physical knowledge accumulated over years, the relationship with a place built through use.'"},
    {question:"What conclusion did Mira reach in her journal?",options:["Conservation should take priority over tradition","Fishing families should be given exceptions","Both the necessity of conservation and the reality of her father's grief could be true at the same time","The government had made the wrong decision"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Both things could be true at the same time — and the difficulty of holding them together was not a reason to let go of either.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][9].push({
  id:"l4.10s4", levelId:4, subLevel:10,
  title:"The Slow Reader", emoji:"📖", genre:"School",
  wordCount:335, readMins:3,
  blurb:"After years of struggling in English class, Dmitri discovers that reading slowly might actually be an advantage — if you're reading the right things.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Dmitri read slowly. This had been established early, noted by teachers, and addressed through various intervention programmes that had improved his speed without ever fully closing the gap between him and his faster classmates. He had made a quiet peace with being a slow reader: he accepted that he would not finish all the assigned texts in the time given, that he would sometimes miss discussion points because he had not reached the relevant passage, and that reading for pleasure was something that other people did more easily than him.",
    "In Year 9, a new English teacher set the class a different kind of task: a close reading exercise in which the students were given a single paragraph and forty minutes to write about everything they noticed in it. Dmitri was the first student to finish his written response. He was also, by the feedback he received, the student who had noticed the most.",
    "His teacher explained what had happened: slow readers, she said, were often close readers by necessity — they moved through text at a pace that required each word to arrive individually, which meant they registered details that faster readers absorbed collectively and then forgot. The skill that had been framed as a deficit was, in specific contexts, an advantage. It did not help with timed reading tests. It helped considerably with anything that required depth over speed.",
    "Dmitri did not become a fast reader. But he did, over the rest of that year, begin to think differently about what he was doing when he read. He had always experienced reading as something slightly effortful. He began to understand that the effort was producing something — an attention to language that his faster classmates did not necessarily share. His final English essay of the year was the most detailed piece of writing he had ever produced. He wrote it, as always, slowly.",
    "His teacher wrote at the end of it: 'This is what close reading looks like. Don't change the pace.' Dmitri kept the essay for a long time."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "intervention":{def:"An action taken to improve a situation.",pos:"noun"},
    "deficit":{def:"A lack of something; an area where something is missing.",pos:"noun"},
    "close reading":{def:"Reading carefully with attention to specific details and language.",pos:"noun"},
    "collectively":{def:"Together as a group; all at once.",pos:"adverb"},
    "effortful":{def:"Requiring a lot of effort.",pos:"adjective"},
    "passage":{def:"A section of a text.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How had Dmitri felt about being a slow reader before Year 9?",options:["He was proud of his reading style","He had made a quiet peace with it and accepted its limitations","He was determined to improve his speed","He thought his teachers were wrong about his ability"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'He had made a quiet peace with being a slow reader: he accepted that he would not finish all the assigned texts.'"},
    {question:"What happened during the close reading exercise?",options:["Dmitri struggled more than usual","He finished first and noticed the most — because slow reading had made him a close reader","He was last to finish but had the most interesting ideas","He skipped the task"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Dmitri was the first student to finish his written response... and had noticed the most.'"},
    {question:"How did his teacher explain why slow readers notice more?",options:["Slow readers have better memories","Slow reading gave each word time to arrive individually, registering details that faster readers absorbed collectively and forgot","Slow readers take more notes","Slow readers are generally more intelligent"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Slow readers moved through text at a pace that required each word to arrive individually... registering details that faster readers absorbed collectively and then forgot.'"},
    {question:"What did Dmitri understand about his effortful reading by the end of the year?",options:["That he needed to accept it as a weakness","That the effort was producing something — an attention to language his faster classmates didn't necessarily share","That close reading was not worth the extra time","That he should focus on other subjects instead"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'He began to understand that the effort was producing something — an attention to language that his faster classmates did not necessarily share.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[4][9].push({
  id:"l4.10s5", levelId:4, subLevel:10,
  title:"The Weather Observer", emoji:"🌤️", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:336, readMins:3,
  blurb:"After inheriting her great-uncle's weather notebooks, Sasha discovers that amateur observation over decades can reveal things that professional science has missed.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Her great-uncle had been recording the weather every morning for forty-one years. Not in a casual way — he had a standardised set of measurements: temperature, wind direction, precipitation in millimetres, cloud cover by type, and the time of the first bird call he heard each morning. He had recorded all of these in identical green notebooks, one per year, forty-one in total. When he died at eighty-seven, he left them to Sasha with a note that said only: 'These might be useful to someone who knows what to do with them.'",
    "Sasha was fifteen and studying biology and geography. She recognised that the notebooks were significant, but did not know in what direction. She contacted the meteorology department of a nearby university, attaching a scan of three sample pages from different decades. A researcher named Dr. Chen replied within two days. 'This is an unusual record,' she wrote. 'Most long-term amateur weather observation lacks the methodological consistency needed for research use. Your great-uncle's does not.'",
    "Working with Dr. Chen over several months, Sasha helped digitise the notebooks and build a dataset. The temperature records showed something that the regional meteorological stations — which had moved location twice and changed measurement equipment several times — had not clearly captured: a local warming trend in a specific valley microclimate that deviated from the regional average in ways that were consistent with a particular geographic feature. The observation was not world-changing, but it was the kind of specific, local detail that long-term datasets generated by professionals often smoothed away.",
    "Sasha was credited as a co-researcher on a short paper that Dr. Chen submitted to a journal. She read the paper several times, trying to understand all of it, and managed about seventy percent. What she understood completely was the acknowledgement section, which noted that the primary source was forty-one years of morning observations made by a retired teacher who had simply found the weather interesting.",
    "She put the forty-one green notebooks back in their box carefully. They had become, in the space of several months, something different from what they had been. They were the same notebooks. But now they had an audience, and a purpose, and a place in something larger than a single life."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "precipitation":{def:"Rain, snow, or other water that falls from the sky.",pos:"noun"},
    "methodological":{def:"Relating to the method or system used in research.",pos:"adjective"},
    "microclimate":{def:"The weather conditions specific to a small local area.",pos:"noun"},
    "digitise":{def:"To convert information into digital form for computer use.",pos:"verb"},
    "deviated":{def:"Differed from what is expected or normal.",pos:"verb"},
    "consistency":{def:"The quality of always doing or producing something in the same way.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What made Sasha's great-uncle's weather notebooks unusual for amateur records?",options:["They were written in Latin","They included photographs","They had methodological consistency that most amateur records lacked","They were the oldest known weather records in the region"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Most long-term amateur weather observation lacks the methodological consistency needed for research use. Your great-uncle's does not.'"},
    {question:"What did the notebooks reveal that professional meteorological stations had missed?",options:["A new storm pattern","A record-breaking temperature","A local warming trend in a valley microclimate that deviated from the regional average","An undiscovered weather phenomenon"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A local warming trend in a specific valley microclimate that deviated from the regional average in ways consistent with a particular geographic feature.'"},
    {question:"Why had professional stations missed this trend?",options:["They were not interested in local data","They had moved location and changed equipment several times, smoothing away local detail","Their data was not digitised","They only recorded temperature, not other measurements"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Regional meteorological stations had moved location twice and changed measurement equipment several times — the kind of specific local detail that long datasets generated by professionals often smoothed away.'"},
    {question:"What had the notebooks become by the end of the story?",options:["A museum exhibit","The basis of a major scientific discovery","Something larger — they had an audience, a purpose, and a place in something larger than a single life","Family heirlooms to be kept private"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'They had become something different... now they had an audience, and a purpose, and a place in something larger than a single life.'"}
  ]
});


