STORIES[5][1].push({
  id:"l5.2s1", levelId:5, subLevel:2,
  title:"The Rewilding Project", emoji:"🌿", genre:"Nature",
  wordCount:302, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When a rewilding scheme proposes reintroducing wolves to nearby farmland, Callum finds himself torn between two kinds of argument he cannot reconcile.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The proposal had come from an environmental charity: a rewilding initiative that would reintroduce a small population of wolves to a large area of upland farmland that had been purchased and would be managed as a nature reserve. The ecological argument was well documented. Wolves were a keystone species whose absence had caused observable cascade effects: without predators to regulate deer populations, overgrazing had degraded vegetation that streams, soil stability, and smaller species depended upon. Reintroduction, the charity argued, would restore these relationships.",
    "Callum's family farmed two kilometres from the edge of the proposed zone. His father had attended the public consultation meeting and returned describing it as 'a room full of people who don't live here telling people who do live here what's good for them.' This was, Callum thought, partly fair and partly unfair. The charity representatives had acknowledged that livestock losses were likely and proposed a full compensation scheme. But his father's objection was not primarily financial — it was about who had the right to change the conditions of a working landscape.",
    "Callum tried to think through both positions as honestly as he could. The ecological benefits of rewilding were supported by substantial evidence from similar projects in other countries. The concerns of farming communities were also legitimate — not simply as resistance to change, but as a genuine claim that the people most affected by a decision should have meaningful influence over it. Both of these things seemed to him to be true, and they did not resolve neatly into a single position.",
    "He wrote about it for an environmental studies assignment. His teacher appreciated the balance of the argument but noted that it didn't reach a conclusion. Callum wrote back that he thought the absence of a conclusion was itself a conclusion — that some decisions genuinely required ongoing negotiation rather than a settled answer, and pretending otherwise was its own kind of dishonesty."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "keystone species":{def:"A species whose presence is critical to maintaining the balance of an ecosystem.",pos:"noun"},
    "rewilding":{def:"Restoring land to its natural state, often including the return of native animals.",pos:"noun"},
    "cascade effects":{def:"A series of changes triggered by one event.",pos:"noun"},
    "negotiation":{def:"Discussion aimed at reaching an agreement.",pos:"noun"},
    "overgrazing":{def:"When animals eat vegetation faster than it can regrow.",pos:"noun"},
    "legitimate":{def:"Reasonable and justifiable; in accordance with rules or principles.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the ecological argument for reintroducing wolves?",options:["Wolves attract tourists","Wolves are endangered and need protection","Without wolves, deer overgraze and damage the vegetation that other species depend on","Wolves help control disease in deer populations"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Wolves were a keystone species whose absence had caused cascade effects: overgrazing had degraded vegetation that streams, soil stability, and smaller species depended upon.'"},
    {question:"What was Callum's father's primary objection to the scheme?",options:["He was worried about his financial losses","He didn't believe the ecological argument","His objection was about who had the right to change the conditions of a working landscape","He thought wolves were dangerous to people"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'His father's objection was not primarily financial — it was about who had the right to change the conditions of a working landscape.'"},
    {question:"Why couldn't Callum resolve the two positions into one conclusion?",options:["He had not done enough research","He was biased towards his father's view","Both the ecological evidence and farming communities' concerns seemed legitimately true, and they didn't resolve neatly","He thought the question was too political"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Both of these things seemed to him to be true, and they did not resolve neatly into a single position.'"},
    {question:"What did Callum argue to his teacher about his lack of conclusion?",options:["He needed more time to research","The assignment had not been clearly set","The absence of a conclusion was itself a conclusion — some decisions require ongoing negotiation rather than a settled answer","He would write a follow-up essay with a firmer position"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Some decisions genuinely required ongoing negotiation rather than a settled answer, and pretending otherwise was its own kind of dishonesty.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][1].push({
  id:"l5.2s2", levelId:5, subLevel:2,
  title:"The Training Partner", emoji:"🥋", genre:"Sport",
  wordCount:299, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When Sora's judo club gains a new member who is significantly stronger than anyone else, she discovers how the presence of someone much better changes how you train.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The new member arrived on a Thursday evening in November. His name was Anton, he was sixteen, and he was, as their coach explained matter-of-factly, a regional bronze medallist at under-73kg. Sora, who was fourteen and weighed considerably less, assumed this was broadly irrelevant to her training, since she would never be in his weight category and they were unlikely to be paired. She was corrected on this point within twenty minutes of his first session.",
    "Their coach believed in mixed-level randori — the free practice portion of a judo session where two players attempt throws on each other. 'You don't learn speed by training with someone slow,' she said, which was a philosophy Sora had heard before but whose implications she had not previously experienced at this level of disparity. Training with Anton was, for the first three weeks, an almost entirely educational experience in what did not work. Every approach she had, every grip, every entry to a throw — he read it, neutralised it, and countered with a control she could not escape.",
    "What changed, unexpectedly, was not Sora's technique. It was her timing. Forced to attempt things that had no chance of working through sheer strength or simple advantage, she began — through repetition and something close to desperation — to find the very small windows that existed between Anton's movements. Her coach noticed this and began to describe it in sessions: Sora, she said, was learning to see time differently.",
    "By spring, Sora had won two of her four competitions at her own level and placed second in a regional tournament. Her improvement was measurable and specific. In her competition post-match reviews, she noticed that the patterns she was exploiting in opponents were exactly the same small windows she had spent all winter failing to exploit in Anton. She sent him a brief message afterwards. He replied: 'I know. You got faster. I could feel it.'"
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "randori":{def:"Free practice in judo where both players attempt throws.",pos:"noun"},
    "disparity":{def:"A great difference between two things.",pos:"noun"},
    "neutralised":{def:"Prevented from having effect; cancelled out.",pos:"verb"},
    "implications":{def:"The possible effects or results of something.",pos:"noun"},
    "exploit":{def:"To make full use of an opportunity.",pos:"verb"},
    "entry":{def:"In martial arts: the initial movement to begin a throw.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did Sora initially think Anton's arrival was irrelevant to her training?",options:["She was already at a high level","She would never be in his weight category","She planned to move clubs","She didn't believe in mixed-level training"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She assumed this was broadly irrelevant to her training, since she would never be in his weight category.'"},
    {question:"What was the coach's philosophy about training with better partners?",options:["Safety should always come first","Students at the same level learn best from each other","You don't learn speed by training with someone slow","Advanced students should only train together"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'You don't learn speed by training with someone slow.'"},
    {question:"What unexpected improvement did Sora develop from training with Anton?",options:["Greater strength and power","Better defensive technique","Improved timing — learning to see and find the small windows between an opponent's movements","More aggressive throwing technique"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She began to find the very small windows that existed between Anton's movements... Her coach said she was learning to see time differently.'"},
    {question:"What did Sora notice in her competition reviews?",options:["She was stronger than before","She was using the same small windows against opponents that she had spent all winter trying to find in Anton","Her technique had changed completely","She was winning by strength rather than skill"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The patterns she was exploiting in opponents were exactly the same small windows she had spent all winter failing to exploit in Anton.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][1].push({
  id:"l5.2s3", levelId:5, subLevel:2,
  title:"The Memory Palace", emoji:"🏛️", genre:"School",
  wordCount:300, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Struggling to memorise large amounts of information for her history exam, Petra discovers an ancient technique — and what it reveals about how memory actually works.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The history exam required Petra to know dates, names, causes, consequences, and the connections between events spanning four hundred years. She had tried conventional revision methods — notes, flashcards, repeated reading — and found that the information refused to consolidate in a usable way. She knew she had read it. She could not retrieve it reliably under pressure. Her older brother mentioned, almost in passing, a memorisation technique called the memory palace.",
    "The method was ancient, originating with Greek and Roman orators who needed to recall long speeches without notes. It worked by associating pieces of information with specific locations in a familiar, imagined space — typically a house or building the user knew well. You 'placed' each piece of information in a specific room or at a specific point on a route through the building, and then recalled it by mentally walking through the space. The key was that the associations had to be vivid, surprising, or absurd — the more unusual the image, the more firmly it was retained.",
    "Petra used the floor plan of her school as her palace. She placed the causes of the First World War at the school entrance, the key events of the 1917 Russian Revolution at the main staircase, and the consequences of the Treaty of Versailles in the science corridor. Each piece of information became a strange, memorable image in a familiar place. The process of constructing the palace took three evenings. Retrieving the information afterwards felt, to her considerable surprise, almost effortless.",
    "She scored the highest mark of her school year in the history exam. But what remained with her afterwards was not the technique itself but the implication: memory was not simply a matter of how many times you had been exposed to something. It was a matter of how it had been encoded — what structure it had been attached to, and how distinctive that structure was. The brain, she concluded, was far more interested in place and story than in lists."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "consolidate":{def:"To make something stronger or more stable by combining elements.",pos:"verb"},
    "orators":{def:"People who are skilled at public speaking.",pos:"noun"},
    "encode":{def:"To convert information into a form suitable for memory or communication.",pos:"verb"},
    "retrieve":{def:"To find and bring back information from memory.",pos:"verb"},
    "vivid":{def:"Very clear and bright; producing strong mental images.",pos:"adjective"},
    "absurd":{def:"Completely unreasonable or ridiculous.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did conventional revision methods not work well for Petra?",options:["She did not spend enough time revising","The history course was too difficult","She could not retrieve the information reliably under pressure despite having read it","She was distracted during revision"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She knew she had read it. She could not retrieve it reliably under pressure.'"},
    {question:"What was the key to making the memory palace technique effective?",options:["Revising the associations every day","Placing information in alphabetical order","Making the images vivid, surprising, or absurd — the more unusual, the more firmly retained","Using a building you don't know well"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The associations had to be vivid, surprising, or absurd — the more unusual the image, the more firmly it was retained.'"},
    {question:"What did Petra use as her memory palace?",options:["Her own house","A building she had visited on a school trip","The floor plan of her school","An imaginary building she constructed"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Petra used the floor plan of her school as her palace.'"},
    {question:"What did Petra conclude about how memory works?",options:["Repetition is the most effective method","Memory depends on how information is encoded — what structure it's attached to — and the brain prefers place and story over lists","Visual learners naturally have better memories","The ancient methods are always the best"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Memory was a matter of how it had been encoded... The brain was far more interested in place and story than in lists.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][1].push({
  id:"l5.2s4", levelId:5, subLevel:2,
  title:"The Letter to the Editor", emoji:"📰", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:301, readMins:3,
  blurb:"After reading an article she finds badly argued, Margot writes her first letter to a newspaper — and discovers how much harder it is to write well than to criticise writing.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The article had appeared in the local newspaper under the headline 'Young People Don't Read Anymore.' It made several claims supported by no specific evidence and concluded that the decline of reading was causing a crisis in attention span and empathy. Margot, who was fifteen and read voraciously, found it infuriating — not only because she found it personally incorrect but because the argument itself was poorly constructed. She decided to write a letter to the editor.",
    "The first draft ran to four hundred words and was, she recognised on rereading it, mostly an expression of annoyance. It addressed the author's claims, but in a way that was reactive and somewhat aggressive. If someone else had written it, she would have described it as lacking rigour. She wrote a second draft.",
    "The second draft was better structured, but it occurred to her, midway through, that she was now in the position of criticising an argument for lacking evidence while also not providing much herself. She spent an afternoon looking up studies on reading habits in teenagers and found, to her slight surprise, that the picture was genuinely complicated: reading for pleasure had declined in certain demographics, while reading overall — including digital texts of various kinds — had increased in quantity if not in traditional literary forms. This was more nuanced than either the original article or her second draft had suggested.",
    "The third draft acknowledged the complexity, made a specific and evidenced counter-argument, and was three hundred words long. She submitted it. The newspaper published it, with minor edits, ten days later. Her English teacher, who had seen it in the paper, mentioned it at the start of class. Margot felt two distinct things: satisfaction at being published and a nagging sense that even the third draft had been less careful than the subject deserved. She began to think this was probably how good writers always felt."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "voraciously":{def:"With great enthusiasm and in large quantities.",pos:"adverb"},
    "rigour":{def:"The quality of being thorough and careful.",pos:"noun"},
    "demographic":{def:"A particular group of people defined by age, location, or other characteristics.",pos:"noun"},
    "reactive":{def:"Responding to events rather than thinking ahead.",pos:"adjective"},
    "counter-argument":{def:"An argument made against another argument.",pos:"noun"},
    "nagging":{def:"Continuing to bother someone; persistent.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why was Margot angry about the article?",options:["She had written a similar article that wasn't published","She found both the argument poorly constructed and its claims personally incorrect","She thought the newspaper had misquoted her","The article was about a topic she found boring"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'She found it infuriating — not only because she found it personally incorrect but because the argument itself was poorly constructed.'"},
    {question:"What was wrong with Margot's first draft?",options:["It was too short","It agreed with the original article","It was mostly an expression of annoyance — reactive and somewhat aggressive, lacking rigour","It used too much evidence"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'It was mostly an expression of annoyance... reactive and somewhat aggressive. She would have described it as lacking rigour.'"},
    {question:"What did Margot find when she actually researched reading habits?",options:["The original article was completely right","Young people read more than ever","The picture was genuinely complicated — pleasure reading had declined but overall reading had increased","There was no reliable data available"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Reading for pleasure had declined in certain demographics, while reading overall had increased in quantity... More nuanced than either the article or her second draft had suggested.'"},
    {question:"What did Margot think about even her final, published draft?",options:["She thought it was perfect","She felt it could have been more careful — and thought this was probably how good writers always felt","She was embarrassed it had been published","She wished she had written it differently from the start"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A nagging sense that even the third draft had been less careful than the subject deserved. She began to think this was probably how good writers always felt.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][1].push({
  id:"l5.2s5", levelId:5, subLevel:2,
  title:"The Translator's Dilemma", emoji:"🌐", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:302, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Researching a literary translation for a project, Iris discovers that every translation is also an interpretation — and that neutrality may be impossible.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The project asked students to compare two different translations of the same poem, originally written in Arabic, and analyse what differences they could find. Iris had never previously thought about translation as anything other than a technical exercise — the conversion of words from one language to another, more or less equivalent. By the end of the project, she had changed her mind completely.",
    "The two translations she worked with were from different decades and different translators. The original poem was a well-known piece about grief and memory. The first translation was spare and literal, using plain English vocabulary and maintaining the poem's short, compressed lines. The second used richer vocabulary, longer phrases, and occasionally imported images that were not in the original but that the translator had added — in a note — to convey what she described as 'the emotional register of the original in a way that literal equivalents could not.'",
    "Iris found both translations moving, but in different ways. The first felt distant and stripped-back; the second felt warmer and more immediately accessible. She read an essay by a translation theorist who argued that all translation involved choices, and choices always reflected the translator's own relationship with the text, the target audience, and the cultural moment in which the translation was made. 'There is no neutral translation,' the essay argued. 'There is only a translation made from a particular position, in a particular time, for a particular purpose.'",
    "This made Iris uncomfortable in a productive way. She had been taught to think of texts as having fixed meanings, and she had understood analysis as the process of uncovering those meanings. Translation revealed that even the text you were working from was already an interpretation. She wrote in her conclusion that this did not make reading pointless — it made it more demanding. Every text, she decided, needed to be held more lightly and questioned more carefully than she had previously thought necessary."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "literal":{def:"Following the exact meaning of a word or text.",pos:"adjective"},
    "spare":{def:"Using few words; without extra detail.",pos:"adjective"},
    "register":{def:"The style and tone of language used in a particular context.",pos:"noun"},
    "theorist":{def:"A person who develops or studies theories.",pos:"noun"},
    "stripped-back":{def:"Reduced to its simplest form; without decoration.",pos:"adjective"},
    "equivalent":{def:"Equal in value, amount, or meaning.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What had Iris originally thought translation was?",options:["An artistic and creative process","A political act","A technical exercise — the conversion of words, more or less equivalent","Something only experts could do well"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had never thought about translation as anything other than a technical exercise — the conversion of words from one language to another, more or less equivalent.'"},
    {question:"What was the key difference between the two translations?",options:["One was much longer than the other","One was in verse and one in prose","One was spare and literal; the other used richer vocabulary and added images to convey the emotional register","One was made by a native speaker and one was not"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The first was spare and literal; the second used richer vocabulary and occasionally imported images that were not in the original to convey the emotional register.'"},
    {question:"What did the translation theorist argue?",options:["Good translators can achieve a neutral translation","All translation is impossible","There is no neutral translation — only one made from a particular position, in a particular time, for a particular purpose","Literal translation is always the most honest"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'There is no neutral translation. There is only a translation made from a particular position, in a particular time, for a particular purpose.'"},
    {question:"What conclusion did Iris draw about reading texts?",options:["Fixed meanings can be uncovered with careful analysis","Translation should not be studied in schools","Every text needs to be held more lightly and questioned more carefully than she had previously thought","Translated texts are always less valuable than originals"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Every text needed to be held more lightly and questioned more carefully than she had previously thought necessary.'"}
  ]
});


