STORIES[5][2].push({
  id:"l5.3s1", levelId:5, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Overnight Hike", emoji:"⛺", genre:"Adventure",
  wordCount:316, readMins:3,
  blurb:"On a two-day wilderness hike with no phones allowed, a group of teenagers discovers that boredom is not the problem they expected it to be.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The no-phone rule had been the most discussed element of the overnight hiking trip. Several students had objected, not loudly but persistently, in the weeks before departure. Their objections were framed in practical terms — navigation, safety, communication with parents — but the organisers had prepared for each of these: group compasses, a satellite communicator for emergencies, and a scheduled check-in call at the midpoint. The practical arguments addressed, the objections continued at a lower volume, which suggested, the trip leader noted privately, that the real concern was something else.",
    "On the first afternoon, about three hours into the hike, the low-level restlessness that some students carried became visible. There was no screen to reach for. The pace of the hiking was too demanding for extended conversation. The landscape — a high moorland with long sightlines and very little shelter — was impressive but not constantly stimulating. Several students later reported that they had found the first four hours uncomfortable in a way they struggled to name.",
    "What happened after that was less easy to predict. The discomfort, rather than intensifying, began to recede. Students who had been quiet became more talkative. Conversations arose that the trip leader described, in her debrief notes, as having a different quality from ordinary group socialising — more sustained, less performance-oriented, as if the removal of the option to disengage electronically had produced a different kind of availability to each other.",
    "The second day was, by general agreement, a good one. Nobody performed well on their map-reading assessments, but several participants reported, in the written evaluations, that the trip had been among the most memorable experiences of their school year. When asked to explain this, most found it difficult. One student wrote: 'I think we were actually somewhere, instead of being somewhere and also somewhere else.' The trip leader kept this sentence. She used it in her pitch for next year's funding."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "persistently":{def:"Continuously; without stopping.",pos:"adverb"},
    "satellite communicator":{def:"A device that sends and receives signals via satellite.",pos:"noun"},
    "sightlines":{def:"The lines from which something can be seen without obstruction.",pos:"noun"},
    "debrief":{def:"A meeting to discuss a completed event or task.",pos:"noun"},
    "performance-oriented":{def:"Focused on how you appear to others.",pos:"adjective"},
    "recede":{def:"To move back or become less strong.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What were the students' practical objections to the no-phone rule?",options:["They needed phones for music","They were worried about the weight of other equipment","Navigation, safety, and communication with parents","They had previously had bad experiences on trips"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Their objections were framed in practical terms — navigation, safety, communication with parents.'"},
    {question:"What happened to the students' discomfort during the first afternoon?",options:["It grew steadily worse throughout the day","It disappeared immediately after the first rest stop","It was uncomfortable for the first four hours and then began to recede","They distracted each other from it"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The discomfort, rather than intensifying, began to recede.'"},
    {question:"How did the conversations on the trip differ from ordinary socialising?",options:["They focused mainly on the landscape","They were shorter and less frequent","They were more sustained and less performance-oriented — removing electronic options produced different availability to each other","They were louder and more energetic"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'More sustained, less performance-oriented, as if the removal of the option to disengage electronically had produced a different kind of availability to each other.'"},
    {question:"How did one student describe why the trip had been memorable?",options:["'We were in a beautiful place with no distractions'","'We were actually somewhere, instead of being somewhere and also somewhere else'","'The challenge made us feel proud of ourselves'","'Working as a team taught us a lot'"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'I think we were actually somewhere, instead of being somewhere and also somewhere else.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][2].push({
  id:"l5.3s2", levelId:5, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Confidence Gap", emoji:"🎤", genre:"School",
  wordCount:317, readMins:3,
  blurb:"After research shows a persistent gap in confidence between boys and girls in her school, Zara tries to understand what produces it — and what can change it.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The student council had been given access to anonymised data from a school wellbeing survey, and Zara, who was working on the gender equality subcommittee, was asked to analyse a specific subset of the results. The question had been a simple one: 'How confident are you in your own abilities?' Across Year 9, the average confidence score for girls was notably lower than for boys, even in subjects where girls' academic results were higher. Zara had expected to find this — she had read about it — but seeing it rendered numerically in her own school was different from knowing it abstractly.",
    "She spent two weeks reading research on the confidence gap. The literature was extensive and not entirely consistent, but several recurring themes emerged. Girls were more likely to attribute academic success to external factors — luck, a good teacher, working hard — while attributing failure to internal ones, such as not being smart enough. Boys showed the reverse pattern more frequently. This meant that the same outcome produced different beliefs about capability in different groups, which had consequences for which subjects were attempted, how risks were taken, and how criticism was responded to.",
    "What Zara found more useful than the diagnosis, however, were the interventions that had demonstrated measurable effect. Schools that had introduced structured opportunities for students to practise public risk-taking in low-stakes environments — presenting ideas that might be wrong, defending positions they were uncertain about — reported significant confidence gains in previously lower-confidence groups. The key element was not reassurance but practice in tolerating the specific discomfort of being visibly uncertain.",
    "She presented her findings to the student council and proposed three pilot activities for the following term. Two were implemented. In her end-of-year reflection, she noted that the most interesting part of the research was not the gap itself but the evidence that confidence was a skill rather than a trait — something that could be built through structured experience rather than simply felt or not felt. This reframing, she thought, was the most useful thing to communicate."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "anonymised":{def:"Made anonymous; with identifying information removed.",pos:"verb"},
    "attribute":{def:"To say that something is caused by a particular thing.",pos:"verb"},
    "subcommittee":{def:"A smaller group within a larger committee focused on a specific task.",pos:"noun"},
    "intervention":{def:"An action taken to improve a situation.",pos:"noun"},
    "reframing":{def:"Presenting or thinking about something in a new or different way.",pos:"noun"},
    "trait":{def:"A quality or characteristic of a person.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was surprising about the confidence data from Zara's school?",options:["Girls had lower confidence than boys even in subjects where girls' academic results were higher","Boys showed lower confidence in arts subjects","The data was the same for all year groups","Girls were less confident only in science subjects"],correct:0,
     feedback:"'The average confidence score for girls was notably lower than for boys, even in subjects where girls' academic results were higher.'"},
    {question:"How did the research describe the difference in how boys and girls attributed outcomes?",options:["Boys were more likely to attribute failure to luck","Girls attributed failure to external factors and success to internal ones","Girls attributed success to external factors (luck, teachers) and failure to internal ones (not being smart enough)","There was no consistent pattern found"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Girls were more likely to attribute academic success to external factors... while attributing failure to internal ones. Boys showed the reverse pattern more frequently.'"},
    {question:"What kind of school activities were shown to improve confidence in lower-confidence groups?",options:["Extra coaching in academic subjects","Solo work rather than group presentations","Structured practice in low-stakes risk-taking — presenting uncertain ideas, tolerating visible uncertainty","More praise and reassurance from teachers"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Schools that introduced structured opportunities for students to practise public risk-taking in low-stakes environments reported significant confidence gains.'"},
    {question:"What did Zara identify as the most useful insight from the research?",options:["That the confidence gap was larger than previously thought","That confidence is a skill that can be built through structured experience, not just a trait you have or don't","That girls need more support from teachers","That academic results are a better measure than confidence surveys"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Confidence was a skill rather than a trait — something that could be built through structured experience rather than simply felt or not felt.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][2].push({
  id:"l5.3s3", levelId:5, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Fossil Shore", emoji:"🦕", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:315, readMins:3,
  blurb:"On a geology field trip to a coastal cliff, Hanna holds a fossil 150 million years old — and begins to think about what deep time means for human-scale concerns.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The geology field trip involved a bus, a two-kilometre coastal walk in variable weather, and a cliff face of Jurassic limestone that the teacher, Mr. Osei, described as a 'very good section.' Hanna had brought the right equipment and the wrong expectations. She had anticipated a lesson that was essentially outdoor textbook work — identification, classification, note-taking. What she had not anticipated was the experience of holding a fossil.",
    "The ammonite she extracted from the soft shale was approximately twelve centimetres in diameter and in good condition. Mr. Osei dated it verbally to around 150 million years before the present. Hanna was familiar with this number as an abstract datum. Holding the fossil made it less abstract. The creature had been alive. It had moved through water. It had been buried, compressed, mineralised, and then eroded back to the surface over a period of time so long that the word 'long' did not adequately represent it. She turned it over in her hands and could not quite resolve this into ordinary thought.",
    "Mr. Osei gave a short informal talk at the cliff face about geological time scales. He used the analogy of compressing the Earth's history into a single calendar year: life did not appear until late summer; the dinosaurs arrived on 25th December and were gone by 30th; humans appeared in the final few seconds before midnight on 31st December. 'We are,' he said, 'in geological terms, a very new thing, with a very incomplete understanding of what new things usually do.'",
    "Hanna wrote about the field trip for her reflective journal. She found it difficult to connect the scale of geological time to the scale of ordinary life without the connection feeling either trivial or overwhelming. She settled on something in between: the fossil was a reminder that the world was not arranged around human concerns and did not run on human timescales. This was, she thought, either disturbing or liberating depending on when you happened to think about it."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "ammonite":{def:"An extinct sea creature with a coiled shell, now found as a fossil.",pos:"noun"},
    "mineralised":{def:"Turned into mineral material through geological processes.",pos:"verb"},
    "analogy":{def:"A comparison that helps explain something by linking it to something more familiar.",pos:"noun"},
    "geological":{def:"Relating to the science of the Earth's rocks and physical history.",pos:"adjective"},
    "eroded":{def:"Worn away gradually by natural forces.",pos:"verb"},
    "datum":{def:"A single piece of information (plural: data).",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What had Hanna expected from the geology field trip?",options:["Exciting discoveries of new species","An experience that would change how she thought","Essentially outdoor textbook work — identification, classification, note-taking","A chance to swim and explore the coast"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had anticipated a lesson that was essentially outdoor textbook work — identification, classification, note-taking.'"},
    {question:"What made the age of the fossil feel less abstract to Hanna?",options:["Mr. Osei's lecture about geological time","Seeing photographs of the Jurassic period","Holding the fossil and thinking about the living creature it had once been","Reading the age in her textbook"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Holding the fossil made it less abstract. The creature had been alive. It had moved through water.'"},
    {question:"What was Mr. Osei's analogy for human history in geological time?",options:["Humans as the last chapter of a book","Humans as a single sentence in a library","Compressing Earth's history into a year, with humans appearing in the final few seconds","Humans as the newest layer of rock"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Compressing Earth's history into a calendar year: humans appeared in the final few seconds before midnight on 31st December.'"},
    {question:"What dual feeling did Hanna have about geological time's scale?",options:["It made her feel proud of human achievement","It was either disturbing or liberating depending on when you happened to think about it","She found it only overwhelming","She thought it proved that humans are insignificant"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Either disturbing or liberating depending on when you happened to think about it.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][2].push({
  id:"l5.3s4", levelId:5, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Interview Panel", emoji:"💼", genre:"School",
  wordCount:318, readMins:3,
  blurb:"As part of a work experience programme, Theo must face an interview panel — and discovers that the preparation he did was not quite the preparation he needed.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The school's work experience programme included a mock interview conducted by a panel of two local employers. Theo had prepared thoroughly. He had researched the industry sector, written responses to common questions, and practised his answers with his older sister until she told him to stop. He was confident that he had covered the likely questions. He had not covered the interview itself.",
    "The two panellists were polite and professional. They asked him why he was interested in the field, what skills he thought he had to offer, and where he saw himself in five years. He answered all three from memory, delivering his prepared responses cleanly and accurately. Then the first panellist said, 'Those are good answers. Can you tell me which of those responses you actually believe?' Theo experienced a very specific kind of blankness — the failure not of memory but of contact. He had prepared for what to say. He had not prepared for the possibility that someone would ask him to distinguish between what he had said and what he meant.",
    "He recovered and gave a different, shorter, and considerably less polished answer to the underlying question. The panellists moved on. In the feedback afterwards, the first panellist said something Theo wrote down: 'Preparation is important. But in an interview, what we're looking for is the person behind the preparation. Don't be so prepared that you disappear.'",
    "Theo thought about this for several days. He had understood the purpose of the interview as a test of knowledge and presentation. The panellist was suggesting it was something else: an occasion when two people were trying to assess whether they could work with a third, and that this assessment depended on encountering something genuine. You could not prepare your way into being genuine. The preparation was necessary — but what it was supposed to reveal was real, and the real thing was not located in the preparation itself."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "panellists":{def:"Members of a group of people who ask questions in a formal setting.",pos:"noun"},
    "sector":{def:"A distinct part of an economy or field of activity.",pos:"noun"},
    "blankness":{def:"A state of having nothing to think of; mental emptiness.",pos:"noun"},
    "polished":{def:"Carefully prepared and very smooth in delivery.",pos:"adjective"},
    "genuine":{def:"Real and authentic; not pretend or performed.",pos:"adjective"},
    "distinguish":{def:"To recognise or point out a difference.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How had Theo prepared for the interview?",options:["He had not prepared at all","He had researched the industry, prepared responses, and practised answers with his sister","He had researched the company but not practised speaking","He had relied on his natural confidence"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'He had researched the industry sector, written responses to common questions, and practised his answers with his older sister.'"},
    {question:"What did the first panellist's follow-up question reveal?",options:["That Theo's answers were factually wrong","That Theo had not researched the field well enough","That Theo had prepared what to say but not prepared for being asked to distinguish it from what he actually meant","That the panellist was trying to confuse him"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had prepared for what to say. He had not prepared for the possibility that someone would ask him to distinguish between what he had said and what he meant.'"},
    {question:"What advice did the panellist give in the feedback?",options:["Prepare more thoroughly for common questions","'Don't be so prepared that you disappear'","Focus more on body language and eye contact","Research the company more specifically"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Don't be so prepared that you disappear.'"},
    {question:"What did Theo conclude about the true purpose of an interview?",options:["It is mainly a test of knowledge","It is about making the right first impression","It is an occasion for people to assess whether they can work with someone — and this requires encountering something genuine","It is mostly about formal presentation skills"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Two people were trying to assess whether they could work with a third, and that assessment depended on encountering something genuine.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][2].push({
  id:"l5.3s5", levelId:5, subLevel:3,
  title:"The Unfinished Symphony", emoji:"🎼", genre:"Art",
  wordCount:316, readMins:3,
  blurb:"While studying Schubert's Unfinished Symphony, Maya begins to wonder whether a work of art needs to be complete to be valuable.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The piece was called the Unfinished Symphony not as a description of a planned state but as a historical fact: Franz Schubert had written two movements of what would have been a four-movement symphony and then stopped. Musicologists had spent two centuries debating why. Some argued he had lost interest; others that he considered it complete in the two-movement form; others still that illness or other demands had simply intervened. The mystery was part of the piece's identity now, whether it would have been or not.",
    "Maya was listening to a recording of it for a music history assignment and found, unexpectedly, that the open-endedness of the piece affected how she heard it. The second movement ended without the resolution a four-movement structure would normally provide. There was no concluding gesture, no harmonic arrival, no sense of problems definitively solved. And yet the piece did not feel unresolved to her — it felt suspended, which was different. Suspension implied that something was being held, not abandoned.",
    "She had been taught that good writing needed a conclusion, that arguments required resolution, and that narratives needed endings. These seemed, in the context of the symphony, like conventions rather than requirements. The Unfinished Symphony had been performed and appreciated continuously for two hundred years without ever providing the ending its title promised. Perhaps the expectation of completion was a convention of a particular kind of thinking, rather than a universal principle of what it meant for something to be finished.",
    "Maya wrote about this in her music assignment, then crossed it out and wrote it again more carefully, because she was not sure the argument held in all cases and did not want to claim more than she could support. Her music teacher gave her a high mark and wrote: 'This is a good argument. Notice that you revised it to make sure it was accurate. That caution is itself the right response to a piece that resists resolution.' Maya read this note several times."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "musicologists":{def:"Scholars who study the history and theory of music.",pos:"noun"},
    "harmonic":{def:"Relating to the notes that sound pleasant together in music.",pos:"adjective"},
    "suspension":{def:"In music: a note held over into the next chord; here also: a state of being held without resolution.",pos:"noun"},
    "convention":{def:"A generally accepted way of doing something.",pos:"noun"},
    "resolution":{def:"In music: the movement from tension to a restful ending; generally: the settling of something.",pos:"noun"},
    "definitively":{def:"In a final, conclusive way.",pos:"adverb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why is Schubert's symphony called 'Unfinished'?",options:["The composer chose not to title it","He deliberately wrote only two movements as a statement","He wrote two movements and then stopped, leaving it historically incomplete","The manuscript was lost and only two movements were found"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Schubert had written two movements of what would have been a four-movement symphony and then stopped.'"},
    {question:"How did Maya describe the feeling of the second movement's ending?",options:["Abrupt and disappointing","Sad and unresolved","Suspended rather than unresolved — something held, not abandoned","Peaceful and complete"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The piece did not feel unresolved to her — it felt suspended, which was different. Suspension implied that something was being held, not abandoned.'"},
    {question:"What broader question did the symphony raise for Maya?",options:["Whether classical music was relevant today","Whether Schubert was a great composer","Whether the expectation of completion is a convention of a particular kind of thinking rather than a universal principle","Whether music or writing was a higher art form"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Perhaps the expectation of completion was a convention of a particular kind of thinking, rather than a universal principle of what it meant for something to be finished.'"},
    {question:"What did Maya's teacher say her careful revision demonstrated?",options:["That she had been uncertain about her argument","That she should have been more confident","That caution in revising an argument is itself the right response to a piece that resists resolution","That she should write more boldly next time"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'That caution is itself the right response to a piece that resists resolution.'"}
  ]
});


