STORIES[5][3].push({
  id:"l5.4s1", levelId:5, subLevel:4,
  title:"The Wildfire Season", emoji:"🔥", genre:"Nature",
  wordCount:332, readMins:3,
  blurb:"After wildfires destroy forests near her grandmother's home, Aiko struggles to write a school essay about climate change that feels honest rather than performative.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The fires had burned for three weeks in August. Aiko had followed the news from her home city, two hundred kilometres away, watching satellite images of the smoke plume and sending messages to her grandmother, who refused to evacuate until the second advisory notice. The forest her grandmother walked in most mornings — a place Aiko had known since she was very small — was substantially gone by the time the rains came. The house was untouched. The landscape was not the same place.",
    "When her English teacher set an essay on climate change in September, Aiko found herself unable to write it in the register she was expected to use. The essay guidelines called for a structured argument, evidence, and a clear conclusion. All of this was available to her — she had read extensively, and she could construct the argument. What she could not do was write about it in the detached, academic way the format required while simultaneously holding the knowledge of what the summer had actually felt like.",
    "She wrote a version of the essay that was correct in all formal respects and handed it in. Her teacher gave it a reasonable mark and wrote: 'Clearly argued, but slightly flat — I'd like to see more of your voice.' Aiko did not know what to make of this. Her 'voice' was exactly what she had excluded from the essay, because it seemed wrong to make climate change personal in an academic context. She reread the feedback and concluded that the teacher had noticed the absence of something she had deliberately removed.",
    "She went to discuss it with her teacher during a free period. The conversation was useful: her teacher explained that 'voice' did not necessarily mean emotional disclosure, but rather a quality of genuine engagement with the material — the sense that the writer was thinking, not just assembling. Aiko wrote a second version that integrated what she knew analytically with a single, careful paragraph about the summer. It was not a personal essay. But it was, her teacher said, alive.",
    "She thought about the difference between the two versions for a long time afterwards. The first had been correct. The second had been true. She had not previously understood that these were different things."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "performative":{def:"Done for show or to make an impression, rather than genuinely felt.",pos:"adjective"},
    "register":{def:"The style and tone appropriate to a particular context.",pos:"noun"},
    "detached":{def:"Not emotionally involved; objective.",pos:"adjective"},
    "disclosure":{def:"The sharing of private information.",pos:"noun"},
    "analytically":{def:"Using logical analysis and careful reasoning.",pos:"adverb"},
    "plume":{def:"A long column or cloud of smoke or other substance.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why couldn't Aiko write the essay in the required academic register?",options:["She had not done enough research","The essay guidelines were too restrictive","She could not write in a detached way while simultaneously holding the personal experience of the summer's fires","She disagreed with the essay topic"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She could not write about it in the detached, academic way the format required while simultaneously holding the knowledge of what the summer had actually felt like.'"},
    {question:"What feedback did her teacher give on the first essay?",options:["'Excellent — very well argued'","'Too emotional and personal'","'Clearly argued, but slightly flat — I'd like to see more of your voice'","'Good but needs more evidence'"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Clearly argued, but slightly flat — I'd like to see more of your voice.'"},
    {question:"What did the teacher mean by 'voice'?",options:["Personal emotions and disclosures","Using a less formal writing style","A quality of genuine engagement — the sense that the writer was thinking, not just assembling","More direct opinions about climate policy"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Voice did not necessarily mean emotional disclosure, but rather a quality of genuine engagement — the sense that the writer was thinking, not just assembling.'"},
    {question:"What distinction did Aiko make between her two versions?",options:["The first was longer; the second was better structured","The first used more evidence; the second used more opinion","The first was correct; the second was true","The first was emotional; the second was academic"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The first had been correct. The second had been true. She had not previously understood that these were different things.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][3].push({
  id:"l5.4s2", levelId:5, subLevel:4,
  title:"The Night Runner", emoji:"🌃", genre:"Sport",
  wordCount:331, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When insomnia turns his nights sleepless, Marco starts running at 2am — and finds that the city at night is an entirely different world.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Marco's insomnia had started in November, without obvious cause. He would lie awake until two or three in the morning, surface into a shallow, unsatisfying sleep, and wake early with the particular exhaustion of someone who has rested without recovering. His doctor had suggested standard sleep hygiene advice: consistent sleep times, no screens after ten, reduced caffeine. He had tried most of these, with limited effect.",
    "The running started by accident. On a sleepless Wednesday night, unwilling to spend another hour looking at the ceiling, he put on trainers and went outside at 2:15am. He lived in a medium-sized city and had assumed the streets would be empty. They were not. There were delivery drivers, a group of hospital workers beginning or ending a shift, a man walking a dog with a deliberateness that suggested this was a long-established habit, and one other runner, going the other way, who raised a hand without slowing. Marco found himself running faster than usual, partly because the cold air required it and partly because the unfamiliar quality of the city — familiar roads made strange by the absence of the daytime crowd — made him want to cover more of it.",
    "He ran for forty minutes, returned home, and slept for four hours without interruption. This was, by his recent standards, excellent. He ran again the following night, and the night after that. The insomnia did not immediately resolve, but the nights became less something to be endured and more something to be used. He found himself running six nights out of seven, which was more exercise than he had done at any point in his life.",
    "The city at 2am was, he found, a specific and interesting place. It contained evidence of everything that happened when most people were not watching: the logistics of supply chains, the continuity of essential services, the particular community of people for whom night was ordinary time rather than exceptional time.",
    "By March, his sleep had improved substantially. The night running had become, independently of the insomnia, something he did not want to stop. He had found something in a problem that he intended to keep after the problem was gone."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "insomnia":{def:"Persistent difficulty in falling or staying asleep.",pos:"noun"},
    "hygiene":{def:"Here: practices that support a healthy routine.",pos:"noun"},
    "logistics":{def:"The organisation and management of moving goods.",pos:"noun"},
    "deliberateness":{def:"The quality of doing something carefully and with intention.",pos:"noun"},
    "endured":{def:"Experienced something difficult or unpleasant without giving up.",pos:"verb"},
    "continuity":{def:"The state of continuing without interruption.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What started Marco's night running?",options:["A doctor's recommendation","A training programme for a race","Unable to sleep one Wednesday night, he put on trainers and went outside at 2:15am","A friend suggested it as a cure for insomnia"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'On a sleepless Wednesday night, unwilling to spend another hour looking at the ceiling, he put on trainers and went outside at 2:15am.'"},
    {question:"What surprised Marco about the city at 2am?",options:["It was completely empty and silent","It was noisier than expected","The streets were not empty — they contained delivery drivers, hospital workers, and others for whom night was ordinary time","It felt more dangerous than he expected"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had assumed the streets would be empty. They were not.' — delivery drivers, hospital workers, and others were present."},
    {question:"What effect did the first night run have on his sleep?",options:["None — he stayed awake for the rest of the night","He slept for four hours without interruption, which was excellent by his recent standards","He slept for twelve hours and was late for school","He felt worse the next day"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'He slept for four hours without interruption. This was, by his recent standards, excellent.'"},
    {question:"What did Marco decide by March?",options:["He would stop running once his sleep was better","Night running was too disruptive to his schedule","He had found something in a problem that he intended to keep after the problem was gone","He would start running during the day instead"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had found something in a problem that he intended to keep after the problem was gone.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][3].push({
  id:"l5.4s3", levelId:5, subLevel:4,
  title:"The Heritage Language", emoji:"🏠", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:334, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Growing up speaking her parents' language only at home, Lena discovers that her relationship with that language is stranger and more interesting than she had realised.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Lena's parents had come from Poland before she was born, and the language of the household was Polish. Outside, everything was English. She had never experienced this as unusual — it was simply how things were — and had not thought of herself as bilingual in any particularly significant sense. She could communicate comfortably in both languages, though her Polish was, she knew, different from the Polish of people who had lived their whole lives in Poland: slightly old-fashioned in some respects, missing certain contemporary references, and confined, in emotional register, to the particular contexts it had always been used in.",
    "This last point became clearer to her in Year 10, when a sociolinguistics unit mentioned the concept of heritage language — a language learned at home from immigrant parents, maintained through family use rather than formal education. Heritage speakers, her teacher explained, often had a distinctive relationship with the language: strong in spoken fluency and emotional resonance, less strong in formal writing and specialist vocabulary, and occasionally disorienting in the experience of returning to the 'home' country where the language was public rather than private.",
    "Lena recognised her own experience in all of these descriptions, but the one that stayed with her was the last. She had visited Poland twice, and on both occasions had found her Polish — which felt entirely natural at home — placed in a context that made its specific character visible. The phrases she used were her parents' phrases. The register she operated in was the register of family, domesticity, and emotion. It was not the register of streets, offices, and public argument. She was, in Poland, fluent and slightly foreign simultaneously.",
    "She wrote about this for a sociology extended essay, and the process of writing helped her articulate something she had only previously felt: that a language is not just a system of communication but a container for a particular life, and that the life it contained in her case was the specific life her family had brought with them and maintained, which was a version of Poland that existed, fully formed, in a house in Birmingham.",
    "She felt, writing this, something that was not quite sadness and not quite pride. It was something that required both languages to name properly, and even then she was not sure she had found exactly the right words."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "sociolinguistics":{def:"The study of how language relates to society and culture.",pos:"noun"},
    "heritage language":{def:"A language spoken at home but not the dominant language of the wider society.",pos:"noun"},
    "resonance":{def:"A quality of evoking strong feelings or memories.",pos:"noun"},
    "domesticity":{def:"The activities and experiences of home life.",pos:"noun"},
    "disorienting":{def:"Causing confusion about where or who you are.",pos:"adjective"},
    "fluency":{def:"The ability to speak or write a language easily and accurately.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How did Lena's Polish differ from that of people who grew up in Poland?",options:["She was less fluent in speaking","Her Polish was old-fashioned in some respects and confined to the emotional registers of family life","She had a strong accent that stood out","She only knew formal Polish from reading"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Her Polish was slightly old-fashioned in some respects, missing certain contemporary references, and confined, in emotional register, to the particular contexts it had always been used in.'"},
    {question:"What is a 'heritage language' as explained in her school unit?",options:["A language from an ancient civilisation","A language that has died out and been reconstructed","A language learned at home from immigrant parents, maintained through family use","A language that is officially protected"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A language learned at home from immigrant parents, maintained through family use rather than formal education.'"},
    {question:"What did visiting Poland reveal about Lena's Polish?",options:["That it was perfectly standard and natural","That it was better than she had thought","That she was fluent but slightly foreign simultaneously — her Polish was the register of family and home, not public life","That she had forgotten most of it"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was, in Poland, fluent and slightly foreign simultaneously.' Her language was private-register Polish, not public-register Polish."},
    {question:"What did Lena conclude about what a language really is?",options:["A system of grammar and vocabulary","A tool for efficient communication","A container for a particular life — in her case, a version of Poland maintained within a house in Birmingham","A marker of cultural identity that should be preserved"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A language is not just a system of communication but a container for a particular life.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][3].push({
  id:"l5.4s4", levelId:5, subLevel:4,
  title:"The Experiment Fails", emoji:"🧪", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:330, readMins:3,
  blurb:"When her carefully designed biology experiment produces results that contradict her hypothesis, Jess must decide what to do with evidence she didn't expect.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The experiment had been designed over three weeks. Jess's hypothesis was that plants grown under blue light wavelengths would show measurably faster growth rates than those grown under red wavelengths, based on research suggesting blue light stimulated more compact, vigorous growth. She had designed the methodology carefully, controlled for variables as thoroughly as the school lab environment permitted, and set up sixteen pots across four conditions. When she began collecting data in week four, the results were not what she expected.",
    "The plants under blue light were not growing faster. Two of the four groups showed negligible differences. The third showed slight red-light advantage, and the fourth — which she had intended as a control — had produced the fastest growth of all, which made no immediate sense. She checked her methodology for errors. She re-measured. She recalculated. The numbers were what they were.",
    "Her first instinct was to wonder whether she had made a mistake significant enough to invalidate the experiment. Her second, harder instinct was to consider whether the results might simply be correct — and if so, what they meant. She read further and found that the relationship between light wavelength and plant growth was substantially more complex than the simplified version she had encountered in the introductory literature: growth rate varied by species, growth stage, intensity, and the ratio of wavelengths present, among other factors. Her experiment had not been wrong, precisely. It had been underpowered and undercontextualised.",
    "She wrote her results section honestly, reporting what she had found and acknowledging that it contradicted her hypothesis. In the discussion, she explained why the results might have come out as they did and what a more rigorous experiment would have required. Her teacher gave her the highest mark in the class. 'A lot of students,' she wrote in the feedback, 'would have quietly adjusted their data. What you did instead is what scientists actually do: report what you found and understand why it might be.'",
    "Jess kept the feedback and thought about it. The experiment had failed to prove what she expected. It had produced something more interesting: a lesson in how much complexity a simple hypothesis conceals."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "hypothesis":{def:"A proposed explanation that can be tested by experiment.",pos:"noun"},
    "methodology":{def:"The system of methods used in research.",pos:"noun"},
    "negligible":{def:"Too small or unimportant to be worth considering.",pos:"adjective"},
    "invalidate":{def:"To make something not valid or effective.",pos:"verb"},
    "underpowered":{def:"Here: not large or controlled enough to produce reliable results.",pos:"adjective"},
    "wavelength":{def:"The distance between two peaks of a wave; different colours of light have different wavelengths.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was Jess's original hypothesis?",options:["Red light would produce faster plant growth","Blue light wavelengths would produce measurably faster plant growth than red","Plants grow best in natural light","Growth rate is not affected by light colour"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Her hypothesis was that plants grown under blue light wavelengths would show measurably faster growth rates than those grown under red wavelengths.'"},
    {question:"What was most puzzling about Jess's results?",options:["All the plants died","The red light produced faster growth","The control group — which shouldn't have been the fastest — produced the fastest growth of all","The data was impossible to measure"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The fourth — which she had intended as a control — had produced the fastest growth of all, which made no immediate sense.'"},
    {question:"What did further reading reveal about her experiment?",options:["She had made a significant error in the methodology","The relationship between light wavelength and growth is far more complex than the simplified version she had encountered","Her hypothesis had been correct all along","The experiment was too small to produce any results"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The relationship between light wavelength and plant growth was substantially more complex than the simplified version she had encountered... Her experiment had been underpowered and undercontextualised.'"},
    {question:"Why did the teacher give Jess the highest mark?",options:["Because the experiment proved the hypothesis","Because her methodology was perfect","Because she reported honestly what she found and explained why it might be, rather than adjusting her data","Because the results were surprising and original"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A lot of students would have quietly adjusted their data. What you did instead is what scientists actually do: report what you found and understand why it might be.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][3].push({
  id:"l5.4s5", levelId:5, subLevel:4,
  title:"The Empty Seat", emoji:"🪑", genre:"Family",
  wordCount:333, readMins:3,
  blurb:"At her first family Christmas after her grandfather's death, Mara discovers that grief works differently in a crowd than it does alone.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The family gathered, as it always had, at her aunt's house on Christmas Day. There were sixteen people, which was the usual number, and the house was the usual house, and the food was largely the usual food, because her aunt was a consistent person who ran celebrations according to an established template. The main difference was that her grandfather was not there. He had died in April. Nobody had formally discussed how Christmas would go, but everyone seemed to have arrived having made the same private calculation: they would proceed as normally as possible, because the alternative was unclear.",
    "Mara had spent the months since April grieving in a way that was, she thought, reasonably well-managed — she had been sad at appropriate times, had spoken about her grandfather when it came up, and had found, by October, that she could think about him without the physical sensation in her chest that the earlier months had produced. She had assumed Christmas would be sad, and had prepared herself accordingly, with a quiet and private preparedness that she thought would be enough.",
    "It was not enough, but not in the way she had expected. What undid her was not the absence of her grandfather at the table — the empty chair had been anticipated, and she found she could look at it — but the presence of everything that continued unchanged. Her uncle's particular way of telling the same story, her younger cousins arguing about who had the largest Yorkshire pudding, the smell of the kitchen, the pattern on the tablecloth: all of it still the same, proceeding as if unchanged, which it was and was not, and the gap between those two things was where the grief was actually located.",
    "She went to the bathroom for ten minutes and came back. Nobody had noticed. At the end of the meal, her aunt said, 'Dad would have loved this,' and everyone agreed and then moved on. Mara found this unbearable and exactly right at the same time — the brevity of it, the fact that it had been said and then the dishes cleared and the games begun.",
    "She wrote about Christmas in her journal that night. She did not arrive at any conclusions about grief, because she did not think it was that kind of subject. She wrote until she had described it accurately, which was the most she could do."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "template":{def:"A pattern or model used repeatedly.",pos:"noun"},
    "preparedness":{def:"The state of being ready for something.",pos:"noun"},
    "brevity":{def:"The quality of being brief and short.",pos:"noun"},
    "anticipated":{def:"Expected in advance.",pos:"verb"},
    "unbearable":{def:"Too painful or difficult to endure.",pos:"adjective"},
    "grief":{def:"Deep sorrow caused by loss.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What approach had the family decided on for Christmas without discussing it?",options:["To cancel Christmas this year","To have a small, quiet gathering instead","To proceed as normally as possible","To each do their own thing separately"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'They would proceed as normally as possible, because the alternative was unclear.'"},
    {question:"Why was Christmas harder than Mara had prepared for?",options:["The empty chair was more painful than expected","The family talked too much about her grandfather","It was not the absence of her grandfather but the unchanged continuation of everything else that undid her","The meal was smaller than usual"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'What undid her was not the absence... but the presence of everything that continued unchanged... the gap between those two things was where the grief was actually located.'"},
    {question:"What did Mara find 'unbearable and exactly right at the same time'?",options:["The empty chair being left at the table","The brevity of her aunt's mention of their grandfather — said and then moved on","The family not discussing their grandfather at all","The family gathering in the same house as always"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Her aunt said 'Dad would have loved this,' and everyone agreed and then moved on. Mara found this unbearable and exactly right at the same time — the brevity of it.'"},
    {question:"What did Mara do in her journal that night?",options:["She wrote a letter to her grandfather","She wrote conclusions about how to manage grief","She wrote until she had described it accurately, which was the most she could do","She listed everything she missed about him"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She wrote until she had described it accurately, which was the most she could do.'"}
  ]
});


