STORIES[5][4].push({
  id:"l5.5s1", levelId:5, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Attention Economy", emoji:"🖥️", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:351, readMins:4,
  blurb:"After studying how digital platforms profit from capturing attention, Finn writes an essay that forces him to examine his own behaviour more honestly than he expected.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The phrase 'attention economy' described, Finn's media studies teacher explained, a particular economic model in which the commodity being traded was not a product or service but human attention — specifically, the time and cognitive engagement of users, which could then be sold to advertisers. The model was simple in structure: the more time a user spent on a platform, the more data could be collected about them, and the more precisely advertising could be targeted. The incentive for the platform was therefore to maximise engagement at all costs.",
    "This led, Finn read in several of the supporting articles, to a set of design decisions that were not in users' interests. Infinite scroll removed natural stopping points. Notification systems were calibrated to create a sense of urgency that was often unwarranted. Recommendation algorithms promoted content that generated strong emotional responses — outrage, fear, and desire being particularly effective — regardless of whether that content was accurate or beneficial to the user. The system was not, the articles argued, neutral technology: it was a set of deliberate choices made to extract as much attention as possible from as many people as possible.",
    "Finn found the argument persuasive and began his essay intending to make it clearly. About halfway through the first draft, he paused. He was making an argument about design decisions that exploited users without their full awareness. He was also someone who spent, he calculated honestly, about four hours a day on platforms operating exactly this model. The argument he was making was about other people, described with a slight distance that implied he was observing a problem rather than participating in it.",
    "He rewrote the essay in the first person. He kept the analytical framework intact but inserted, at appropriate points, honest acknowledgements of his own use: the specific experience of the infinite scroll; the way a notification could redirect his attention from sustained work; the occasions on which he had shared content that produced a strong reaction without checking its accuracy. The essay was more uncomfortable to write in this form. It was also, he thought, more honest.",
    "His teacher gave him the highest mark of the term and said, in the written feedback: 'You did something unusual here — you included yourself in the analysis. This is what makes an argument about media more than academic exercise.' Finn read this and acknowledged, privately, that the most useful part of the essay had been the part that was most difficult to write."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "commodity":{def:"A thing of value that can be bought and sold.",pos:"noun"},
    "calibrated":{def:"Adjusted carefully to produce a particular result.",pos:"verb"},
    "unwarranted":{def:"Not justified or necessary.",pos:"adjective"},
    "outrage":{def:"A strong feeling of anger caused by something unfair.",pos:"noun"},
    "analytical":{def:"Using careful reasoning and detailed examination.",pos:"adjective"},
    "extract":{def:"To remove or take out, especially by effort.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What is the core model of the 'attention economy'?",options:["Selling products directly to users based on their interests","Charging users subscription fees to access content","Trading human attention — platforms sell user time and engagement to advertisers","Creating the most entertaining content possible"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The commodity being traded was not a product or service but human attention — which could then be sold to advertisers.'"},
    {question:"What design decisions did the articles identify as harmful to users?",options:["Too many advertisements per page","Poor visual design","Infinite scroll, notifications calibrated to create urgency, and algorithms promoting emotionally strong content regardless of accuracy","Making platforms too addictive through interesting content"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Infinite scroll removed natural stopping points. Notification systems created unwarranted urgency. Algorithms promoted outrage and fear regardless of accuracy.'"},
    {question:"Why did Finn pause halfway through his first draft?",options:["He couldn't find enough evidence for his argument","He realised his essay was too long","He noticed he was arguing about others as if he were a detached observer, when he himself spent four hours a day on these platforms","He disagreed with the articles he had read"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He was making an argument about design decisions that exploited users... He was also someone who spent about four hours a day on platforms operating exactly this model.'"},
    {question:"What made the final essay more honest?",options:["He added more academic references","He removed personal examples to be more objective","He rewrote in the first person and included honest acknowledgements of his own behaviour","He chose a clearer structure"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He rewrote the essay in the first person... inserted honest acknowledgements of his own use.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][4].push({
  id:"l5.5s2", levelId:5, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Return", emoji:"🏔️", genre:"Adventure",
  wordCount:349, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Three years after a mountain accident that changed her confidence entirely, Petra returns to the same mountain — not to conquer it, but to understand what she is actually afraid of.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The accident had not been dramatic in the way that accidents in films are dramatic. She had slipped on wet rock at a moderate altitude, fallen approximately three metres, and broken her wrist. She had been with an experienced guide, the descent was managed carefully, and she was at a hospital within four hours. By any external measure, the incident had been contained and manageable. By the measure of what happened inside her for the following three years, it had not been.",
    "The aftermath had taken a form she had not predicted. She had not become afraid of heights in general. She had not stopped hiking. What had happened was more specific and harder to name: a particular quality of hesitation that arrived whenever she was on exposed rock above a certain gradient, and that transformed the experience of technical terrain from something she had previously enjoyed into something she could complete but not relax into. She had, she told a friend, 'lost the thing where you trust your feet.'",
    "The return was her own idea, planned over several months. She went back to the same mountain, with a different guide, in dry weather in late summer. She was not attempting to prove anything — she was clear about this to herself and stated it explicitly to the guide, whose name was Elena and who had worked with several clients returning after injuries. Elena's approach was unhurried. They took longer than necessary on sections Petra found difficult. They stopped often. Elena did not offer reassurance of the generic kind — she gave specific, technical information: the quality of the rock, the angle of the gradient, the precise position of the next hold. This, Petra found, was more useful than encouragement, because it shifted her attention from the feeling to the actuality.",
    "She did not reach the summit. She had not intended to. She reached the point below the summit where the accident had occurred, stood there for ten minutes, and then turned around. The hesitation had been present throughout. It had not been absent for a moment. But she had experienced it and continued moving, which was different from the past three years of experiencing it and stopping.",
    "On the drive home, she decided she was not cured. She was functional. For the time being, she thought that was sufficient — and that the difference between cured and functional was one she had not previously been able to make."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "gradient":{def:"The steepness of a slope.",pos:"noun"},
    "exposed":{def:"In climbing: open and vulnerable, with no shelter or protection.",pos:"adjective"},
    "aftermath":{def:"The period following a difficult event.",pos:"noun"},
    "hesitation":{def:"A pause before doing something, due to uncertainty or fear.",pos:"noun"},
    "actuality":{def:"The reality of a situation.",pos:"noun"},
    "functional":{def:"Working well enough to do what is needed.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What specific fear did Petra develop after the accident?",options:["A general fear of heights","Fear of walking on any uneven surface","A particular hesitation on exposed rock above a certain gradient that removed her ability to relax in technical terrain","Fear of going outdoors in wet weather"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A particular quality of hesitation that arrived whenever she was on exposed rock above a certain gradient, and transformed technical terrain from something she had enjoyed into something she could complete but not relax into.'"},
    {question:"Why had Petra returned to the mountain?",options:["To prove she was no longer afraid","To reach the summit this time","Not to prove anything — but to understand what she was actually afraid of","To complete unfinished business with the mountain"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was not attempting to prove anything — she was clear about this to herself.'"},
    {question:"Why was Elena's technical information more useful to Petra than generic reassurance?",options:["Petra didn't trust encouragement from a stranger","Technical information made the route seem shorter","It shifted her attention from the feeling to the actuality","Elena was more experienced than the previous guide"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Elena gave specific, technical information... This shifted Petra's attention from the feeling to the actuality.'"},
    {question:"What distinction did Petra make on the drive home?",options:["Between being afraid and being brave","Between a good mountain and a difficult one","Between cured and functional — she was not cured but she was functional, and that was sufficient for now","Between what guides can help with and what they cannot"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was not cured. She was functional. For the time being, that was sufficient — and the difference between cured and functional was one she had not previously been able to make.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][4].push({
  id:"l5.5s3", levelId:5, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Oral Exam", emoji:"🗣️", genre:"School",
  wordCount:349, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Preparing for her first oral exam in a foreign language, Dana discovers that speaking well in another language requires something more than vocabulary and grammar.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Dana had been learning German for four years and had what her teacher described as 'strong written competence and hesitant oral production.' The translation of this feedback into plain language was: she was good at German when she had time to think and reconstruct, and considerably less fluent when she was required to think and speak simultaneously. The oral examination for her language qualification required her to discuss a prepared topic and then respond to unseen follow-up questions for a total of twelve minutes.",
    "She prepared the first part — the prepared topic — in the way she prepared written work: structured, memorised, and refined. Her topic was the environmental impact of fast fashion, and she could discuss it in German with reasonable fluency because she had spoken it enough times that the language had become partially automatic. The follow-up questions were the problem. They could not be memorised. They required her to actually think in German, in real time, without the scaffolding of a prepared structure.",
    "Her teacher suggested a strategy she found initially uncomfortable: rather than trying to answer questions perfectly, she should practise answering them imperfectly but continuously. The goal was to keep language flowing rather than reaching for exactness and stopping. Her teacher called this 'communicative momentum' — the quality of sustaining meaning even when the precise word was unavailable. 'German speakers make errors,' her teacher said. 'Fluency is not error-free. It is continuous and self-correcting.'",
    "Dana practised with her teacher and with a German conversation partner twice a week for six weeks. The progress was uncomfortable to experience: she made errors she found embarrassing, chose the wrong register on several occasions, and produced sentences that were grammatically inelegant in ways she could hear. But the continuity — the willingness to keep speaking through the uncertainty — gradually became more natural.",
    "In the oral exam, she made several errors and corrected most of them mid-sentence. She kept talking. The examiner, who had examined many candidates that day, wrote in her assessment notes that the candidate had demonstrated genuine communicative competence: the ability to sustain meaning and recover from difficulty in real time. Dana did not see these notes. She only saw the mark, which was higher than she had expected, and which she had earned by being willing to sound wrong on the way to being understood."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "scaffolding":{def:"Here: a structure or support that helps with a task.",pos:"noun"},
    "momentum":{def:"The force that keeps something moving.",pos:"noun"},
    "register":{def:"The style of language appropriate to a situation.",pos:"noun"},
    "inelegant":{def:"Lacking grace or skill.",pos:"adjective"},
    "simultaneously":{def:"At the same time.",pos:"adverb"},
    "competence":{def:"The ability to do something successfully.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was Dana's particular weakness in German?",options:["Her written German was very weak","She struggled to remember vocabulary","She was fluent in writing but hesitant when required to think and speak simultaneously","She could not understand spoken German"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Strong written competence and hesitant oral production' — good at German with time to think, less fluent when thinking and speaking simultaneously."},
    {question:"Why couldn't Dana memorise her way through the follow-up questions?",options:["They were too long to memorise","There were too many possible questions","They were unseen and required real-time thinking in German without a prepared structure","The topic changed without warning"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The follow-up questions could not be memorised. They required her to actually think in German, in real time, without the scaffolding of a prepared structure.'"},
    {question:"What was the teacher's concept of 'communicative momentum'?",options:["Speaking at the right speed","Sustaining meaning even when the precise word was unavailable, by keeping language flowing","Using advanced vocabulary to demonstrate competence","Correcting all errors as they happen"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'Communicative momentum — the quality of sustaining meaning even when the precise word was unavailable.'"},
    {question:"What did the examiner note about Dana's performance?",options:["That she had excellent grammar","That her vocabulary was impressive","That she had demonstrated genuine communicative competence — sustaining meaning and recovering from difficulty in real time","That she had memorised her answers too obviously"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The candidate had demonstrated genuine communicative competence: the ability to sustain meaning and recover from difficulty in real time.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][4].push({
  id:"l5.5s4", levelId:5, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Food Bank Volunteer", emoji:"🥫", genre:"Daily Life",
  wordCount:350, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Volunteering at a food bank for the first time, Oscar is confronted with assumptions he didn't know he had.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Oscar's school required forty hours of community service before the end of Year 11, and he had arranged his allocation at the local food bank primarily because the timing was convenient and it required no specialist skills. He had not thought very carefully about what he would encounter. In the induction session, the coordinator — a woman named Paula who had been running the site for eight years — said something he noted down: 'You may find that your assumptions about who uses a food bank and why are not accurate. That is fine. Just be aware that you have them.'",
    "The first thing Oscar discovered was the demographic range of visitors. He had assembled, without examining it, an image of who came to a food bank. What he found was people who were employed, elderly, in families, single, young, and in occupations he would not have associated with food insecurity. He spoke, during his first shift, with a secondary school teacher who came in for the first time with visible embarrassment, and with a man in his thirties who had been coming for two years and chatted with the volunteers as if visiting a regular social space.",
    "The second thing he discovered was the administrative complexity of the system. The food bank operated a referral structure that required visitors to be sent by a social worker, doctor, or other professional before they could access food. This had originally been designed as a quality control mechanism. Paula explained that it was increasingly criticised because it created a barrier for people who most needed help but were least connected to the services that could refer them. 'The system wasn't designed to be difficult,' she said. 'But design and effect are not the same thing.'",
    "Oscar completed his forty hours and then requested permission to continue volunteering. Paula added him to the rota. He could not have said exactly why he wanted to continue, except that the conversations he had had were among the more genuinely interesting he could remember from that year — not because the circumstances were good, but because the people were complex and the situation was honest. School, he thought, had taught him quite a lot about subjects. The food bank had taught him something harder to name but similarly useful."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "demographic":{def:"Relating to a particular group of people in society.",pos:"adjective"},
    "insecurity":{def:"Uncertainty about having enough of a basic need.",pos:"noun"},
    "referral":{def:"The act of directing someone to a specialist or service.",pos:"noun"},
    "rota":{def:"A list showing when each person is scheduled to do something.",pos:"noun"},
    "allocation":{def:"An amount of something given or set aside for a particular purpose.",pos:"noun"},
    "induction":{def:"An introduction or orientation for a new role.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did Oscar choose to volunteer at the food bank?",options:["He was passionate about food poverty","His friend had recommended it","The timing was convenient and it required no specialist skills","His teacher had specifically suggested it"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had arranged his allocation at the local food bank primarily because the timing was convenient and it required no specialist skills.'"},
    {question:"What assumption about food bank users did Oscar find to be incorrect?",options:["That they would be unfriendly","That they only came once","He had an unexamined image of who came — but found a wide demographic range including employed people, teachers, and others he hadn't expected","That the food bank would be a sad place"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had assembled an image of who came to a food bank. What he found was people who were employed, elderly, in families, single, young, and in occupations he would not have associated with food insecurity.'"},
    {question:"What was the problem with the referral system?",options:["It was too easy to access","It allowed too many people to use the service","It created a barrier for people who most needed help but were least connected to referral services","The paperwork was too difficult for volunteers to manage"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'It was increasingly criticised because it created a barrier for people who most needed help but were least connected to the services that could refer them.'"},
    {question:"Why did Oscar want to continue volunteering after completing his required hours?",options:["He needed more hours for a university application","Paula had asked him to stay","The conversations he had were genuinely interesting — people were complex and the situation was honest","He had become friends with other volunteers"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The conversations he had had were among the more genuinely interesting he could remember — not because the circumstances were good, but because the people were complex and the situation was honest.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][4].push({
  id:"l5.5s5", levelId:5, subLevel:5,
  title:"The Physics of Falling", emoji:"🌌", genre:"Science",
  wordCount:352, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When her physics teacher explains that every object falls at the same rate regardless of mass, Aria finds the counterintuitive truth leads her into a much larger question.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The demonstration was standard: two objects of different mass dropped simultaneously from the same height, reaching the ground at the same time. Aria had encountered this fact before — it was in the textbook — but seeing it demonstrated produced a feeling she associated with genuine surprise, which was different from the feeling of encountering a new piece of information. She knew it intellectually. She did not believe it, quite, until she saw it. The gap between those two states seemed to her worth thinking about.",
    "She stayed behind after the lesson to ask her teacher, Dr. Farouk, to explain the mechanism again. He did so patiently: in the absence of air resistance, all objects experience the same gravitational acceleration regardless of mass, because although a heavier object has greater gravitational force acting on it, it also has greater inertia — resistance to acceleration — and the two effects cancel precisely. 'The maths,' he said, 'works out beautifully.' Aria asked how anyone had first worked this out. He explained Galileo's thought experiment and, later, his famous alleged demonstration from the Tower of Pisa.",
    "This opened a question Aria had not been looking for: how did you know something was true before you could measure it? Galileo had reportedly understood the principle through reasoning before he had the technology to test it with sufficient precision. This suggested that the relationship between theory and experiment was not always the one she had been taught — not always 'observe first, theorise second.' Sometimes it was 'reason first, confirm later,' which was a different epistemological position and one she found more interesting.",
    "She wrote about this for an extended project, framing the question as: what is the relationship between mathematical truth and physical reality? Her physics teacher marked it, but suggested she also show it to the philosophy teacher, which she did. The philosophy teacher said it was a question that had been argued about seriously for centuries and remained genuinely open. Aria found this reassuring rather than discouraging. She had asked a real question. That, she thought, was rarer than getting a good answer."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "inertia":{def:"The resistance of an object to changes in its motion.",pos:"noun"},
    "gravitational acceleration":{def:"The rate at which objects speed up when falling due to gravity.",pos:"noun"},
    "epistemological":{def:"Relating to how we know what we know.",pos:"adjective"},
    "counterintuitive":{def:"Against what you would naturally expect or assume.",pos:"adjective"},
    "mechanism":{def:"The way something works or operates.",pos:"noun"},
    "alleged":{def:"Said to have happened, but not definitely proved.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"Why did the demonstration surprise Aria even though she knew the fact from the textbook?",options:["She thought the textbook was wrong","She had never read that part of the textbook","Knowing something intellectually and genuinely believing it are different — seeing it made it real","The demonstration produced an unexpected result"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She knew it intellectually. She did not believe it, quite, until she saw it. The gap between those two states seemed worth thinking about.'"},
    {question:"Why do objects of different masses fall at the same rate?",options:["Heavier objects fall more slowly due to gravity","Mass has no effect on any physical property","Although heavier objects have more gravitational force, they also have more inertia — the two effects cancel precisely","Air resistance cancels the difference"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A heavier object has greater gravitational force acting on it, but also greater inertia — resistance to acceleration — and the two effects cancel precisely.'"},
    {question:"What alternative model of scientific discovery did Aria identify?",options:["Experiment first, theorise second — always","Technology must precede understanding","Reason first, confirm later — sometimes theory precedes experiment","Random observation leads to theory"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Sometimes it was 'reason first, confirm later,' which was a different epistemological position.'"},
    {question:"Why did Aria find it reassuring that her question remained genuinely open?",options:["It meant she didn't need to answer it","She had asked a real question — and that was rarer than getting a good answer","It meant the philosophy teacher would help her","She preferred open questions to answered ones"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had asked a real question. That was rarer than getting a good answer.'"}
  ]
});


