STORIES[5][5].push({
  id:"l5.6s1", levelId:5, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Open Source Town", emoji:"💻", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:367, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When a small town adopts an open-source software approach to local government, Kemi researches whether transparency alone is enough to create trust.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The town of Vaxholm, in Kemi's research case study, had adopted an unusual approach to local governance. All council meeting minutes, budget decisions, and planning applications were published online in real time, in full, without the redaction or delay that characterised most equivalent processes elsewhere. The council had described this as 'radical transparency' — the idea that if citizens could see everything their government did, trust would naturally follow. Kemi had been assigned the case study for her politics project and began her research expecting to confirm this idea. The evidence was more complicated.",
    "What the council had not fully anticipated was the problem of comprehension. Published information is not the same as understandable information. The budget documents, while publicly available, ran to several hundred pages of specialist financial notation. The planning applications required knowledge of planning law to interpret meaningfully. The meeting minutes were accurate transcriptions of proceedings that assumed familiarity with process, procedure, and prior context. For residents without specialist knowledge — which was most residents — the transparency was formal rather than functional.",
    "The second problem was selective engagement. Those who had engaged most intensely with the published data were a small group of residents with existing political interests, many of whom used the access to contest decisions they had already opposed rather than to form fresh views. Transparency had not created a broader citizenry of informed participants; it had given better tools to an existing engaged minority, which was valuable but different from what had been claimed.",
    "The third finding was more interesting. Several residents whom Kemi interviewed described the transparency as important not because they read the documents, but because they knew they could. The possibility of access — whether or not it was exercised — changed their sense of the relationship with the council. Trust, in this account, was not primarily built by information but by the perceived willingness to share it.",
    "Kemi's conclusion argued that transparency was a necessary but not sufficient condition for institutional trust, and that the council's design had confused availability with accessibility. She recommended, in a short appendix, that the council invest in civic education alongside document publication. Her politics teacher described the report as the best piece of sixth-form research she had read that year. Kemi was pleased, but noted privately that the case study had produced more questions than it answered, which seemed to her like the right outcome for political research."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "redaction":{def:"The removal of sensitive parts of a document before publishing.",pos:"noun"},
    "radical transparency":{def:"The practice of making all information publicly available without restriction.",pos:"noun"},
    "citizenry":{def:"The citizens of a place, considered as a group.",pos:"noun"},
    "accessibility":{def:"The quality of being easily reached, used, or understood.",pos:"noun"},
    "sufficient":{def:"Enough; as much as is needed.",pos:"adjective"},
    "institutional":{def:"Relating to an organisation or established system.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the council's claim about radical transparency?",options:["That it would reduce government costs","That if citizens could see everything, trust would naturally follow","That transparency would attract more residents to participate in meetings","That it would reduce the number of complaints"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The idea that if citizens could see everything their government did, trust would naturally follow.'"},
    {question:"What was the 'comprehension problem' with the transparency?",options:["Documents were in a foreign language","The council did not publish enough documents","Published documents in specialist language were not understandable to most residents — transparency was formal rather than functional","Residents were not interested in reading the documents"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Published information is not the same as understandable information... For most residents, the transparency was formal rather than functional.'"},
    {question:"Who engaged most intensely with the published data?",options:["Young people and students","Newly arrived residents","A small group with existing political interests who used the access to contest decisions they already opposed","Local journalists and academics"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A small group of residents with existing political interests, many of whom used the access to contest decisions they had already opposed.'"},
    {question:"What was the most interesting finding about residents who didn't read the documents?",options:["They trusted the council more than those who read them","They wanted the council to publish less","The knowledge that they could access documents — even if they didn't — changed their sense of the relationship with the council","They were more likely to vote"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Several residents described the transparency as important not because they read the documents, but because they knew they could.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][5].push({
  id:"l5.6s2", levelId:5, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Unspoken Agreement", emoji:"🤫", genre:"Family",
  wordCount:364, readMins:4,
  blurb:"As her parents' marriage becomes increasingly strained, Sofia tries to understand why adults pretend that everything is fine — and whether that pretence is ever useful.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The atmosphere in the house had changed in the way that atmospheres change when adults decide not to discuss something in front of children: it had not disappeared but become structured around its own absence, which was more visible in some ways than the thing itself would have been. Sofia was fifteen and was not under any illusion that she did not notice. She had been noticing since March. It was October.",
    "What she observed was a series of micro-adjustments — the small behavioural negotiations that accompany sustained conflict that is not being named. Her parents were more careful with each other than they had previously been. Conversations were conducted at a lower temperature, which in her parents' case meant that they were saying less than they meant. Their ordinary warmth — the ease of two people who had spent twenty years together and knew each other well — had been replaced by something more effortful and less natural. This was, to Sofia, more difficult to be around than open argument would have been.",
    "She asked her older sister, who was at university, whether she thought their parents were going to separate. Her sister said she did not know. She also said: 'They're trying not to make it your problem, which I think is actually kind, even if it doesn't feel like it.' Sofia had not thought of the pretence in those terms. She had experienced it as a form of dishonesty — the withholding of reality that implied she could not handle it. Her sister's reframing did not fully resolve this, but it added a dimension that Sofia had not included.",
    "She did not ask her parents about it. She was not sure she had the right to, or that she wanted the specific knowledge that would follow. Instead, she focused on what was in front of her: school, her friends, the guitar she had been learning for two years. She found that keeping busy was not the same as not thinking about something, but it reduced the proportion of the day in which the thinking was active.",
    "In December, her parents announced that they were going to couple's counselling. They told her directly, in the kitchen, and asked if she had questions. She had several, but the one she asked was: 'How long have you been doing that?' They said since September. She felt a specific kind of relief she had not expected, which was not relief that things would be fine, but relief that they were doing something — that the pretence had contained something real and the real thing was being addressed."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "micro-adjustments":{def:"Very small changes in behaviour.",pos:"noun"},
    "pretence":{def:"An attempt to make something false appear true.",pos:"noun"},
    "sustained":{def:"Continuing for a long time.",pos:"adjective"},
    "reframing":{def:"Presenting or thinking about something in a different way.",pos:"noun"},
    "withholding":{def:"Refusing to give or share something.",pos:"verb"},
    "counselling":{def:"Professional guidance given to help people with problems.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"How did Sofia first notice that something had changed at home?",options:["Her parents had a loud argument","Her sister told her what was happening","The atmosphere had changed — structured around the absence of what wasn't being discussed","Her parents changed the family routine"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The atmosphere had become structured around its own absence, which was more visible in some ways than the thing itself would have been.'"},
    {question:"Why did Sofia find the careful, lowered-temperature conversations difficult?",options:["She preferred shouting to silence","Her parents were being dishonest about smaller things","Their ordinary ease had been replaced by effortful, less natural behaviour — which was harder to be around than open argument","She was being deliberately excluded from conversations"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Their ordinary warmth had been replaced by something more effortful and less natural. This was more difficult to be around than open argument would have been.'"},
    {question:"How did Sofia's sister reframe the parents' pretence?",options:["She said it was definitely dishonest","She said Sofia should confront them","She said they were trying not to make it Sofia's problem, which was actually kind, even if it didn't feel like it","She said Sofia was overreacting"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'They're trying not to make it your problem, which I think is actually kind, even if it doesn't feel like it.'"},
    {question:"What specific relief did Sofia feel when her parents told her about counselling?",options:["Relief that everything would be fine","Relief that they had been honest from the start","Relief that they were doing something — that the pretence had contained something real being addressed","Relief that she could now talk to them about it"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Relief that was not relief that things would be fine, but relief that they were doing something — that the pretence had contained something real and the real thing was being addressed.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][5].push({
  id:"l5.6s3", levelId:5, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Archive Project", emoji:"📂", genre:"History",
  wordCount:366, readMins:4,
  blurb:"While digitising a local newspaper archive for a history project, Nadia begins to notice what the archive reveals — and what it has systematically left out.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The archive project had been proposed by a local history society that wanted to make a hundred years of the town's newspaper available online. The society had recruited students to assist with the digitisation process — scanning documents, entering metadata, and writing short descriptive entries to accompany each edition. Nadia had joined because her history teacher described it as 'primary source work,' which sounded more interesting than the textbook chapter it would replace.",
    "The work was, for the first two weeks, largely mechanical. She scanned pages, cropped images, entered dates. But she was reading as she scanned, and patterns began to form. The newspaper had, over its hundred-year run, covered the town's commercial life extensively — the opening and closing of businesses, the arrivals and departures of prominent figures, the results of sporting events and local elections. What it had covered far less consistently was the life of the town's non-white and immigrant communities, which had been present since at least the 1920s according to census data she had accessed separately.",
    "When these communities appeared in the archive at all, it was most frequently in specific contexts: immigration restriction debates, incidents associated with social tension, or, from the later decades, cultural celebrations treated as local colour. The ordinary life — the businesses, the families, the civic participation, the professional achievements — that characterised coverage of other communities was substantially absent. The archive was not a complete record. It was the record that someone had chosen to make, and the criteria of that choice were now, a hundred years later, recoverable from the pattern of inclusions and exclusions.",
    "Nadia raised this in a debrief meeting with the history society. The response was varied: some members were interested and invited her to include a methodological note in the project's introduction; others were defensive, arguing that the newspaper had reflected its time and shouldn't be judged by contemporary standards. Both responses, she thought, contained something true.",
    "She wrote the methodological note carefully, framing it not as criticism of the archive but as guidance for anyone using it as a historical source: the archive documented some things well, other things incompletely, and some things not at all, and users should approach it with that awareness. Her history teacher told her the note was the most important contribution to the project. Nadia thought this might be right, and found it slightly uncomfortable, which seemed to her the appropriate feeling."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "digitisation":{def:"Converting physical documents into digital format.",pos:"noun"},
    "metadata":{def:"Data that describes and provides information about other data.",pos:"noun"},
    "census":{def:"An official count of a population with details about people.",pos:"noun"},
    "methodological":{def:"Relating to the system or methods used.",pos:"adjective"},
    "civic":{def:"Relating to a city or town and its citizens.",pos:"adjective"},
    "criteria":{def:"Standards used for judging or deciding something.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What pattern did Nadia notice in the archive after two weeks?",options:["The newspaper had covered sports excessively","The archive was missing decades of editions","The newspaper covered commercial life well but had systematically underrepresented non-white and immigrant communities","The archive was in very poor physical condition"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The newspaper had covered the town's commercial life extensively... What it had covered far less consistently was the life of the town's non-white and immigrant communities.'"},
    {question:"In what contexts did non-white and immigrant communities appear in the archive?",options:["In sports results and cultural events only","Only in advertisements","Mainly in immigration debates, social tension incidents, and later cultural celebrations — not in the ordinary coverage of their lives","In equal proportion to other communities"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'When these communities appeared, it was most frequently in immigration restriction debates, incidents of social tension, or cultural celebrations treated as local colour.'"},
    {question:"What two responses did the history society give to Nadia's observation?",options:["Agreement and immediate action","Silence and defensiveness","Some interest (inviting a methodological note) and some defensiveness (arguing the newspaper reflected its time)","Praise and an offer to expand the project"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Some members were interested and invited a methodological note; others were defensive, arguing the newspaper had reflected its time.'"},
    {question:"What was the key message of Nadia's methodological note?",options:["The archive should be considered unreliable","The newspaper had been deliberately biased","The archive documented some things well and others incompletely — users should approach it with that awareness","The missing communities' stories should be found elsewhere"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The archive documented some things well, other things incompletely, and some things not at all — users should approach it with that awareness.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][5].push({
  id:"l5.6s4", levelId:5, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Goalkeeper's Afternoon", emoji:"🥅", genre:"Sport",
  wordCount:365, readMins:4,
  blurb:"On the afternoon of the most important match of his career, Kofi discovers that the way he deals with waiting is as important as the way he plays.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The match was at seven in the evening. Kofi had been awake since six, had eaten at eight, and had nothing structured to do until the three-thirty team meeting. He was, by temperament, a person who needed occupation — not because he became bored exactly, but because unstructured time, especially before significant events, allowed a particular quality of anxious thinking to establish itself and expand into whatever space was available.",
    "He had tried various approaches in previous pre-match afternoons. Music did not help — he chose badly under pressure, reaching for things that were either too stimulating or too melancholy. Watching highlights of other matches activated the part of him that was always watching for things that went wrong. Reading worked better than most other things, but required a concentration that was difficult to sustain when his attention kept moving towards the evening.",
    "What worked, he had discovered through a process of elimination over two seasons, was manual activity. He spent the afternoon of this particular match reorganising the equipment room at the training ground — a task that required no cognitive engagement but produced visible, tangible results. He sorted boots, re-labelled storage boxes, checked the inventory against a list he found on the wall, and spent forty minutes repairing the binding on a goalkeeper glove that had been sitting unattended in a drawer since October.",
    "His coach, who found him doing this at about two in the afternoon, said nothing and left him to it. She had learned, in five years of working with him, that the pre-match rituals of experienced players were not irrational, even when they appeared to be. The research on pre-performance anxiety supported this: structured physical activity in the hours before a significant event was one of the most consistently effective strategies for managing cognitive arousal to an optimal level.",
    "Kofi played well that evening. He made two saves in the second half that were described in the match report as decisive. After the match, a journalist asked him how he prepared mentally for big games. He paused, because the accurate answer — 'I reorganised a storage room' — was not the kind of answer the journalist was expecting, and Kofi was not sure it was the kind of answer that served any useful purpose. He said something general about focus and preparation. He kept the real answer for himself."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "temperament":{def:"A person's natural way of thinking, behaving, and feeling.",pos:"noun"},
    "tangible":{def:"Real and able to be touched or experienced.",pos:"adjective"},
    "cognitive arousal":{def:"The state of mental alertness and stimulation.",pos:"noun"},
    "melancholy":{def:"A feeling of pensive sadness.",pos:"noun"},
    "inventory":{def:"A complete list of items in a place.",pos:"noun"},
    "ritual":{def:"A repeated action or set of actions that has personal significance.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was Kofi's problem with unstructured time before a match?",options:["He fell asleep and missed warm-ups","He overeat","Unstructured time allowed anxious thinking to expand into whatever space was available","He argued with teammates"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Unstructured time, especially before significant events, allowed a particular quality of anxious thinking to establish itself and expand into whatever space was available.'"},
    {question:"What had Kofi discovered worked best for him before matches?",options:["Listening to music","Watching match highlights","Reading a novel","Manual activity — physical tasks requiring no cognitive engagement but producing tangible results"],correct:3,
     feedback:"'What worked was manual activity... a task that required no cognitive engagement but produced visible, tangible results.'"},
    {question:"Why did the coach say nothing when she found him reorganising the equipment room?",options:["She was busy and hadn't noticed","She disapproved but chose not to interfere","She had learned that the pre-match rituals of experienced players were not irrational","She planned to ask him about it after the match"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She had learned that the pre-match rituals of experienced players were not irrational, even when they appeared to be.'"},
    {question:"Why did Kofi give a general answer to the journalist's question?",options:["He hadn't thought about his preparation","He was tired after the match","The accurate answer ('I reorganised a storage room') was not the kind of answer that served any useful purpose","He was planning to write a book about his method"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The accurate answer — 'I reorganised a storage room' — was not the kind of answer the journalist was expecting, and Kofi was not sure it served any useful purpose.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][5].push({
  id:"l5.6s5", levelId:5, subLevel:6,
  title:"The Island Survey", emoji:"🏝️", genre:"Nature",
  wordCount:366, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When a marine biology team surveys an uninhabited island, volunteer researcher Tala discovers that scientific observation and personal experience are harder to separate than she expected.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The island survey was a ten-day research expedition to a small uninhabited island off the coast, conducted by a marine biology research group. Tala, who was sixteen, had been accepted as a volunteer through a youth science programme. She had expected to be given peripheral tasks — data entry, equipment maintenance, note-taking. Instead, the lead researcher, Dr. Adama, distributed responsibility in a way that assumed competence unless evidence of its absence emerged. Tala was assigned a transect survey of the intertidal zone on the island's northern shore.",
    "A transect survey involved walking a fixed line at low tide and systematically recording every organism observed within a defined width on either side. The method was designed for objectivity: the categories were predetermined, the recording protocol standardised, and the observer's role was to observe accurately and resist interpretation. Tala had read the method description carefully. She found, in practice, that the instruction to 'resist interpretation' was more difficult than it appeared.",
    "The difficulty was not incompetence — she was recording accurately. The difficulty was that the act of seeing something interesting produced, involuntarily, a response that was not scientific. The first time she encountered a large purple sea urchin in the intertidal zone, she stopped moving for a moment, which was technically a methodological error. The creature was exactly in the place it was supposed to be, doing what sea urchins do, but the quality of its presence — the colour, the spines, the improbable vividness of a living thing in a context she had only previously seen in photographs — produced something she later described in her journal as 'the feeling that it mattered that I was the one looking.'",
    "She discussed this with Dr. Adama in the evening debrief. He was not dismissive. He said that the distinction between observation and experience was a recurring methodological and philosophical problem in field biology — that good scientists needed both, and that managing the relationship between them was a skill that took years to develop. 'The urchin mattered,' he said. 'And recording it accurately also mattered. Both are true. The challenge is to be present for both without letting one undermine the other.'",
    "Tala included the urchin encounter in her field journal, in a separate section marked 'observer notes' that Dr. Adama had suggested she maintain alongside the formal data. She found, over the ten days, that this section became increasingly full. She was, she concluded, a better scientist for having a place to put what could not go in the data."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "transect":{def:"A line along which organisms are counted in a scientific survey.",pos:"noun"},
    "intertidal zone":{def:"The area of shoreline exposed at low tide and covered at high tide.",pos:"noun"},
    "protocol":{def:"An official set of rules governing scientific procedures.",pos:"noun"},
    "involuntarily":{def:"Without intention or conscious control.",pos:"adverb"},
    "peripheral":{def:"Of minor importance; on the edge of something.",pos:"adjective"},
    "methodological":{def:"Relating to the system of methods used in research.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was Tala's assigned task on the island survey?",options:["Equipment maintenance and data entry","Photographing marine wildlife","A transect survey of the intertidal zone on the northern shore","Collecting water samples for analysis"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Tala was assigned a transect survey of the intertidal zone on the island's northern shore.'"},
    {question:"What instruction did Tala find harder than expected during the survey?",options:["Recording the names of organisms","Staying on the fixed transect line","The instruction to 'resist interpretation' — she found observation produced involuntary personal responses","Distinguishing between similar-looking species"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The instruction to 'resist interpretation' was more difficult than it appeared.' — seeing interesting things produced involuntary non-scientific responses."},
    {question:"What did Dr. Adama say about the tension between observation and experience?",options:["Observation should always override personal experience","Experience should be kept entirely separate from scientific work","Both mattered — the challenge was to be present for both without letting one undermine the other","Only inexperienced researchers had this problem"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Good scientists needed both, and managing the relationship between them was a skill that took years. 'Be present for both without letting one undermine the other.''"},
    {question:"What did Tala conclude about the separate 'observer notes' section of her journal?",options:["It was too distracting and should have been kept briefer","It had no scientific value","She was a better scientist for having a place to put what could not go in the data","It had made her observations less accurate"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was a better scientist for having a place to put what could not go in the data.'"}
  ]
});


