STORIES[5][6].push({
  id:"l5.7s1", levelId:5, subLevel:7,
  title:"The River and the Map", emoji:"🗺️", genre:"Nature",
  wordCount:388, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When a hydrologist explains why rivers rarely match the maps drawn of them, Petra begins to think about the difference between representation and reality.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The school's geography department had arranged a field visit with a hydrologist from the county water authority, whose name was Dr. Varo and who had been studying the river that ran through the district for eleven years. He met them on the south bank, at a point where the river curved, and his first action was to spread a topographic map on the ground and ask the group what they noticed about the river's shape on the map compared to the river in front of them. Several students immediately saw it: the mapped river was straight at this point. The actual river was not.",
    "'Maps are snapshots,' Dr. Varo said. 'But rivers are not. A river is a process, not an object. It moves laterally, erodes and deposits, migrates across its floodplain over years and decades. The map records what was there when the survey was made. By the time you're reading it, the river has continued.'",
    "This seemed, to Petra, like a specific example of a more general problem: that representations are necessarily static and the things they represent are not. She thought about this more broadly as Dr. Varo continued his explanation — about meanders, about oxbow lakes, about the way floods redistribute sediment and accelerate change in ways that can permanently alter a channel. The river moved because it was a living system, and living systems did not hold still to be mapped.",
    "Dr. Varo also discussed the management implications of this. Flood prevention, he explained, was complicated by the tendency of engineers — particularly in earlier decades — to treat rivers as fixed infrastructure problems to be solved, rather than dynamic systems to be understood. Straightening rivers reduced the friction that slowed water; removing vegetation increased runoff; building on floodplains removed the natural buffers that absorbed high flows. Each individual decision had been locally rational. The cumulative effect, distributed across river systems over decades, had contributed significantly to the increase in flood frequency that many regions were now experiencing.",
    "Petra asked, on the coach home, whether it was possible to undo some of the changes. Her teacher said that river restoration was an active area of research and practice — that there were projects which had deliberately re-meandered straightened rivers, and that early results suggested this could meaningfully reduce flood risk downstream. 'But it takes time,' her teacher said. 'Rivers are slow systems even when they're changing. You have to be patient.' Petra thought about a slow system being asked to accept a fast fix, and decided the patience might need to extend in more than one direction."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "hydrologist":{def:"A scientist who studies water systems.",pos:"noun"},
    "meanders":{def:"Curves or bends in a river.",pos:"noun"},
    "oxbow lake":{def:"A curved lake formed when a meander is cut off from the river.",pos:"noun"},
    "sediment":{def:"Material deposited by water, wind, or ice.",pos:"noun"},
    "floodplain":{def:"The flat land beside a river that floods during high water.",pos:"noun"},
    "cumulative":{def:"Increasing by successive additions.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the first thing Dr. Varo asked the group to notice?",options:["The speed of the current","The depth of the water","That the river's shape on the map was straight, while the actual river was curved","The wildlife on the riverbank"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The mapped river was straight at this point. The actual river was not.'"},
    {question:"What did Dr. Varo mean by 'a river is a process, not an object'?",options:["Rivers are too difficult to understand","Rivers cannot be measured","Rivers move and change continuously — maps record a moment that the river has already left behind","Processes are always better than objects"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A river is a process, not an object. It moves laterally, erodes and deposits, migrates across its floodplain. The map records what was there when the survey was made.'"},
    {question:"How had earlier engineering approaches to rivers contributed to increased flooding?",options:["By building too many bridges","By removing too much water for industrial use","Straightening rivers, removing vegetation, and building on floodplains removed the natural friction and buffers — locally rational decisions with cumulatively damaging effects","By allowing too much sediment to build up"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Straightening rivers reduced friction; removing vegetation increased runoff; building on floodplains removed natural buffers. Each individual decision was locally rational. The cumulative effect contributed to increased flood frequency.'"},
    {question:"What was Petra's final thought about river restoration?",options:["That it was probably not worth attempting","That it needed more funding","That patience was needed in more than one direction — both in the slow systems and in the people waiting for results","That engineers should have listened to hydrologists earlier"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Petra thought about a slow system being asked to accept a fast fix, and decided the patience might need to extend in more than one direction.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][6].push({
  id:"l5.7s2", levelId:5, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Evidence Question", emoji:"⚖️", genre:"School",
  wordCount:386, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When his class studies a controversial historical trial, Marcus finds himself unable to decide whether the verdict was just — and begins to understand why that uncertainty is not a weakness.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The trial Marcus's history class was studying was a real one, from the early twentieth century, in which a man had been convicted of a crime based on circumstantial evidence — evidence that suggested guilt without directly demonstrating it. The man had maintained his innocence. The conviction had been upheld on appeal. The man had died in prison. Twenty years after his death, new evidence had emerged that strongly suggested he had been innocent. No posthumous exoneration had been officially granted.",
    "His teacher presented the case in three phases: the original trial, the appeal, and the later evidence. She then asked the class a question that Marcus had not expected: 'Based on what the jury knew at the time of the original trial, do you think they reached the right verdict?' She was not asking whether the man was guilty. She was asking whether the decision-making process had been sound.",
    "This distinction — between a decision being correct and being well-reasoned — was new to Marcus, and he spent considerable time thinking about it. He had initially framed the question as: was the man guilty? This was the factual question, and it had become somewhat clearer with the later evidence. But his teacher's question was different: given what was available to the jury, was their reasoning process appropriate? The two questions could have different answers. A jury could reason correctly from limited information and still reach a wrong conclusion. A jury could reach a correct conclusion through flawed reasoning.",
    "He wrote an essay that tried to hold both questions separately without collapsing them into each other. He argued that the jury's reasoning had been, at the time, within the norms of the period's evidentiary standards — that given what was available, a reasonable person could have concluded as they did. He also argued that the outcome was unjust, regardless of the procedural validity of the process. His teacher gave him the highest mark in the class and noted: 'Most students conflate the two questions. You kept them distinct. That is exactly the right analytical move in this kind of case.'",
    "Marcus found the feedback satisfying in an unexpected way. He had not been certain about his argument. He had not resolved the case. What he had done was structure the uncertainty carefully — and had been told that this was, in itself, an achievement. He began to revise his understanding of what good thinking looked like. It was not, he decided, the same as arriving at a confident conclusion."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "circumstantial evidence":{def:"Evidence that implies something without proving it directly.",pos:"noun"},
    "posthumous":{def:"Happening after a person's death.",pos:"adjective"},
    "exoneration":{def:"An official declaration that someone is not guilty.",pos:"noun"},
    "evidentiary":{def:"Relating to evidence used in legal proceedings.",pos:"adjective"},
    "conflate":{def:"To treat two different things as if they are the same.",pos:"verb"},
    "procedural":{def:"Relating to the established steps in a process or system.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the specific question Marcus's teacher asked about the trial?",options:["Was the man guilty?","Was the conviction morally right?","Given what the jury knew at the time, was their decision-making process sound?","Should the man have been exonerated posthumously?"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Based on what the jury knew at the time, do you think they reached the right verdict?' — not asking about guilt, but about the reasoning process."},
    {question:"What key distinction did Marcus identify?",options:["The difference between civil and criminal law","The difference between a decision being correct and being well-reasoned","The difference between guilt and innocence","The difference between a verdict and a sentence"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'A jury could reason correctly from limited information and still reach a wrong conclusion. A jury could reach a correct conclusion through flawed reasoning.' — correct and well-reasoned are different things."},
    {question:"What two separate arguments did Marcus make in his essay?",options:["That the man was innocent and that the jury was corrupt","That the jury's reasoning was within period norms, and separately that the outcome was unjust","That the evidence was forged and that the appeal had failed","That the case should be reopened and that the evidence was strong"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The jury's reasoning had been, at the time, within the norms of the period's evidentiary standards. He also argued the outcome was unjust, regardless of procedural validity.'"},
    {question:"What did Marcus conclude about what good thinking looks like?",options:["It always arrives at a confident conclusion","It involves finding the right answer efficiently","It is not the same as arriving at a confident conclusion — structuring uncertainty carefully is itself an achievement","It requires complete agreement with accepted views"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'He had not resolved the case. He had structured the uncertainty carefully — and had been told that this was, in itself, an achievement. Good thinking was not the same as arriving at a confident conclusion.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][6].push({
  id:"l5.7s3", levelId:5, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Sports Scientist", emoji:"🏋️", genre:"Sport",
  wordCount:387, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When her sprinting coach starts applying sports science data to her training, Zara discovers that numbers can describe performance without capturing it.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The club had recently acquired a suite of measurement tools: GPS vests, heart rate monitors, force plates for measuring jump power, and a video analysis system that tracked joint angles through the sprint cycle. The head coach, who had done a postgraduate qualification in sports science and was clearly enthusiastic about the new equipment, introduced a data-led training approach at the start of the new season. Zara, who had been sprinting competitively since she was twelve, found it instructive and, at times, quietly disorienting.",
    "The instructive part was straightforward: she discovered objective information about her performance that she had not previously known. Her ground contact time — the duration of each foot-contact with the track — was slightly longer than optimal for her leg length, which meant she was spending fractionally too long on the ground rather than in the air. Her force plates revealed that her power generation was asymmetric, with her right leg consistently producing more force than her left. These were useful things to know. Training adjustments were made, and over three months, her times improved measurably.",
    "The disorienting part was harder to articulate. She had always experienced sprinting as something felt as much as done — a specific qualitative state that her best runs had and her mediocre ones did not, which she had thought of as 'flow' or 'being on' without having a more technical vocabulary for it. The data captured what had happened, with precision. It could not capture what it had been like when it happened at its best. The number at the end of the run told her how fast she had been. It did not tell her whether it had been one of those runs.",
    "She discussed this with the coach, who was genuinely interested. He said that the gap she was describing was well-documented in the sports science literature — the distinction between performance metrics and what athletes described as 'subjective performance quality' — and that there was active research into what physiological indicators correlated with the qualitative states athletes reported. 'The data can approximate it,' he said. 'It can't replace it. They're measuring different things.'",
    "Zara thought about this for several weeks. She concluded that the data and the felt experience were not in competition — they were two different and both valuable descriptions of the same activity. She began to keep a training journal alongside the data logs, and found that the two records, read together, produced a picture that neither could produce alone."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "asymmetric":{def:"Not the same on both sides.",pos:"adjective"},
    "ground contact time":{def:"The time a sprinter's foot is in contact with the track during each stride.",pos:"noun"},
    "metrics":{def:"Measurements used to assess performance.",pos:"noun"},
    "physiological":{def:"Relating to the functions of living organisms.",pos:"adjective"},
    "qualitative":{def:"Relating to quality rather than quantity or numbers.",pos:"adjective"},
    "articulate":{def:"To express something clearly in words.",pos:"verb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What two specific problems did the sports science data reveal about Zara's running?",options:["She was too slow on straight sections and too fast on bends","Her posture was poor and she had slow reactions","Slightly long ground contact time, and asymmetric force generation between her legs","Her heart rate was too high and her stride too short"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Her ground contact time was slightly longer than optimal... Her force plates revealed asymmetric power generation, with her right leg consistently producing more force than her left.'"},
    {question:"What could the data not capture?",options:["How fast she was running","Her muscle activation patterns","The qualitative experience of her best runs — the 'flow' or 'being on' quality","Her technique errors"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The data captured what had happened, with precision. It could not capture what it had been like when it happened at its best.'"},
    {question:"How did the coach describe the gap between data and subjective experience?",options:["He said the data would eventually capture everything","He said subjective experience was not scientifically valid","He said data can approximate the felt quality but cannot replace it — they measure different things","He said athletes should not trust their subjective feelings"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The data can approximate it. It can't replace it. They're measuring different things.'"},
    {question:"What was Zara's solution to the gap between data and experience?",options:["She stopped looking at the data","She trusted only the data and ignored her feelings","She kept a training journal alongside the data logs — both together produced a picture neither could produce alone","She asked the coach to redesign the measurement system"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She began to keep a training journal alongside the data logs, and found that the two records, read together, produced a picture that neither could produce alone.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][6].push({
  id:"l5.7s4", levelId:5, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Accessible Design", emoji:"♿", genre:"Daily Life",
  wordCount:386, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When her school's student council commissions an accessibility audit, Miriam discovers that design for inclusion often benefits everyone — and asks why it doesn't happen by default.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The accessibility audit had been proposed by a council member whose younger brother used a wheelchair, and who had noticed that several key areas of the school building were effectively unavailable to him when he visited. The council submitted a formal request to the school management. Management agreed, to the council's mild surprise, and contracted an accessibility consultant named Ms. Osei to conduct the assessment.",
    "Ms. Osei's methodology was systematic. She moved through the building with a checklist developed from the relevant accessibility standards and recorded every point of failure: steps without ramp alternatives, doors with handles that required grip strength many people could not provide, signage without braille, visual fire alarms that did not include auditory components for hearing-impaired students, classroom acoustic properties that made speech comprehension significantly more difficult for anyone using a hearing aid. The list, by the end of the morning, was long.",
    "What interested Miriam most — she was shadowing Ms. Osei as part of the project — was not the failures themselves but something the consultant said midway through the assessment. She was noting a heavy fire door that required significant force to open, and she said: 'This is a barrier for wheelchair users. It is also a barrier for anyone carrying something, anyone with reduced grip strength — which includes a significant proportion of the general population — and anyone who has just injured a hand. Designing it out would benefit everyone.' This was, Ms. Osei explained, a principle called universal design: the idea that designing for the most constrained user typically improved the environment for all users.",
    "Miriam had been taught, in a general way, that accessibility was about fairness and inclusion. She had not previously thought about it as also being about better design for everyone. She spent an hour after the audit with Ms. Osei's written report, identifying the changes that would primarily benefit a specific group and those that would benefit most or all users. The intersection was larger than she had expected.",
    "She presented the findings to the student council with a framing she had developed: 'Most of these changes are not accommodations for minority needs. They are corrections to design failures that affect everyone.' The council voted unanimously to request a full implementation plan. Ms. Osei, who had been sent the summary, wrote back to say it was the best student presentation of an accessibility audit she had encountered in twelve years of practice."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "accessibility":{def:"The quality of being usable by people with a range of abilities.",pos:"noun"},
    "audit":{def:"An official inspection or review.",pos:"noun"},
    "universal design":{def:"The design of environments and products usable by all people, without adaptation.",pos:"noun"},
    "constrained":{def:"Limited or restricted.",pos:"adjective"},
    "auditory":{def:"Relating to hearing.",pos:"adjective"},
    "acoustic":{def:"Relating to sound and its transmission.",pos:"adjective"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What prompted the student council to request an accessibility audit?",options:["A legal requirement","A complaint from a parent","A council member noticed that his wheelchair-using brother could not access key areas of the school","The school had recently been inspected"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A council member whose younger brother used a wheelchair had noticed that several key areas of the school were effectively unavailable to him when he visited.'"},
    {question:"What principle did Ms. Osei introduce during the audit?",options:["That accessibility should be the school's first priority","That all buildings should be rebuilt to modern standards","Universal design — designing for the most constrained user typically improves the environment for all users","That accessibility standards were too strict"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Universal design: the idea that designing for the most constrained user typically improved the environment for all users.'"},
    {question:"What example did Ms. Osei use to illustrate universal design?",options:["Wider corridors for wheelchairs","A heavy fire door that was a barrier for wheelchair users, people carrying things, those with reduced grip strength — designing it out would benefit everyone","Braille signage that also helped sighted people","Ramps that were faster than stairs"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'This is a barrier for wheelchair users. It is also a barrier for anyone carrying something, anyone with reduced grip strength... Designing it out would benefit everyone.'"},
    {question:"How did Miriam reframe the accessibility findings for the student council?",options:["As a moral obligation to support disabled students","As expensive but necessary changes","As corrections to design failures that affected everyone, not just accommodations for minority needs","As a way to improve the school's reputation"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Most of these changes are not accommodations for minority needs. They are corrections to design failures that affect everyone.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][6].push({
  id:"l5.7s5", levelId:5, subLevel:7,
  title:"The Quiet Museum", emoji:"🏛️", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:387, readMins:4,
  blurb:"After a school trip to a natural history museum, Rosa finds herself thinking not about what the museum contained but about what it decided to display — and what it means to curate.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The natural history museum was large, well-funded, and comprehensive in the way that institutions of its kind could be when they had been collecting for a hundred and fifty years. The school group moved through the exhibition halls in a loose formation, attending to what the teacher indicated and also to what individually attracted attention. Rosa found herself drawn, less to the specimens and more to the labels — specifically to the dates, the collecting locations, and occasionally the names of the individuals who had originally obtained the specimens.",
    "Several of the large mammals had been collected in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, at a time when specimen collection had involved killing the animal — often in significant numbers, since multiple individuals were collected to ensure good condition examples. The labels recorded this without comment, in the matter-of-fact language of natural science: 'Collected: 1903. Location: Central Africa. Collector: W.H. Marsden.' Rosa found herself wondering about the relationship between the calm authority of the label and the nature of what the label was describing.",
    "She also noticed, in the ethnographic section — a smaller area of the museum that displayed objects from various cultures — that the objects had been acquired in a range of ways that the labels did not detail. Some had been purchased. Some had been gifted. Some were identified in the catalogue notes, which she accessed on the museum's website that evening, as having been removed under colonial authority without the consent of the communities of origin. The museum's website acknowledged this and described an ongoing process of reviewing the collection with communities of origin about appropriate disposition.",
    "What Rosa found most interesting was not the controversy — she had read about repatriation debates before — but the physical experience of standing in front of an object that had one story in its label and a more complicated story in its history. The display case made an argument through what it contained and how it was presented. Curation, she understood, was not neutral. Every museum was an argument about what mattered and how to present it, and the authority of the institution made that argument feel more final than it was.",
    "She wrote about this for an art history assignment, and found that the writing helped her separate what she had seen from what she had felt from what she thought. All three seemed like necessary components of an honest response to the experience, and she was not sure she could have arrived at the third without the first two."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "specimens":{def:"Examples of animals, plants, or minerals collected for study.",pos:"noun"},
    "ethnographic":{def:"Relating to the study of human cultures and societies.",pos:"adjective"},
    "repatriation":{def:"The return of objects or people to their country of origin.",pos:"noun"},
    "disposition":{def:"Here: the decision about what to do with something.",pos:"noun"},
    "colonial":{def:"Relating to the period of colonial rule.",pos:"adjective"},
    "curation":{def:"The selection and organisation of items for display or presentation.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What did Rosa find herself drawn to in the museum, rather than the specimens themselves?",options:["The architecture of the building","The gift shop and educational materials","The labels — particularly dates, locations, and collectors' names","The other students' reactions"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Rosa found herself drawn less to the specimens and more to the labels — specifically to the dates, the collecting locations, and the names of the individuals who had originally obtained them.'"},
    {question:"What did Rosa notice about how the collection labels described the acquisition of large mammals?",options:["They were very detailed about the methods used","They described killing and collecting in matter-of-fact natural science language, without comment","They expressed regret about the methods used","They did not mention how the specimens were acquired"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The labels recorded this without comment, in the matter-of-fact language of natural science.' — the calm authority of the label vs. the nature of what it described."},
    {question:"What had the museum's website acknowledged about some ethnographic objects?",options:["They were all recent acquisitions","They were all purchased legitimately","Some had been removed under colonial authority without consent; the museum was reviewing disposition with communities of origin","They could not be returned due to legal restrictions"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Some objects had been removed under colonial authority without the consent of the communities of origin... The museum was reviewing the collection with communities about appropriate disposition.'"},
    {question:"What key insight did Rosa develop about museum curation?",options:["Museums are always biased against non-Western cultures","Curation is neutral and objective when done professionally","Curation is not neutral — every museum is an argument about what mattered, and institutional authority makes that argument feel more final than it is","Museums should only display objects from their own country"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Curation was not neutral. Every museum was an argument about what mattered and how to present it, and the authority of the institution made that argument feel more final than it was.'"}
  ]
});


