STORIES[5][7].push({
  id:"l5.8s2", levelId:5, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Returning Expedition", emoji:"🌍", genre:"Adventure",
  wordCount:406, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Six months after returning from an eight-week wilderness expedition, Theo writes in his journal about what has — and hasn't — changed.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The expedition had been described, in the programme brochure, as 'a transformative experience.' Theo had held this phrase at arm's length from the beginning — it was the kind of language that made strong claims without specific content — but he had also not known, before going, what the experience would actually be like. Now, six months after his return, he was trying to assess honestly what had changed and what the expedition had actually meant.",
    "The eight weeks had been physically demanding in ways that the preparation had warned him about but that he had not been able to fully anticipate. Cold, sustained effort at altitude, group dynamics under stress, and — the thing he had found most challenging — extended periods of genuine uncertainty, when the route ahead was unclear and the decision about which way to go carried real consequences. He had discovered things about his own responses in that environment that he could not have discovered at home: how he responded to physical discomfort when there was no option to stop; what happened to his judgement when he was tired and cold; which of his contributions to a group under pressure were useful and which were not.",
    "Six months later, much of this knowledge had begun to feel theoretical again. He was back in a context where discomfort had an exit, where difficulty was optional at a certain level, and where the group dynamics of daily life were managed by structures of politeness that the expedition had briefly suspended. He was not sure whether the self he had met in the expedition environment was more real than the self who navigated ordinary life — both seemed genuine — but they were clearly different, and the difference was produced by circumstances rather than by character alone.",
    "He had expected to feel changed in a permanent way. He felt, instead, changed in a conditional way — as if the capacity for the expedition-self was still present, but required particular conditions to activate. This was, on reflection, different from the transformative narrative of the brochure but not necessarily less interesting. Transformation implied a permanent new state. What he had experienced seemed more like the discovery of a capacity that existed within a context.",
    "He wrote about this in his journal and found that the act of writing helped him resist the pressure — which came partly from others' expectations and partly from his own — to describe the experience in a way that was more dramatic than accurate. The expedition had been hard and important and had taught him specific things. That seemed sufficient, and more honest than the word 'transformative.' He put the journal away and began planning, idly, a second trip."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "transformative":{def:"Causing a major and lasting change.",pos:"adjective"},
    "altitude":{def:"Height above sea level.",pos:"noun"},
    "conditional":{def:"Depending on certain conditions.",pos:"adjective"},
    "suspended":{def:"Temporarily stopped or removed.",pos:"verb"},
    "dynamics":{def:"Forces or patterns of behaviour in a group or situation.",pos:"noun"},
    "idly":{def:"Without serious intention or effort; casually.",pos:"adverb"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What had Theo found most challenging during the expedition?",options:["The physical demands at altitude","Working in a group under pressure","Extended periods of genuine uncertainty where decisions carried real consequences","The cold temperatures"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Extended periods of genuine uncertainty, when the route ahead was unclear and the decision about which way to go carried real consequences.'"},
    {question:"What did Theo notice six months after returning?",options:["He had changed permanently and completely","He had forgotten most of what he had learned","Much of the self-knowledge from the expedition had begun to feel theoretical again — back in a context where discomfort had an exit","He wanted to go back immediately"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Six months later, much of this knowledge had begun to feel theoretical again. He was back in a context where discomfort had an exit.'"},
    {question:"How did Theo describe the change the expedition had produced?",options:["Permanent transformation as described in the brochure","No real change had occurred","Conditional change — a capacity for a different self that required particular conditions to activate","A change in values that stayed with him permanently"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Changed in a conditional way — as if the capacity for the expedition-self was still present, but required particular conditions to activate.'"},
    {question:"Why did Theo resist the 'transformative' narrative when writing in his journal?",options:["He thought the expedition had not been worth it","The transformation hadn't happened","He wanted to resist describing the experience more dramatically than accurately — 'hard and important and taught specific things' was more honest","He planned to write something more positive later"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Writing helped him resist the pressure to describe the experience in a way that was more dramatic than accurate. That seemed sufficient, and more honest than the word 'transformative.''"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][7].push({
  id:"l5.8s3", levelId:5, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Cost of Speed", emoji:"🚄", genre:"Culture",
  wordCount:407, readMins:4,
  blurb:"Researching high-speed rail infrastructure for an economics project, Yuen discovers that the full cost of a public project is rarely the number that appears in the headline.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The economics project required an analysis of a major public infrastructure investment: the costs, the claimed benefits, and an assessment of whether the investment represented good value. Yuen chose a high-speed rail project because she found transport infrastructure interesting and because there appeared to be a reasonable quantity of publicly available data. She had not anticipated how complex the question of 'cost' would turn out to be.",
    "The headline capital cost of the project — the figure that appeared in news coverage and parliamentary debates — was the construction and equipment cost. This was substantial, running to tens of billions, and was the number most often cited when the project was described as expensive. But as Yuen worked through the financial documentation, she found a series of additional cost categories that were less consistently included in the public discussion: land acquisition costs, which were subject to ongoing legal disputes and were likely to exceed initial estimates; the costs of interest on borrowed capital over the project's lifetime; the opportunity cost — the value of the alternative things the same money could have funded; and the environmental costs of construction, which had been assessed but whose monetary quantification was acknowledged as highly uncertain.",
    "The claimed benefits were similarly layered. Journey time reductions were the most commonly cited and the most straightforwardly measurable. But the economic models also included 'agglomeration benefits' — the economic gains produced when people and businesses are clustered together in accessible areas — which were based on assumptions about how improved connectivity would change economic geography over several decades. These benefits were large in the models and also highly speculative, depending on economic behaviours that had not yet occurred and might not.",
    "Yuen's conclusion was not that the project was a bad investment. She did not have the technical expertise to make that assessment reliably. Her conclusion was about the structure of the public debate: that the headline cost and the headline benefit were both simplified abstractions from a much more complex reality, and that public decisions of this scale deserved the fuller picture even if it was more difficult to communicate. 'Complexity is not a reason to simplify beyond recognition,' she wrote. 'It is a reason to be more careful about what gets simplified and what does not.'",
    "Her economics teacher gave her the highest grade of the year and suggested she submit the essay to a national student economics competition. Yuen was pleased, but thought the most useful outcome of the project had been the discovery that in economics, as in many fields, the first number you are given is rarely the number that matters most."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "agglomeration":{def:"The process of things coming together in a cluster.",pos:"noun"},
    "opportunity cost":{def:"The value of the next best alternative when a choice is made.",pos:"noun"},
    "capital cost":{def:"The cost of buying or building something, as opposed to running costs.",pos:"noun"},
    "speculative":{def:"Based on guesses rather than firm evidence.",pos:"adjective"},
    "abstraction":{def:"A simplified idea that represents something more complex.",pos:"noun"},
    "quantification":{def:"The measurement of something in numbers.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the headline capital cost of the project, as usually cited?",options:["The total long-term economic benefit","The construction and equipment cost","The full cost including interest and land","The environmental assessment figure"],correct:1,
     feedback:"'The headline capital cost — the figure that appeared in news coverage — was the construction and equipment cost. This was the number most often cited.'"},
    {question:"What additional costs did Yuen find were less consistently included in public discussion?",options:["Salaries for railway staff","Only the land acquisition costs","Land acquisition, interest on borrowed capital, opportunity cost, and environmental costs","International comparisons and travel statistics"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Land acquisition costs; costs of interest on borrowed capital over the project's lifetime; opportunity cost; and environmental costs of construction.'"},
    {question:"Why were the 'agglomeration benefit' claims considered speculative?",options:["They were based on fraudulent data","They were calculated by non-economists","They depended on economic behaviours over several decades that had not yet occurred and might not","They were based on data from a different country"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'These benefits were large in the models and also highly speculative, depending on economic behaviours that had not yet occurred and might not.'"},
    {question:"What was the core conclusion of Yuen's essay?",options:["The project should be cancelled","The headline numbers were accurate enough for public debate","The headline cost and benefit were simplified abstractions — public decisions deserve the fuller picture; complexity is a reason to be more careful about what gets simplified","Economic models are always unreliable"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The headline cost and benefit were simplified abstractions from a much more complex reality... 'Complexity is not a reason to simplify beyond recognition.''"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][7].push({
  id:"l5.8s4", levelId:5, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Painting Class", emoji:"🖌️", genre:"Art",
  wordCount:406, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When her school offers an evening life drawing class to sixth formers, Amara joins reluctantly — and finds herself confronted with a different kind of observation than she expected.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The life drawing class had been set up by the art department as an optional extra, offered on Thursday evenings to sixth-form students who wanted to extend their practice. Amara had agreed mainly to support a friend who was too nervous to go alone and had asked if she would come. She had not drawn seriously since Year 9, when she had stopped art to focus on the sciences. She arrived without strong expectations and found the first session disorienting in a way she had not anticipated.",
    "The disorientation was not what she had expected it to be. She had assumed the primary challenge would be technical — proportion, anatomy, the difficulty of capturing a three-dimensional form in two dimensions. These challenges were present. But the more fundamental difficulty was something the teacher, Ms. Hargreaves, named at the start of the class: the difficulty of actually looking. 'Most people,' she said, 'spend the majority of their time drawing what they think they see rather than what they are actually seeing. The brain substitutes a concept of 'hand' or 'face' for the actual shape in front of you. Your job is to override that substitution.'",
    "This was, Amara found, phenomenologically accurate in a way she had not expected. She kept finding herself drawing symbols rather than forms — the mark for an eye that she had always made, the shorthand curve for a shoulder — rather than attending to the actual angles, the specific relationship of light and shadow, the precise way this particular hand was positioned at this particular moment. The class was teaching her to see, not to draw, and the seeing was harder than the drawing.",
    "She began to connect this to her scientific work in a way that interested her. In biology and chemistry, she was trained to observe carefully, to resist premature interpretation, to record what was there rather than what she expected to find. The principle was identical. The application was in a different medium. She mentioned this connection to Ms. Hargreaves, who was not surprised. 'Drawing and science,' she said, 'both require the same thing: the willingness to look before you conclude.'",
    "Amara attended the class for the rest of the year. By the end, she was not a good draughtsperson, but she had become a better observer — not of drawings, but of everything. She noticed details she had previously filtered out, attended to things she had previously processed at the level of category rather than specifics. She was not certain this made her a better scientist. She was fairly certain it made her a more attentive person, which seemed to her the more important outcome."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "phenomenologically":{def:"In terms of how something is actually experienced by a person.",pos:"adverb"},
    "draughtsperson":{def:"A person skilled in drawing, especially technical or artistic drawing.",pos:"noun"},
    "substitution":{def:"The action of replacing one thing with another.",pos:"noun"},
    "premature":{def:"Happening or done too early; before the right time.",pos:"adjective"},
    "anatomical":{def:"Relating to the structure of living organisms.",pos:"adjective"},
    "proportion":{def:"The relationship between the sizes of different parts.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What did Ms. Hargreaves identify as the fundamental difficulty of life drawing?",options:["Getting the proportions correct","Drawing slowly and carefully enough","Actually looking — the brain substitutes a concept for the real form, and the challenge is to override that substitution","Understanding anatomical structure"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Most people spend the majority of their time drawing what they think they see rather than what they are actually seeing. The brain substitutes a concept for the actual shape. Your job is to override that substitution.'"},
    {question:"What did Amara find herself doing instead of looking?",options:["Copying other students' work","Sketching very quickly","Drawing symbols and shorthand she had always used, rather than attending to the actual specific form in front of her","Focusing only on the outline rather than details"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She kept finding herself drawing symbols rather than forms — the mark for an eye she had always made, the shorthand curve for a shoulder — rather than attending to the actual angles and shapes.'"},
    {question:"What connection did Amara make between drawing and science?",options:["Both require technical precision","Both are better when you work quickly","Both require resisting premature interpretation and recording what is actually there — the principle is identical, just in different mediums","Both improve with practise over many years"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'In biology and chemistry she was trained to observe carefully, resist premature interpretation, record what was there rather than what she expected to find. The principle was identical.'"},
    {question:"What did Amara decide was the most important outcome of the drawing class?",options:["Becoming a skilled draughtsperson","Improving her scientific observation skills","Becoming a more attentive person — noticing details she had previously filtered out","Discovering she enjoyed art after all"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'She was fairly certain it made her a more attentive person, which seemed to her the more important outcome.'"}
  ]
});

STORIES[5][7].push({
  id:"l5.8s5", levelId:5, subLevel:8,
  title:"The Speed of Trust", emoji:"🌳", genre:"Daily Life",
  wordCount:407, readMins:4,
  blurb:"When her town proposes using an algorithm to allocate social housing, Priya researches the proposal and finds that fairness and transparency are not the same thing.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The local council had announced a pilot programme in which an algorithmic system would assist with the allocation of social housing, replacing a process previously managed by housing officers. The stated aims were to reduce waiting times, eliminate unconscious bias in allocation decisions, and create a more transparent and auditable process. The council's communications framed the change as a modernisation that would make the system fairer. Priya, who was researching local governance for her politics extended project, decided to examine this claim.",
    "The first thing she found was that the algorithm's criteria were not public. The council had contracted a private company to develop the system, and the specific weighting of factors — need score, time on waiting list, location preferences, household composition — was described as proprietary information. The council had published the general categories considered but not the precise formula. 'Transparent and auditable' therefore meant that a record was kept of each allocation decision, but not that residents or advocacy groups could examine whether the formula was fair, because they could not see the formula.",
    "The second issue was more subtle. Academic research on algorithmic decision-making in social housing had found that such systems could replicate existing inequalities if the training data or input categories reflected historical patterns of discrimination. A weighting system that prioritised, for example, time spent in stable accommodation as a proxy for housing readiness would disadvantage groups whose historical experience of housing instability was itself a product of discrimination. The algorithm would be fair in the narrow sense of applying the same formula to everyone. It might be systematically unfair in the broader sense of encoding the effects of past injustice.",
    "Priya raised these concerns in her project and also in a formal submission to the council's consultation. The council's response acknowledged the first concern and committed to publishing more detail about the weighting criteria. It addressed the second concern less directly, noting that the system would be reviewed annually. Priya thought the annual review commitment was not nothing — it was better than no review — but it was also not the same as an ongoing accountability mechanism that would catch systematic bias as it emerged rather than retrospectively.",
    "She presented her findings at a sixth-form conference and received the most engaged questions she had experienced in any public presentation. She thought this was because the topic connected two things people were already thinking about separately — algorithmic systems and housing — and the connection made each of them more legible. She filed the research away and noted, in her project conclusion, that the most useful thing a researcher could do was often to create the conditions for a question to be asked that had not been asked before."
  ],
  vocabulary:{
    "proprietary":{def:"Owned by a private company and protected from disclosure.",pos:"adjective"},
    "proxy":{def:"A substitute measure used to represent something harder to measure directly.",pos:"noun"},
    "auditable":{def:"Able to be officially examined and verified.",pos:"adjective"},
    "retrospectively":{def:"Looking back at past events.",pos:"adverb"},
    "advocacy":{def:"Public support for a particular cause.",pos:"noun"},
    "replication":{def:"The reproduction of something, including patterns or problems.",pos:"noun"}
  },
  quiz:[
    {question:"What was the key transparency problem Priya identified with the algorithm?",options:["The algorithm was too slow","The council had not told residents about the change","The algorithm's specific formula was proprietary — residents could not examine whether it was fair","The system had produced many errors already"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The council had contracted a private company and the specific weighting of factors was described as proprietary information. Transparent and auditable meant a record was kept, but not that anyone could examine the formula.'"},
    {question:"How could an algorithm replicate historical inequalities?",options:["By making random errors that disadvantaged certain groups","By being designed by biased engineers","If its weighting criteria used factors that reflected historical discrimination — such as stable accommodation as a proxy — groups disadvantaged by history would be further disadvantaged","By processing applications too slowly"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'A system that prioritised time spent in stable accommodation as a proxy for housing readiness would disadvantage groups whose historical housing instability was itself a product of discrimination.'"},
    {question:"What was Priya's assessment of the annual review commitment?",options:["It was adequate and reassuring","It was unnecessary if the formula was fair","It was better than no review, but not the same as an ongoing accountability mechanism that would catch systematic bias as it emerged","It was too frequent to be useful"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'Not nothing — better than no review — but not the same as an ongoing accountability mechanism that would catch systematic bias as it emerged rather than retrospectively.'"},
    {question:"What did Priya identify as the most useful thing a researcher could do?",options:["Provide clear yes or no policy recommendations","Create visualisations of complex data","Create the conditions for a question to be asked that had not been asked before","Compile comprehensive evidence for existing debates"],correct:2,
     feedback:"'The most useful thing a researcher could do was often to create the conditions for a question to be asked that had not been asked before.'"}
  ]
});


