      { question: "What has the theatre done over its 37 years that the spreadsheets cannot capture?", options: ["Generated significant profit", "Hired famous directors", "Created first experiences of live theatre for thousands and supported emerging playwrights", "Consistently sold out every performance"], correct: 2, feedback: "Eleanor thinks of the elderly regular attendee and the playwrights she commissioned on instinct — human value that numbers cannot represent." },
      { question: "Why does Eleanor tell the company the situation 'without performance'?", options: ["She doesn't want to be emotional in public", "It would be disrespectful to perform to people whose profession is performance", "She doesn't know the full situation yet", "She has always disliked public speaking"], correct: 1, feedback: "She deliberately strips away theatrical delivery as a gesture of honesty — giving performers straight truth rather than a staged version of it." },
      { question: "What distinction does Eleanor make near the end of the story?", options: ["Between good theatre and bad theatre", "Between a theatre that closed and one that was closed down", "Between arts council funding and private funding", "Between professional and community theatre"], correct: 1, feedback: "She sees an important difference between passively shutting and actively fighting until there are no options left — one involves agency, the other does not." }
