// ── LEVEL 6 · SUB-LEVEL 7 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
STORIES[6][6] = [
  {
    id: "l6.7s1", levelId: 6, subLevel: 7,
    title: "The Last Witness", emoji: "👴", genre: "History / Memory",
    wordCount: 488, readMins: 4,
    blurb: "A documentary filmmaker races to record the final testimony of the last living witness to a forgotten massacre.",
    paragraphs: [
      "Jonas Brandt had been making documentary films for twenty years, and he had developed, over that time, a reasonably clear sense of when he was making something necessary and when he was making something interesting. The distinction mattered to him, though he rarely discussed it with funders or broadcasters, who tended to prefer content that was primarily interesting, and who sometimes confused the two categories in ways he found professionally convenient and personally uncomfortable.",
      "The film he was making now was, he believed, necessary. A small town in the mountains had been the site of a massacre in 1944 — fifty-three people, killed over two days by retreating soldiers, in a context that had never been adequately documented. The official record was thin: a few lines in a postwar administrative report, a memorial plaque installed in 1987, a local history book published in a print run of four hundred copies. The town had not forgotten, exactly, but the knowledge had become the kind of knowledge that lives in families rather than histories — passed down privately, diminished with each generation, increasingly inaccessible to the wider record.",
      "The woman he was driving to meet was ninety-one years old. She had been seven at the time of the events. She was, as far as Jonas had been able to establish after six months of research, the last living person who had been present. Her name was Elise, and she had agreed to be filmed on the condition that her granddaughter was present throughout, which Jonas had accepted without hesitation.",
      "What he had not anticipated, arriving at the small house with its view of the same mountains under which the events had taken place, was the quality of her attention. She had expected him to ask about the violence, and he did — carefully, and with pauses she used to think rather than, as he had feared, to protect herself. She described what she had seen with the precision of someone who had carried an image for eight decades without choosing to carry it. But it was what she said afterward, when the formal interview questions were exhausted, that stayed with him.",
      "She said that the worst thing was not what she remembered but what she did not. She knew the names of twenty-three of the fifty-three. The others had been lost not by deliberate erasure but by the ordinary attrition of time — photographs not labelled, relatives not interviewed before they died, archives not consulted before they flooded. 'The forgetting,' she said, 'was not done to us. We did it ourselves, by not being ready in time.'",
      "Jonas filmed for three days. The footage was, he knew, irreplaceable in the literal sense — when Elise died, which she was clear-eyed about being likely to happen within a small number of years, the living connection to these events would be gone. Whatever he recorded now was not a substitute for what had been lost. But it was what remained, and remaining was something."
    ],
    vocabulary: {
      "massacre": { def: "the killing of a large number of people unjustly and cruelly", pos: "noun" },
      "attrition": { def: "gradual reduction through loss or wear", pos: "noun" },
      "testimony": { def: "a formal or personal account of events as a witness", pos: "noun" },
      "irreplaceable": { def: "impossible to replace once lost", pos: "adjective" },
      "erasure": { def: "the complete removal of something", pos: "noun" },
      "administrative": { def: "relating to the running of organisations or records", pos: "adjective" }
    },
    quiz: [
      { question: "What distinction does Jonas make that he rarely shares with funders?", options: ["Between historical and contemporary documentary subjects", "Between films that are necessary and films that are merely interesting", "Between films that will be profitable and those that will not", "Between subjects who are reliable and those who are not"], correct: 1, feedback: "He values the difference between necessity and interest — and worries that broadcasting pressures tend to favour the latter over the former." },
      { question: "Why is this the last opportunity to record Elise's account?", options: ["She has refused to speak publicly until now", "She is the last living witness to the events of 1944", "The town is being demolished and access will be lost", "The archive containing her documents is being sealed"], correct: 1, feedback: "After six months of research, Jonas has established that Elise is the last person still alive who was actually present when the massacre occurred." },
      { question: "What does Elise identify as the 'worst thing' about the events?", options: ["The violence she witnessed directly", "The failure of the postwar justice system", "The forgetting of names due to ordinary neglect over time", "The decision of local officials to minimise the memorial"], correct: 2, feedback: "She doesn't identify the horror of what she saw — she identifies the loss of names through ordinary inattention: unlabelled photos, uninterviewed relatives, unflooded archives consulted too late." },
      { question: "What does Elise mean by 'we did it ourselves, by not being ready in time'?", options: ["The community failed to resist the soldiers", "Forgetting happened through their own inaction, not through deliberate erasure by others", "The families chose not to speak about the events for cultural reasons", "Local historians were not given sufficient funding"], correct: 1, feedback: "She makes a distinction that shocks Jonas: the forgetting wasn't done to them by those who wanted the events erased — it happened through the ordinary failures of ordinary people to preserve what they had." }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "l6.7s2", levelId: 6, subLevel: 7,
    title: "The Displacement", emoji: "🏗️", genre: "Social / Urban",
    wordCount: 486, readMins: 4,
    blurb: "An urban planner implementing a regeneration project begins to question who regeneration is actually for.",
    paragraphs: [
      "The regeneration framework described the area as 'economically underperforming, with low residential desirability scores and significant infrastructure deficit.' Marta had written this language herself, three years earlier, when she was still thinking of the project in terms of the outputs it was designed to produce. Reading it now, sitting with a community survey that described the same area as a place where three generations of the same family often lived within a few streets of one another, where informal economies supported people the formal economy had failed, and where social networks had been built over decades of shared difficulty, she felt the distance between the two descriptions as a kind of vertigo.",
      "She had entered urban planning because she believed in cities — in their capacity to absorb and improve lives, to generate opportunity through density and proximity. She still believed this. What she had underestimated, in the way that she now thought all planners underestimated it until they were forced not to, was the difference between the city as an economic system and the city as a set of relationships. The relationships did not appear in the infrastructure audit. They did not appear in the viability assessment or the phasing plan. They were, in the terminology of her profession, externalities.",
      "The regeneration project would bring new housing, better transport connections, a new school, and commercial spaces intended to attract businesses that would create local employment. Marta believed all of these things were good. She also knew, from the displacement data she had been examining for the past several months, that seventy percent of current residents would not be in the area in ten years. Not because they had been forcibly removed — the project contained no compulsory purchase orders — but because the cumulative effect of improved desirability was higher rents, which displaced the people who could no longer afford them, which changed the character of the area, which accelerated the process.",
      "She had flagged this in two internal memos and been told, politely, that the authority's responsibility extended to existing residents through the statutory consultation process, and that market dynamics beyond the scope of the project were not within the authority's remit. Both of these things were true. Neither of them felt adequate.",
      "She requested a meeting with the project director and came prepared with a proposal: a community land trust element, which would remove a portion of the new residential development from the market and hold it in perpetuity for affordable tenancy, available first to current residents. The director listened carefully. He said it was an interesting model, that it would require additional legal structure and might affect the viability assessment, and that he would take it to the steering committee.",
      "She did not know what the committee would decide. But she thought that at some point, every planner had to choose whether to be responsible for what the framework measured or for what it missed. She had decided which one she wanted to be."
    ],
    vocabulary: {
      "regeneration": { def: "the renewal or improvement of a run-down area", pos: "noun" },
      "externality": { def: "a side effect not included in an economic analysis", pos: "noun" },
      "viability": { def: "the ability to work successfully or be financially sustainable", pos: "noun" },
      "perpetuity": { def: "for all future time; forever", pos: "noun" },
      "cumulative": { def: "increasing or building up over time", pos: "adjective" },
      "statutory": { def: "required or permitted by law", pos: "adjective" }
    },
    quiz: [
      { question: "What contrast does Marta notice between official planning language and the community survey?", options: ["One uses statistics, the other uses personal stories", "One describes the area as economically underperforming; the other describes it as a place of deep community relationships", "One is accurate and one contains errors", "The official language was written by a different team"], correct: 1, feedback: "Her own planning language calls the area 'underperforming'; the community survey describes generations of connected families and social networks — the same place seen through entirely different lenses." },
      { question: "What does Marta mean by calling community relationships 'externalities'?", options: ["They are caused by external political forces", "They fall outside the measurements and categories of the planning framework", "They are brought in from outside the local area", "They depend on external funding sources"], correct: 1, feedback: "Externalities in economics are effects not captured by the main accounting system — here, relationships and informal networks simply don't appear in audits, viability assessments, or phasing plans." },
      { question: "How does Marta expect 70% of residents to be displaced without compulsory purchase orders?", options: ["They will be offered housing in other boroughs", "Improved desirability will raise rents, which residents can no longer afford", "The new buildings will replace the old residential units", "Construction work will make the area temporarily uninhabitable"], correct: 1, feedback: "No one is being directly removed — but rising rents from increased desirability will price out existing residents, who will leave gradually over a decade." },
      { question: "What is Marta's proposed solution, and what does it involve?", options: ["Cancelling the regeneration project entirely", "A community land trust, removing some housing from the market for permanent affordable tenancy", "Applying compulsory purchase orders to protect current residents", "Reducing the scale of the new commercial development"], correct: 1, feedback: "A community land trust would take some housing permanently out of the market, holding it for affordable rent — first offered to current residents — regardless of how surrounding property values change." }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "l6.7s3", levelId: 6, subLevel: 7,
    title: "The Diagnosis", emoji: "🩺", genre: "Medicine / Identity",
    wordCount: 490, readMins: 4,
    blurb: "A neurologist considers how the language doctors use to deliver diagnoses shapes patients' understanding of their own futures.",
    paragraphs: [
      "Dr. Fatou Diallo had been a neurologist for eighteen years, and she had delivered a great many diagnoses. She had delivered them in small rooms and large ones, with families present and without, after long waits and after unexpectedly short ones. She had learned, over time, that the clinical content of a diagnosis was only one of the things being communicated — and that the way it was delivered had consequences that extended well beyond the conversation itself.",
      "The realisation had been gradual. Early in her career, she had been trained to be clear and accurate above all else. A diagnosis should be stated plainly, the prognosis should be given in the most reliable terms available, and the patient's questions should be answered honestly. This framework was ethically correct, and she had never abandoned it. But she had come to believe that it was insufficient, because it treated the patient as a receiver of information rather than a person constructing a revised understanding of their own life.",
      "What she noticed, across hundreds of consultations, was that the metaphors doctors used in delivering diagnoses had lives beyond the clinic. Patients who had been told their brain was 'misfiring' tended to describe themselves, months later, in similar terms — as unreliable, prone to error, unpredictably broken. Patients who had been told they had a 'slow-burning' condition tended to structure their planning around a different kind of time. Patients who had been told their neurons were 'miscommunicating' often expressed, in follow-up appointments, a sense of internal estrangement — as if the self and the brain were now two separate things.",
      "She was not arguing that metaphor should replace accuracy. She was arguing that the choice of metaphor was itself a clinical decision, with effects that were as real and as important as the choice of medication. A metaphor that pathologised the person — rather than describing a process occurring within a complex biological system — had observable downstream effects on self-perception, compliance with treatment, and psychological resilience.",
      "She began running workshops for junior neurologists, not on communication technique as such — that existed in the curriculum already — but on the phenomenology of diagnosis: what it felt like to receive one, how patients integrated new medical information into existing identity structures, and how the framing of a diagnosis shaped the story a patient told themselves in the years that followed.",
      "The workshops were well attended. She found that junior doctors were often relieved to have a space in which clinical precision and human consequence could be discussed together, as if they were parts of the same thing, which she had come to believe they were."
    ],
    vocabulary: {
      "prognosis": { def: "a forecast of the likely course of a medical condition", pos: "noun" },
      "metaphor": { def: "a word or phrase used to describe something by comparison", pos: "noun" },
      "phenomenology": { def: "the study of conscious experience from a first-person perspective", pos: "noun" },
      "pathologise": { def: "to treat something as a medical disorder", pos: "verb" },
      "estrangement": { def: "a feeling of distance or disconnection", pos: "noun" },
      "compliance": { def: "acting in accordance with a requirement or instruction", pos: "noun" }
    },
    quiz: [
      { question: "What does Dr. Diallo identify as insufficient in her early training?", options: ["The training focused too much on accuracy and not enough on listening", "Treating the patient as a receiver of information rather than someone constructing a new self-understanding", "Junior doctors were not given enough time with patients", "The ethical framework of diagnosis was poorly defined"], correct: 1, feedback: "Being clear and accurate is necessary but not enough — it doesn't account for how patients integrate a diagnosis into their understanding of who they are." },
      { question: "What pattern does Dr. Diallo notice about diagnostic metaphors?", options: ["Patients prefer technical language to metaphor", "Metaphors used by doctors appear in how patients describe themselves months later", "Negative metaphors help patients accept difficult diagnoses", "Patients forget metaphors but remember statistics"], correct: 1, feedback: "The language doctors use to describe a condition becomes the language patients use to describe themselves — 'misfiring,' 'slow-burning,' 'miscommunicating' all shape self-perception over time." },
      { question: "What is the core of Dr. Diallo's argument about metaphor?", options: ["Metaphors should always be avoided in clinical contexts", "The choice of metaphor is itself a clinical decision with real consequences", "Patients should choose their own metaphors for their conditions", "Metaphor is less important than statistical accuracy in prognosis"], correct: 1, feedback: "She is not against metaphor — she argues that choosing a metaphor is as consequential as choosing a medication, and should be treated with the same care." },
      { question: "What do junior doctors find valuable about the workshops Dr. Diallo runs?", options: ["They replace clinical communication training", "They cover topics not available in medical school", "They allow clinical precision and human consequence to be discussed together", "They give access to patient case studies from other hospitals"], correct: 2, feedback: "The workshops create space for something the curriculum often treats as separate: the relationship between technical accuracy and human impact, understood as parts of the same clinical act." }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "l6.7s4", levelId: 6, subLevel: 7,
    title: "The Open Question", emoji: "❓", genre: "Philosophy / Education",
    wordCount: 492, readMins: 4,
    blurb: "A philosophy teacher considers why students find unanswerable questions more uncomfortable than wrong answers.",
    paragraphs: [
      "Ms. Adaora had taught philosophy to students between the ages of sixteen and eighteen for fourteen years, and in that time she had noticed a consistent pattern that she found both frustrating and, eventually, fascinating: her students were significantly more comfortable with a wrong answer they could defend than with a genuine open question they could not resolve.",
      "This was not, she thought, a failure of intelligence. Most of her students were highly capable. It was something more cultural — a learned expectation, reinforced through years of education in which the right answer existed and was the goal, that intellectual engagement meant finding and defending a position. The idea that a question might have no final answer — or, more precisely, that its value might lie not in resolution but in what it revealed about the nature of thinking itself — was, for many of them, initially indistinguishable from a waste of time.",
      "She had developed a practice she called 'sitting with it' — a structured refusal to resolve a question before the class had genuinely examined what made it difficult. When a student offered a confident answer to a question like 'Is it possible to act entirely without self-interest?', she did not simply push back. She asked what would need to be true for their answer to be correct, what would count as evidence against it, and whether they could construct an interpretation of a given historical example that supported the opposite position. The goal was not to undermine their answer but to make visible the assumptions on which it rested.",
      "What she found, over time, was that students who went through this process did not become less confident — they became differently confident. They made more careful distinctions. They were slower to use general terms as if their meaning were obvious. They were better at recognising when a disagreement was factual (in principle resolvable by evidence) and when it was philosophical (resolvable only by examining the values and definitions embedded in the question itself).",
      "She also found, and this was the thing she thought about most, that the capacity to remain with uncertainty had consequences beyond her classroom. Former students contacted her, sometimes years later, to tell her that the practice of examining assumptions had made them better at their jobs: as doctors who could hold competing diagnoses while awaiting test results, as engineers who could model multiple scenarios without prematurely committing to one, as parents who could stay present in situations that had no clear resolution.",
      "She continued to teach in a system that measured most of what students knew through examinations with correct answers. She thought this was mostly fine, and mostly inadequate, and that both things were true simultaneously — which was, she thought, exactly the kind of thought she had been trying to teach them to tolerate."
    ],
    vocabulary: {
      "resolution": { def: "the act of solving or settling something", pos: "noun" },
      "indistinguishable": { def: "unable to be told apart", pos: "adjective" },
      "assumption": { def: "something accepted as true without proof", pos: "noun" },
      "simultaneously": { def: "at the same time", pos: "adverb" },
      "prematurely": { def: "before the appropriate or expected time", pos: "adverb" },
      "embedded": { def: "fixed firmly within something; built into", pos: "adjective" }
    },
    quiz: [
      { question: "What pattern does Ms. Adaora observe in her students?", options: ["They prefer philosophical questions to factual ones", "They are more comfortable with a wrong defensible answer than a genuinely open question", "They work better in groups than individually", "They are reluctant to share opinions publicly"], correct: 1, feedback: "She identifies a cultural conditioning: education has taught students to expect a correct answer, so open questions without resolution feel like a failure rather than a different kind of thinking." },
      { question: "What is the aim of Ms. Adaora's 'sitting with it' practice?", options: ["To teach students to accept that they are wrong", "To reveal the assumptions on which confident answers rest", "To slow down classroom discussion and reduce conflict", "To help students memorise philosophical positions"], correct: 1, feedback: "She doesn't want to undermine answers — she wants to make visible what the answer depends on, so students can examine the structure of their own thinking." },
      { question: "How does engaging with open questions change students, according to the story?", options: ["They become less willing to commit to positions", "They perform better on examinations", "They become differently confident — more careful with distinctions and assumptions", "They lose interest in practical careers"], correct: 2, feedback: "The result isn't lower confidence — it's a different kind: slower, more precise, better at recognising what kind of question they're actually dealing with." },
      { question: "What does Ms. Adaora think about the examination system she works within?", options: ["It should be completely reformed", "It is mostly fine and mostly inadequate — both true simultaneously", "It unfairly disadvantages philosophical thinkers", "It accurately measures what students learn in philosophy classes"], correct: 1, feedback: "She holds a genuinely ambivalent view — the system is mostly fine and mostly inadequate at the same time — which is, she notes, precisely the kind of double-truth she teaches her students to sit with." }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "l6.7s5", levelId: 6, subLevel: 7,
    title: "The Field Season", emoji: "🦅", genre: "Science / Nature",
    wordCount: 491, readMins: 4,
    blurb: "An ornithologist completing her final field season reflects on what forty years of watching the same bird population has taught her.",
    paragraphs: [
      "Dr. Ingrid Sorensen had been monitoring the same population of cliff-nesting seabirds for forty-one years. She had begun as a postgraduate student with a borrowed rain jacket and a notebook that became illegible in wet weather, and she had continued, through various appointments and interrupted funding cycles and one serious injury, as the kind of scientist who is either admirable or eccentric depending on who is doing the evaluating. She was sixty-seven now, and this was to be her last field season.",
      "The scientific value of her longitudinal dataset was, she knew from the way other ecologists spoke about it, considerable. Forty-one years of breeding success, chick survival, adult return rates, and dietary data from the same population, in the same location, using the same methodology, was genuinely rare. The dataset had been used in thirty-seven papers, most of which she had contributed to, several of which she had not. It had contributed to conservation policy for two species, challenged the prevailing model of how climate variability affected breeding success in colonial seabirds, and, in ways she found harder to quantify, changed how she thought about time.",
      "What she had not expected, beginning the study, was how much she would come to know the population as a population — not as a set of individually indistinguishable animals, but as something with a character that shifted over decades. There had been periods of high productivity, when the colony expanded and the cliff face filled with the noise and movement of a thriving community. There had been lean years when the fish moved and the chicks starved and the adults returned in the autumn looking, to her eyes at least, diminished. There had been catastrophic events — a major storm, an oil spill, a disease event — each of which the population had absorbed differently, with a resilience that she found, year after year, unexpected.",
      "She had been asked, in interviews and at conferences and by the journalists who periodically found long-term ecological monitoring a compelling subject, whether it was difficult to watch a population she cared about suffer in bad years. She had always answered carefully, because the honest answer was complicated. Yes, there was distress. But the distress was inseparable from something she could only call fidelity — a commitment to seeing the thing as it actually was, in good years and bad, rather than as she wished it to be. Science required this. So, she thought, did most things worth doing.",
      "On the last day of her last field season, she sat at the cliff edge for longer than usual. The colony was returning for the autumn, the air full of calls and the particular salt smell of seabird colonies. She had counted one hundred and twelve returning adults. Forty-one years ago, she had counted one hundred and eight.",
      "She did not know what to make of this. But she wrote it down."
    ],
    vocabulary: {
      "longitudinal": { def: "relating to a study that follows the same subjects over a long period", pos: "adjective" },
      "colonial": { def: "relating to animals that live in large groups or colonies", pos: "adjective" },
      "ornithologist": { def: "a scientist who studies birds", pos: "noun" },
      "fidelity": { def: "accuracy and faithfulness to the truth; loyalty", pos: "noun" },
      "variability": { def: "the tendency of something to change or vary", pos: "noun" },
      "productivity": { def: "the rate at which output or offspring are produced", pos: "noun" }
    },
    quiz: [
      { question: "Why is Dr. Sorensen's dataset considered scientifically valuable?", options: ["She has studied more species than any other ornithologist", "Four decades of consistent data from the same population using the same methodology is extremely rare", "She has personally discovered three new species", "Her research has been funded continuously by the same institution"], correct: 1, feedback: "Longitudinal consistency — same population, same location, same methods for 41 years — is genuinely rare and makes the dataset useful for detecting long-term trends." },
      { question: "What unexpected thing does Dr. Sorensen come to know about the population?", options: ["Individual birds have longer memories than expected", "The colony has a collective character that shifts over decades", "The colony has never fully recovered from the oil spill", "The birds have adapted their diet in response to climate change"], correct: 1, feedback: "Rather than indistinguishable animals, she comes to know the population as something with character — periods of thriving, lean years, catastrophic events absorbed with varying resilience." },
      { question: "How does Dr. Sorensen describe her answer to whether watching suffering is difficult?", options: ["Simple — it never gets easier over time", "Complicated — distress is inseparable from a commitment to seeing the thing as it is", "Easy — scientific detachment helps her remain neutral", "Irrelevant — a scientist should not develop attachments to their subjects"], correct: 1, feedback: "She distinguishes scientific fidelity — seeing the thing as it is, not as you wish it to be — from detachment. The distress and the commitment are the same thing." },
      { question: "What is the significance of the final comparison between 108 and 112 returning adults?", options: ["It proves the conservation policy was successful", "It shows the population is declining slowly", "It is a small, uncertain, but real data point she records without claiming to interpret it", "It confirms that the oil spill had no long-term effect"], correct: 2, feedback: "She doesn't make a claim — the difference is too small to draw conclusions from alone. She simply notices it and writes it down, which is itself the practice she has embodied for 41 years." }
    ]
  }
];

