  wordCount:298, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Aiko takes her visiting cousin to Tsukiji Outer Market before school.",
  paragraphs:[
    "Aiko's cousin Hana was visiting from Osaka for the week, and on Thursday morning Aiko took her to Tsukiji before school. They left the house at six-fifteen, while it was still dark, and took the metro two stops to Tsukuji-shijo station. Aiko had been coming here with her mother since she was small, but she had never seen it through someone else's eyes before.",
    "The outer market was already busy. Stalls ran along both sides of the narrow lanes, selling fresh fish, grilled skewers, tamagoyaki — the thick sweet omelette that Tsukiji is known for — and the kind of tuna onigiri that Hana said she could not find in Osaka. A fishmonger called out to them in a friendly way and offered a small sample of tuna sashimi on a wooden stick. Hana looked uncertain. Aiko ate hers without hesitating.",
    "They found a small stand selling fresh oysters and watched the man who ran it open each shell with a short, flat knife. He worked so quickly that his hands were almost a blur. He noticed them watching and explained the technique without being asked, showing them how the knife went in at exactly the right angle. Hana asked if she could try. He laughed and said no, but he seemed pleased to have been asked.",
    "They ate tamagoyaki from paper bags on the walk back to the metro. It was warm and slightly sweet and a little different from what Aiko made at home — the layers were thinner, and there was something she could not identify in the flavour.",
    "They were at school by eight, which was earlier than usual. Hana said she wanted to come back before she went home. Aiko said she would bring her on Saturday, when there was more time."
  ],
