  blurb:"Mei joins an origami class at her local community centre — and learns that folding paper is harder than it looks.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The community centre ran an origami class on Saturday mornings. Mei had walked past the poster for three weeks before she finally went in. The room smelled of paper and tea, and six people were already seated at a long table when she arrived — mostly older than her, except for one boy around her age who did not look up.",
    "The teacher, a woman called Mrs Nakamura, gave Mei a square of pale green paper and told her they were making tsuru — cranes. The traditional belief is that if you fold one thousand cranes, you may be granted a wish. Mrs Nakamura said this without any particular emphasis, as though she were giving directions, not sharing something remarkable.",
    "The first fold was a mountain fold. Mei pressed the crease carefully, the way she would with a letter, and Mrs Nakamura nodded. The second fold was a valley fold, which went the other way. By the fifth fold, Mei was lost. The paper was behaving in a way that felt impossible — it wanted to open back up, and the corners were not meeting the way they were supposed to.",
    "Mrs Nakamura leaned across and made one small adjustment without speaking. Suddenly the form resolved into something that looked almost right. Mei could see the shape of a bird inside the paper, waiting.",
    "She did not finish the crane that day. She took the half-made shape home wrapped in a tissue and put it on her desk. The boy who had not looked up caught her eye as she was leaving and held up three fingers. It took her a moment to understand. He had made three. She had made none. She smiled anyway."
  ],
