  blurb:"Rafael joins his neighbourhood samba school's drumline six weeks before Carnaval — and learns that rhythm is harder than it looks.",
  paragraphs:[
    "The rehearsal took place in the car park behind the community hall every Thursday evening. Rafael had been watching from his bedroom window for three years. When he finally asked if he could join, the director, a small woman called Dona Bete, handed him a tambourine and told him to stand at the back and listen before he tried to play anything.",
    "He had expected the drumline to be loud. It was loud in a way that went past sound and became physical — he could feel it in his chest and in the soles of his feet on the concrete. Thirty-two drums of different sizes, played in patterns that repeated and shifted and locked together in ways he could not follow from the outside. From the inside, he understood it even less, at first.",
    "Dona Bete said rhythm was not something you learned by watching. You learned it by being inside it until it entered your body. She said this to the new members every year, and the experienced players smiled when she said it, which meant it was true.",
    "By the fourth rehearsal, Rafael could hold his part for about four minutes before losing the beat. By the sixth he could hold it for the whole run-through. Dona Bete came over after the session and said nothing — just tapped the tambourine twice, which he understood was approval.",
    "Carnaval was in February. There were still six weeks of rehearsals left. Rafael now got to the car park early to help set up the drums. He was not sure when this had happened, exactly — it had happened gradually, the way most things did."
  ],
