  title:"The Hutong and the House Behind the Wall", emoji:"🧱", genre:"History / Everyday Life",
  wordCount:298, readMins:3,
  blurb:"Tourist guide Bao takes a small group through a Beijing hutong — and explains why the wall you see is never the whole story.",
  paragraphs:[
    "A hutong is a narrow alleyway in Beijing, formed by the walls of traditional courtyard houses called siheyuan. The word itself is Mongolian, from the time of the Yuan Dynasty. Bao had explained this introduction so many times that he could do it in three languages, but he tried to make it sound new each time, because the people listening were hearing it for the first time.",
    "The group followed him into the hutong. The walls on either side were grey brick, high and undecorated. One wall had a red door set into it, lacquered and solid, with iron ring handles. Bao stopped here and said this was the thing visitors most often misunderstood: the walls were not the homes. The walls hid the homes.",
    "He knocked, because he knew the family. A woman opened the door and let them step into the siheyuan — a square courtyard with rooms on all four sides, open to the sky. There were potted plants along the edges, a bicycle, a table with a half-finished game of cards. The courtyard was not large, but it was private, and the contrast with the narrow alley outside was considerable.",
    "Bao told them that Beijing had once had thousands of hutongs. Many had been demolished to make way for modern buildings. Some areas had been preserved. He did not say this with anger — he said it as a person describes a river that has changed course: something happened, the landscape is different, this is what remains.",
    "They thanked the family and stepped back into the alley. The red door closed. From outside, you could not have guessed what was behind it."
  ],
